1Chr14:8 When the Philistines heard that David had become king of Israel, they came to capture him. But David heard about their plan and marched out to meet them in battle.
1Chr14:9 The Philistines had already camped in Rephaim Valley and were raiding the nearby villages.
1Chr14:10 David asked God, "Should I attack the Philistines? Will you help me win?" The Lord told David, "Yes, attack them! I will give you victory."
1Chr14:11 David and his army marched to Baal-Perazim, where they attacked and defeated the Philistines. He said, "I defeated my enemies because God broke through them like a mighty flood." So he named the place "The Lord Broke Through."
1Chr14:12 Then David ordered his troops to burn the idols that the Philistines had left behind.
1Chr14:13 Some time later, the Philistines came back into the hill country and camped in Rephaim Valley.
1Chr14:14 David asked God what he should do, and God answered, "Don't attack them from the front. Circle around behind them where the balsam trees are.
1Chr14:15 Wait there until you hear the treetops making the sound of marching troops. That sound will mean I have marched out ahead of you to fight the Philistine army. So you must then attack quickly!"
1Chr14:16 David obeyed God and he defeated the Philistines. He even chased them all the way from Gibeon to the entrance to Gezer.
1Chr14:17 From then on, David became even more famous, and the Lord made all the nations afraid of him.
1Chr15:1 David had several buildings built in Jerusalem, and he had a tent set up where the sacred chest would be kept.
1Chr15:2 He said, "Only Levites will be allowed to carry the chest, because the Lord has chosen them to do that work and to serve him forever."
1Chr15:3 Next, David invited everyone to come to Jerusalem and watch the sacred chest being carried to the place he had set up for it.
1Chr15:4 He also sent for Aaron's descendants and for the Levites. The Levites that came were:
1Chr15:5 Uriel, the leader of the Kohath clan, and one hundred twenty of his relatives;
1Chr15:6 Asaiah, the leader of the Merari clan, and two hundred twenty of his relatives;
1Chr15:7 Joel, the leader of the Gershon clan, and one hundred thirty of his relatives;
1Chr15:8 Shemaiah, the leader of the Elizaphan clan, and two hundred of his relatives;
1Chr15:9 Eliel, the leader of the Hebron clan, and eighty of his relatives; and
1Chr15:10 Amminadab, the leader of the Uzziel clan, with one hundred twelve of his relatives.
1Chr15:11 David called together these six Levites and the two priests, Zadok and Abiathar.
1Chr15:12 He said to them, "You are the leaders of the clans in the Levi tribe. You and your relatives must first go through the ceremony to make yourselves clean and acceptable to the Lord . Then you may carry the sacred chest that belongs to the Lord God of Israel and bring it to the place I have prepared for it.
1Chr15:13 The first time we tried to bring the chest to Jerusalem, we didn't ask the Lord what he wanted us to do. He was angry at us, because you Levites weren't there to carry the chest."
1Chr15:14 The priests and the Levites made themselves clean. They were now ready to carry the sacred chest
1Chr15:15 on poles that rested on their shoulders, just as the Lord had told Moses to do.
1Chr15:16 David then told the leaders to choose some Levites to sing and play music on small harps, other stringed instruments, and cymbals.
1Chr15:17 The men chosen to play the cymbals were Heman the son of Joel, his relative Asaph the son of Berechiah, and Ethan the son of Kushaiah from the Merari clan. Some of their assistants played the smaller harps: they were Zechariah, Aziel, Shemiramoth, Jehiel, Unni, Eliab, Maaseiah, and Benaiah. Others played the larger harps: they were Mattithiah, Eliphelehu, Mikneiah, Azaziah, and two of the temple guards, Obed-Edom and Jeiel.
1Chr15:18 ...
1Chr15:19 ...
1Chr15:20 ...
1Chr15:21 ...
1Chr15:22 Chenaniah was chosen to be the music director, because he was a skilled musician.
1Chr15:23 Four Levites were then appointed to guard the sacred chest. They were Berechiah, Elkanah, Obed-Edom, and Jehiah. Finally, David chose priests to walk in front of the sacred chest and blow trumpets. They were Shebaniah, Joshaphat, Nethanel, Amasai, Zechariah, Benaiah, and Eliezer.
1Chr15:24 ...
1Chr15:25 David, the leaders of Israel, and the army commanders were very happy as they went to Obed-Edom's house to get the sacred chest.
1Chr15:26 God gave the Levites the strength they needed to carry the chest, and so they sacrificed seven bulls and seven rams.
1Chr15:27 David, the Levites, Chenaniah the music director, and all the musicians were wearing linen robes, and David was also wearing a linen cloth.
1Chr15:28 While the sacred chest was being carried into Jerusalem, everyone was celebrating by shouting and playing music on horns, trumpets, cymbals, harps, and other stringed instruments.
1Chr15:29 Saul's daughter Michal looked out her window and watched the chest being brought into David's City. But when she saw David jumping and dancing in honor of the Lord , she was disgusted.
1Chr16:1 They put the sacred chest inside the tent that David had set up for it, then they offered sacrifices to please the Lord  and sacrifices to ask his blessing.
1Chr16:2 After David had finished, he blessed the people in the name of the Lord
1Chr16:3 and gave every person in the crowd a small loaf of bread, some meat, and a handful of raisins.
1Chr16:4 David appointed some of the Levites to serve at the sacred chest; they were to play music and sing praises to the Lord God of Israel.
1Chr16:5 Asaph was their leader, and Zechariah was his assistant. Jeiel, Shemiramoth, Jehiel, Mattithiah, Eliab, Benaiah, Obed-Edom, and another man named Jeiel were appointed to play small harps and stringed instruments. Asaph himself played the cymbals,
1Chr16:6 and the two priests Benaiah and Jahaziel were to blow trumpets every day in front of the sacred chest.
1Chr16:7 That same day, David instructed Asaph and his relatives for the first time to sing these praises to the Lord :
1Chr16:8 Praise the Lord and pray in his name! Tell everyone what he has done.
1Chr16:9 Sing praises to the Lord ! Tell about his miracles.
1Chr16:10 Celebrate and worship his holy name with all your heart.
1Chr16:11 Trust the Lord and his mighty power. Worship him always.
1Chr16:12 Remember his miracles and all his wonders and his fair decisions.
1Chr16:13 You belong to the family of Israel, his servant; you are his chosen ones, the descendants of Jacob.
1Chr16:14 The Lord is our God, bringing justice everywhere on earth.
1Chr16:15 We must never forget his agreement and his promises, not in thousands of years.
1Chr16:16 God made an eternal promise
1Chr16:17 to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob
1Chr16:18 when he said, "I'll give you the land of Canaan."
1Chr16:19 At the time there were only a few of us, and we were homeless.
1Chr16:20 We wandered from nation to nation, from one country to another.
1Chr16:21 God did not let anyone mistreat our people. Instead he protected us by punishing rulers
1Chr16:22 and telling them, "Don't touch my chosen leaders or harm my prophets!"
1Chr16:23 Everyone on this earth, sing praises to the Lord . Day after day announce, "The Lord has saved us!"
1Chr16:24 Tell every nation on earth, "The Lord is wonderful and does marvelous things!
1Chr16:25 The Lord is great and deserves our greatest praise! He is the only God worthy of our worship.
1Chr16:26 Other nations worship idols, but the Lord created the heavens.
1Chr16:27 Give honor and praise to the Lord , whose power and beauty fill his holy temple."
1Chr16:28 Tell everyone of every nation, "Praise the glorious power of the Lord .
1Chr16:29 He is wonderful! Praise him and bring an offering into his temple. Worship the Lord , majestic and holy.
1Chr16:30 Everyone on earth, now tremble!" The world stands firm, never to be shaken.
1Chr16:31 Tell the heavens and the earth to be glad and celebrate! And announce to the nations, "The Lord is King!"
1Chr16:32 Command the ocean to roar with all of its creatures and the fields to rejoice with all of their crops.
1Chr16:33 Then every tree in the forest will sing joyful songs to the Lord . He is coming to judge all people on earth.
1Chr16:34 Praise the Lord because he is good to us, and his love never fails.
1Chr16:35 Say to him, "Save us, Lord God! Bring us back from among the nations. Let us celebrate and shout in praise of your holy name.
1Chr16:36 Lord God of Israel, you deserve to be praised forever and ever." After David finished, the people shouted, "Amen! Praise the Lord !"
1Chr16:37 David chose Asaph and the Levites in his clan to be in charge of the daily worship at the place where the sacred chest was kept.
1Chr16:38 Obed-Edom and sixty-eight of his relatives were their assistants, and Hosah and Obed-Edom the son of Jeduthun were the guards.
1Chr16:39 David also chose Zadok the priest and his relatives who were priests to serve at the Lord 's sacred tent at Gibeon.
1Chr16:40 They were to offer sacrifices on the altar every morning and evening, just as the Lord had commanded in the Law he gave Israel.
1Chr16:41 Heman and Jeduthun were their assistants, as well as the other men who had been chosen to praise the Lord for his never-ending love.
1Chr16:42 Heman and Jeduthun were also responsible for blowing the trumpets, and for playing the cymbals and other instruments during worship at the tent. The Levites in Jeduthun's clan were the guards at Gibeon.
1Chr16:43 After that, everyone went home, and David went home to his family.
1Chr17:1 Soon after David moved into his new palace, he said to Nathan the prophet, "Look around! I live in a palace made of cedar, but the sacred chest is kept in a tent."
1Chr17:2 Nathan replied, "The Lord is with you - do what you want."
1Chr17:3 That night, the Lord told Nathan
1Chr17:4 to go to David and tell him: David, you are my servant, so listen carefully: You are not the one to build a temple for me.
1Chr17:5 I didn't live in a temple when I brought my people out of Egypt, and I don't live in one now. A tent has always been my home wherever I have gone with them.
1Chr17:6 I chose special leaders and told them to be like shepherds for my people Israel. But did I ever say anything to even one of them about building a cedar temple for me?
1Chr17:7 David, this is what I, the Lord All-Powerful, say to you. I brought you in from the fields where you took care of sheep, and I made you the leader of my people.
1Chr17:8 Wherever you went, I helped you and destroyed your enemies right in front of your eyes. I have made you one of the most famous people in the world.
1Chr17:9 I have given my people Israel a land of their own where they can live in peace. They will no longer have to tremble with fear - evil nations won't bother them, as they did
1Chr17:10 when I let judges rule my people, and I will keep your enemies from attacking you. Now I promise that like you, your descendants will be kings.
1Chr17:11 I'll choose one of your sons to be king when you reach the end of your life and are buried beside your ancestors. I'll make him a strong ruler,
1Chr17:12 and no one will be able to take his kingdom away from him. He will be the one to build a temple for me.
1Chr17:13 I will be like a father to him, and he will be like a son to me. I will never put an end to my agreement with him, as I put an end to my agreement with Saul, who was king before you.
1Chr17:14 I will make sure that your son and his descendants will rule my people and my kingdom forever.
1Chr17:15 Nathan told David exactly what the Lord had said.
1Chr17:16 David went into the tent he had set up for the sacred chest. He sat there and prayed: Lord God, my family and I don't deserve what you have already done for us,
1Chr17:17 and yet you have promised to do even more for my descendants. You are treating me as if I am a very important person.
1Chr17:18 I am your servant, and you know my thoughts. What else can I say, except that you have honored me?
1Chr17:19 It was your choice to do these wonderful things for me and to make these promises.
1Chr17:20 No other god is like you, Lord  - you alone are God. Everything we have heard about you is true.
1Chr17:21 And there is no other nation on earth like Israel, the nation you rescued from slavery in Egypt to be your own. You became famous by using great and wonderful miracles to force other nations and their gods out of your land, so that your people could live here.
1Chr17:22 You have chosen Israel to be your people forever, and you have become their God.
1Chr17:23 Lord God, please do what you promised me and my descendants.
1Chr17:24 Then you will be famous forever, and everyone will say, "The Lord All-Powerful rules Israel and is their God." My kingdom will be strong,
1Chr17:25 because you are my God, and you have promised that my descendants will be kings. That's why I have the courage to pray to you like this, even though I am only your servant.
1Chr17:26 You are the Lord God, and you have made this good promise to me.
1Chr17:27 Now please bless my descendants forever, and let them always be your chosen kings. You have already blessed my family, and I know you will bless us forever.
1Chr18:1 Later, David attacked and defeated the Philistines. He captured their town of Gath and the nearby villages.
1Chr18:2 David also defeated the Moabites, and so they had to accept him as their ruler and pay taxes to him.
1Chr18:3 While King Hadadezer of Zobah was trying to gain control of the territory near the Euphrates River, David met him in battle at Hamath and defeated him.
1Chr18:4 David captured one thousand chariots, seven thousand chariot drivers, and twenty thousand soldiers. And he crippled all but one hundred of the horses.
1Chr18:5 When troops from the Syrian kingdom of Damascus came to help Hadadezer, David killed twenty-two thousand of them.
1Chr18:6 Then David stationed some of his troops in Damascus, and the people there had to accept David as their ruler and pay taxes to him. Everywhere David went, the Lord helped him win battles.
1Chr18:7 Hadadezer's officers had carried gold shields, but David took these shields and brought them back to Jerusalem.
1Chr18:8 He also took a lot of bronze from the cities of Tibhath and Cun, which had belonged to Hadadezer. Later, Solomon used this bronze to make the large bowl called the Sea, and to make the pillars and other furnishings for the temple.
1Chr18:9 King Tou of Hamath and King Hadadezer had been enemies. So when Tou heard that David had defeated Hadadezer's whole army, he sent his son Hadoram to congratulate David on his victory. Hadoram also brought him gifts made of gold, silver, and bronze.
1Chr18:10 ...
1Chr18:11 David gave these gifts to the Lord , just as he had done with the silver and gold he had captured from Edom, Moab, Ammon, Philistia, and Amalek.
1Chr18:12 Abishai the son of Zeruiah defeated the Edomite army in Salt Valley and killed eighteen thousand of their troops.
1Chr18:13 Then he stationed troops in Edom, and the people there had to accept David as their ruler. Everywhere David went, the Lord gave him victory in war.
1Chr18:14 David ruled all Israel with fairness and justice.
1Chr18:15 Joab the son of Zeruiah was the commander in chief of the army. Jehoshaphat the son of Ahilud kept the government records.
1Chr18:16 Zadok the son of Ahitub and Ahimelech the son of Abiathar were the priests. Shavsha was the secretary.
1Chr18:17 Benaiah the son of Jehoiada was the commander of David's bodyguard. David's sons were his highest-ranking officials.
1Chr19:1 Some time later, King Nahash of Ammon died, and his son Hanun became king.
1Chr19:2 David said, "Nahash was kind to me, so I will be kind to his son." He sent some officials to Ammon to tell Hanun how sorry he was that his father had died. But when David's officials arrived at Ammon,
1Chr19:3 the Ammonite leaders said to Hanun, "Do you really believe King David is honoring your father by sending these men to comfort you? He probably sent them to spy on our country, so he can come and destroy it."
1Chr19:4 Hanun arrested David's officials and had their beards shaved off and their robes cut off just below the waist, and then he sent them away.
1Chr19:5 They were terribly ashamed. When David found out what had happened to his officials, he sent a message that told them, "Stay in Jericho until your beards grow back. Then you can come home."
1Chr19:6 The Ammonites realized they had made David furious. So they paid over thirty tons of silver to hire chariot troops from Mesopotamia and from the Syrian kingdoms of Maacah and Zobah.
1Chr19:7 Thirty-two thousand troops, as well as the king of Maacah and his army, came and camped near Medeba. The Ammonite troops also left their towns and came to prepare for battle.
1Chr19:8 David heard what was happening, and he sent out Joab with his army.
1Chr19:9 The Ammonite troops marched to the entrance of the city and prepared for battle, while the Syrian troops took their positions in the open fields.
1Chr19:10 Joab saw that the enemy troops were lined up on both sides of him. So he picked some of the best Israelite soldiers to fight the Syrians.
1Chr19:11 Then he put his brother Abishai in command of the rest of the army and told them to fight against the Ammonites.
1Chr19:12 Joab told his brother, "If the Syrians are too much for me to handle, come and help me. And if the Ammonites are too strong for you, I'll come and help you.
1Chr19:13 Be brave and fight hard to protect our people and the towns of our Lord God. I pray he will do whatever pleases him."
1Chr19:14 Joab and his soldiers attacked the Syrians, and the Syrians ran from them.
1Chr19:15 When the Ammonite troops saw that the Syrians had run away, they ran from Abishai's soldiers and went back into their own city. Joab then returned to Jerusalem.
1Chr19:16 As soon as the Syrians realized they had been defeated, they sent for their troops that were stationed on the other side of the Euphrates River. Shophach, the commander of Hadadezer's army, led these troops to Ammon.
1Chr19:17 David found out what the Syrians were doing, and he brought Israel's entire army together. They crossed the Jordan River, and he commanded them to take their positions facing the Syrian troops. Soon after the fighting began,
1Chr19:18 the Syrians ran from Israel. David killed seven thousand chariot troops and forty thousand regular soldiers. He also killed Shophach, their commander.
1Chr19:19 When the kings who had been under Hadadezer's rule saw that Israel had defeated them, they made peace with David and accepted him as their new ruler. The Syrians never helped the Ammonites again.
1Chr20:1 The next spring, the time when kings go to war, Joab marched out in command of the Israelite army and destroyed towns all over the country of Ammon. He attacked the capital city of Rabbah and left it in ruins. But David stayed in Jerusalem.
1Chr20:2 Later, David himself went to Rabbah, where he took the crown from the statue of their god Milcom. The crown was made of seventy-five pounds of gold, and there was a valuable jewel on it. David put the jewel on his crown, then carried off everything else of value.
1Chr20:3 He forced the people of Rabbah to work with saws, iron picks, and axes. He also did the same thing with the people in all the other Ammonite towns. David then led Israel's army back to Jerusalem.
1Chr20:4 Some time later, Israel fought a battle against the Philistines at Gezer. During this battle, Sibbecai from Hushah killed Sippai, a descendant of the Rephaim, and the Philistines were defeated.
1Chr20:5 In another battle against the Philistines, Elhanan the son of Jair killed Lahmi the brother of Goliath from Gath, whose spear shaft was like a weaver's beam.
1Chr20:6 Another one of the Philistine soldiers who was a descendant of the Rephaim was as big as a giant and had six fingers on each hand and six toes on each foot. During a battle at Gath,
1Chr20:7 he made fun of Israel, so David's nephew Jonathan killed him.
1Chr20:8 David and his soldiers killed these three men from Gath who were descendants of the Rephaim.
1Chr21:1 Satan decided to cause trouble for Israel by making David think it was a good idea to find out how many people there were in Israel and Judah.
1Chr21:2 David told Joab and the army commanders, "Count everyone in Israel, from the town of Beersheba in the south all the way north to Dan. Then I will know how many people can serve in my army."
1Chr21:3 Joab answered, "Your Majesty, even if the Lord made your kingdom a hundred times larger, you would still rule everyone in it. Why do you need to know how many soldiers there are? Don't you think that would make the whole nation angry?"
1Chr21:4 But David would not change his mind. And so Joab went everywhere in Israel and Judah and counted the people. He returned to Jerusalem
1Chr21:5 and told David that the total number of men who could serve in the army was one million one hundred thousand in Israel and four hundred seventy thousand in Judah.
1Chr21:6 Joab refused to include anyone from the tribes of Levi and Benjamin, because he still disagreed with David's orders.
1Chr21:7 David's order to count the people made God angry, and he punished Israel.
1Chr21:8 David prayed, "I am your servant. But what I did was stupid and terribly wrong. Please forgive me."
1Chr21:9 The Lord said to Gad, one of David's prophets,
1Chr21:10 "Tell David that I will punish him in one of three ways. But he will have to choose which one it will be."
1Chr21:11 Gad went to David and told him: You must choose how the Lord will punish you:
1Chr21:12 Will there be three years when the land won't grow enough food for its people? Or will your enemies constantly defeat you for three months? Or will the Lord send a horrible disease to strike your land for three days? Think about it and decide, because I have to give your answer to God who sent me.
1Chr21:13 David was miserable and said, "It's a terrible choice to make! But the Lord is kind, and I'd rather have him punish me than for anyone else to do it."
1Chr21:14 So the Lord sent a horrible disease on Israel, and seventy thousand Israelites died.
1Chr21:15 Then he sent an angel to destroy the city of Jerusalem. But just as the angel was about to do that, the Lord felt sorry for all the suffering he had caused the people, and he told the angel, "Stop! They have suffered enough." This happened at the threshing place that belonged to Araunah the Jebusite.
1Chr21:16 David saw the Lord 's angel in the air, holding a sword over Jerusalem. He and the leaders of Israel, who were all wearing sackcloth, bowed with their faces to the ground,
1Chr21:17 and David prayed, "It's my fault! I sinned by ordering the people to be counted. They have done nothing wrong - they are innocent sheep. Lord God, please punish me and my family. Don't let the disease wipe out your people."
1Chr21:18 The Lord 's angel told the prophet Gad to tell David that he must go to Araunah's threshing place and build an altar in honor of the Lord .
1Chr21:19 David followed the Lord 's instructions.
1Chr21:20 Araunah and his four sons were threshing wheat at the time, and when they saw the angel, the four sons ran to hide.
1Chr21:21 Just then, David arrived, and when Araunah saw him, he stopped his work and bowed down.
1Chr21:22 David said, "Would you sell me your threshing place, so I can build an altar on it to the Lord ? Then this disease will stop killing the people. I'm willing to pay whatever you say it's worth."
1Chr21:23 Araunah answered, "Take it, Your Majesty, and do whatever you want with it. I'll even give you the oxen for the sacrifice and the wheat for the grain sacrifice. And you can use the threshing-boards for the fire. It's all yours!"
1Chr21:24 But David replied, "No! I want to pay you what they're worth. I can't just take something from you and then offer the Lord a sacrifice that cost me nothing."
1Chr21:25 So David paid Araunah six hundred gold coins for his threshing place.
1Chr21:26 David built an altar and offered sacrifices to please the Lord  and sacrifices to ask his blessing. David prayed, and the Lord answered him by sending fire down on the altar.
1Chr21:27 Then the Lord commanded the angel to put the sword away.
1Chr21:28 When David saw that the Lord had answered his prayer, he offered more sacrifices there at the threshing place,
1Chr21:29 because he was afraid of the angel's sword and did not want to go all the way to Gibeon. That's where the sacred tent that Moses had made in the desert was kept, as well as the altar where sacrifices were offered to the Lord .
1Chr21:30 ...
1Chr22:1 David said, "The temple of the Lord God must be built right here at this threshing place. And the altar for offering sacrifices will also be here."
1Chr22:2 David ordered the foreigners living in Israel to come to Jerusalem. Then he assigned some to cut blocks of stone for building the temple.
1Chr22:3 He got a large supply of iron to make into nails and hinges for the doors, and he provided so much bronze that it could not be weighed.
1Chr22:4 He also had cedar logs brought in from the cities of Sidon and Tyre.
1Chr22:5 He said, "The temple for the Lord must be great, so that everyone in the world will know about it. But since my son Solomon is young and has no experience, I will make sure that everything is ready for the temple to be built." That's why David did all these things before he died.
1Chr22:6 David sent for his son Solomon and told him to build a temple for the Lord God of Israel.
1Chr22:7 He said: My son, I wanted to build a temple where the Lord my God would be worshiped.
1Chr22:8 But some time ago, he told me, "David, you have killed too many people and have fought too many battles. That's why you are not the one to build my temple.
1Chr22:9 But when your son becomes king, I will give him peace throughout his kingdom. His name will be Solomon, because during his rule I will keep Israel safe and peaceful.
1Chr22:10 Solomon will build my temple. He will be like a son to me, and I will be like a father to him. In fact, one of his descendants will always rule in Israel."
1Chr22:11 Solomon, my son, I now pray that the Lord your God will be with you and keep his promise to help you build a temple for him.
1Chr22:12 May he give you wisdom and knowledge, so that you can rule Israel according to his Law.
1Chr22:13 If you obey the laws and teachings that the Lord gave Moses, you will be successful. Be strong and brave and don't get discouraged or be afraid of anything.
1Chr22:14 I have all the supplies you'll need to build the temple: You have four thousand tons of gold and forty thousand tons of silver. There's also plenty of wood, stone, and more bronze and iron than I could weigh. Ask for anything else you need.
1Chr22:15 I have also assigned men who will cut and lay the stone. And there are carpenters and people who are experts in working with
1Chr22:16 gold, silver, bronze, and iron. You have plenty of workers to do the job. Now get started, and I pray that the Lord will be with you in your work.
1Chr22:17 David then gave orders for the leaders of Israel to help Solomon.
1Chr22:18 David said: The Lord our God has helped me defeat all the people who lived here before us, and he has given you peace from all your enemies. Now this land belongs to the Lord and his people.
1Chr22:19 Obey the Lord your God with your heart and soul. Begin work on the temple to honor him, so that the sacred chest and the things used for worship can be kept there.
1Chr23:1 David was old when he chose his son Solomon to be king of Israel.
1Chr23:2 Some time later, David called together all of Israel's leaders, priests, and Levites.
1Chr23:3 He then counted the Levite men who were at least thirty years old, and the total was thirty-eight thousand.
1Chr23:4 He said, "Twenty-four thousand of the Levites will be in charge of the temple, six thousand will be temple officials and judges,
1Chr23:5 four thousand will be guards at the temple, and four thousand will praise the Lord by playing the musical instruments I have given them."
1Chr23:6 David then divided the Levites into three groups according to the clans of Levi's sons, Gershon, Kohath, and Merari.
1Chr23:7 Gershon had two sons: Ladan and Shimei.
1Chr23:8 Ladan was the father of Jehiel, Zetham, and Joel.
1Chr23:9 They were all family leaders among their father's descendants. Shimei was the father of Shelomoth, Haziel, and Haran.
1Chr23:10 Later, Shimei had four more sons, in the following order: Jahath, Zina, Jeush, and Beriah. But Jeush and Beriah didn't have many children, so their descendants were counted as one family.
1Chr23:11 ...
1Chr23:12 Kohath had four sons: Amram, Izhar, Hebron, and Uzziel.
1Chr23:13 Amram was the father of Aaron and Moses. Aaron and his descendants were chosen to be in charge of all the sacred things. They served the Lord by offering sacrifices to him and by blessing the people in his name.
1Chr23:14 Moses, the man of God, was the father of Gershom and Eliezer, and their descendants were considered Levites.
1Chr23:15 ...
1Chr23:16 Gershom's oldest son was Shebuel.
1Chr23:17 Rehabiah, who was Eliezer's only son, had many children.
1Chr23:18 The second son born to Kohath was Izhar, and his oldest son was Shelomith.
1Chr23:19 Hebron, the third son of Kohath, was the father of Jeriah, Amariah, Jahaziel, and Jekameam.
1Chr23:20 Kohath's youngest son, Uzziel, was the father of Micah and Isshiah.
1Chr23:21 Merari had two sons: Mahli and Mushi. Mahli was the father of Eleazar and Kish.
1Chr23:22 Eleazar had no sons, only daughters, and they married their uncle's sons.
1Chr23:23 Mushi the second son of Merari, was the father of Mahli, Eder, and Jeremoth.
1Chr23:24 These were the clans and families of the tribe of Levi. Those who were twenty years and older were assigned to work at the Lord 's temple.
1Chr23:25 David said: The Lord God of Israel has given his people peace, and he will live in Jerusalem forever.
1Chr23:26 And so, the Levites won't need to move the sacred tent and the things used for worship from place to place.
1Chr23:27 From now on, all Levites at least twenty years old
1Chr23:28 will serve the Lord by helping Aaron's descendants do their work at the temple, by keeping the courtyards and rooms of the temple clean, and by making sure that everything used in worship stays pure.
1Chr23:29 They will also be in charge of the sacred loaves of bread, the flour for the grain sacrifices, the thin wafers, any offerings to be baked, and the flour mixed with olive oil. These Levites will weigh and measure these offerings.
1Chr23:30 Every morning and evening, the Levites are to give thanks to the Lord and sing praises to him.
1Chr23:31 They must also give thanks and sing praises when sacrifices are offered on each Sabbath, as well as during New Moon Festivals and other religious feasts. There must always be enough Levites on duty at the temple to do everything that needs to be done.
1Chr23:32 They were once in charge of taking care of the sacred tent; now they are responsible for the temple and for helping Aaron's descendants.
1Chr24:1 Aaron's descendants were then divided into work groups. Aaron had four sons: Nadab, Abihu, Eleazar, and Ithamar.
1Chr24:2 But Nadab and Abihu died long before their father, without having any sons. That's why Eleazar and Ithamar served as priests.
1Chr24:3 David divided Aaron's descendants into groups, according to their assigned work. Zadok, one of Eleazar's descendants, and Ahimelech, one of Ithamar's descendants, helped David.
1Chr24:4 Eleazar's descendants were divided into sixteen groups, and Ithamar's were divided into eight groups, because Eleazar's family included more family leaders.
1Chr24:5 However, both families included temple officials and priests, and so to make sure the work was divided fairly, David asked God what to do.
1Chr24:6 As each group was assigned their duties, Shemaiah the son of Nethanel the Levite wrote down the name of the family leader in charge of that group. The witnesses were David and his officials, as well as Zadok the priest, Ahimelech the son of Abiathar, and the family leaders from the clans of the priests and the Levites.
1Chr24:7 Each group of priests went by the name of its family leader, and they were assigned their duties in the following order: Jehoiarib, Jedaiah, Harim, Seorim, Malchijah, Mijamin, Hakkoz, Abijah, Jeshua, Shecaniah, Eliashib, Jakim, Huppah, Jeshebeab, Bilgah, Immer, Hezir, Happizzez, Pethahiah, Jehezkel, Jachin, Gamul, Delaiah, Maaziah.
