Psa61:8 I will sing your praises forever and will always keep my promises.
Psa62:1 Only God can save me, and I calmly wait for him.
Psa62:2 God alone is the mighty rock that keeps me safe and the fortress where I am secure.
Psa62:3 I feel like a shaky fence or a sagging wall. How long will all of you attack and assault me?
Psa62:4 You want to bring me down from my place of honor. You love to tell lies, and when your words are kind, hatred hides in your heart.
Psa62:5 Only God gives inward peace, and I depend on him.
Psa62:6 God alone is the mighty rock that keeps me safe, and he is the fortress where I feel secure.
Psa62:7 God saves me and honors me. He is that mighty rock where I find safety.
Psa62:8 Trust God, my friends, and always tell him each one of your concerns. God is our place of safety.
Psa62:9 We humans are only a breath; none of us are truly great. All of us together weigh less than a puff of air.
Psa62:10 Don't trust in violence or depend on dishonesty or rely on great wealth.
Psa62:11 I heard God say two things: "I am powerful,
Psa62:12 and I am very kind." The Lord rewards each of us according to what we do.
Psa63:1 You are my God. I worship you. In my heart, I long for you, as I would long for a stream in a scorching desert.
Psa63:2 I have seen your power and your glory in the place of worship.
Psa63:3 Your love means more than life to me, and I praise you.
Psa63:4 As long as I live, I will pray to you.
Psa63:5 I will sing joyful praises and be filled with excitement like a guest at a banquet.
Psa63:6 I think about you before I go to sleep, and my thoughts turn to you during the night.
Psa63:7 You have helped me, and I sing happy songs in the shadow of your wings.
Psa63:8 I stay close to you, and your powerful arm supports me.
Psa63:9 All who want to kill me will end up in the ground.
Psa63:10 Swords will run them through, and wild dogs will eat them.
Psa63:11 Because of you, our God, the king will celebrate with your faithful followers, but liars will be silent.
Psa64:1 Listen to my concerns, God, and protect me from my terrible enemies.
Psa64:2 Keep me safe from secret plots of corrupt and evil gangs.
Psa64:3 Their words cut like swords, and their cruel remarks sting like sharp arrows.
Psa64:4 They fearlessly ambush and shoot innocent people.
Psa64:5 They are determined to do evil, and they tell themselves, "Let's set traps! No one can see us."
Psa64:6 They make evil plans and say, "We'll commit a perfect crime. No one knows our thoughts."
Psa64:7 But God will shoot his arrows and quickly wound them.
Psa64:8 They will be destroyed by their own words, and everyone who sees them will tremble with fear.
Psa64:9 They will be afraid and say, "Look at what God has done and keep it all in mind."
Psa64:10 May the Lord bless his people with peace and happiness and let them celebrate.
Psa65:1 Our God, you deserve praise in Zion, where we keep our promises to you.
Psa65:2 Everyone will come to you because you answer prayer.
Psa65:3 Our terrible sins get us down, but you forgive us.
Psa65:4 You bless your chosen ones, and you invite them to live near you in your temple. We will enjoy your house, the sacred temple.
Psa65:5 Our God, you save us, and your fearsome deeds answer our prayers for justice! You give hope to people everywhere on earth, even those across the sea.
Psa65:6 You are strong, and your mighty power put the mountains in place.
Psa65:7 You silence the roaring waves and the noisy shouts of the nations.
Psa65:8 People far away marvel at your fearsome deeds, and all who live under the sun celebrate and sing because of you.
Psa65:9 You take care of the earth and send rain to help the soil grow all kinds of crops. Your rivers never run dry, and you prepare the earth to produce much grain.
Psa65:10 You water all of its fields and level the lumpy ground. You send showers of rain to soften the soil and help the plants sprout.
Psa65:11 Wherever your footsteps touch the earth, a rich harvest is gathered.
Psa65:12 Desert pastures blossom, and mountains celebrate.
Psa65:13 Meadows are filled with sheep and goats; valleys overflow with grain and echo with joyful songs.
Psa66:1 Tell everyone on this earth to shout praises to God!
Psa66:2 Sing about his glorious name. Honor him with praises.
Psa66:3 Say to God, "Everything you do is fearsome, and your mighty power makes your enemies come crawling.
Psa66:4 You are worshiped by everyone! We all sing praises to you."
Psa66:5 Come and see the fearsome things our God has done!
Psa66:6 When God made the sea dry up, our people walked across, and because of him, we celebrated there.
Psa66:7 His mighty power rules forever, and nothing the nations do can be hidden from him. So don't turn against God.
Psa66:8 All of you people, come praise our God! Let his praises be heard.
Psa66:9 God protects us from death and keeps us steady.
Psa66:10 Our God, you tested us, just as silver is tested.
Psa66:11 You trapped us in a net and gave us heavy burdens.
Psa66:12 You sent war chariots to crush our skulls. We traveled through fire and through floods, but you brought us to a land of plenty.
Psa66:13 I will bring sacrifices into your house, my God, and I will do what I promised
Psa66:14 when I was in trouble.
Psa66:15 I will sacrifice my best sheep and offer bulls and goats on your altar.
Psa66:16 All who worship God, come here and listen; I will tell you everything God has done for me.
Psa66:17 I prayed to the Lord, and I praised him.
Psa66:18 If my thoughts had been sinful, he would have refused to hear me.
Psa66:19 But God did listen and answered my prayer.
Psa66:20 Let's praise God! He listened when I prayed, and he is always kind.
Psa67:1 Our God, be kind and bless us! Be pleased and smile.
Psa67:2 Then everyone on earth will learn to follow you, and all nations will see your power to save us.
Psa67:3 Make everyone praise you and shout your praises.
Psa67:4 Let the nations celebrate with joyful songs, because you judge fairly and guide all nations.
Psa67:5 Make everyone praise you and shout your praises.
Psa67:6 Our God has blessed the earth with a wonderful harvest!
Psa67:7 Pray for his blessings to continue and for everyone on earth to worship our God.
Psa68:1 Do something, God! Scatter your hateful enemies. Make them turn and run.
Psa68:2 Scatter them like smoke! When you come near, make them melt like wax in a fire.
Psa68:3 But let your people be happy and celebrate because of you.
Psa68:4 Our God, you are the one who rides on the clouds, and we praise you. Your name is the Lord , and we celebrate as we worship you.
Psa68:5 Our God, from your sacred home you take care of orphans and protect widows.
Psa68:6 You find families for those who are lonely. You set prisoners free and let them prosper, but all who rebel will live in a scorching desert.
Psa68:7 You set your people free, and you led them through the desert.
Psa68:8 God of Israel, the earth trembled, and rain poured down. You alone are the God who rules from Mount Sinai.
Psa68:9 When your land was thirsty, you sent showers to refresh it.
Psa68:10 Your people settled there, and you were generous to everyone in need.
Psa68:11 You gave the command, and a chorus of women told what had happened:
Psa68:12 "Kings and their armies retreated and ran, and everything they left is now being divided.
Psa68:13 And for those who stayed back to guard the sheep, there are metal doves with silver-coated wings and shiny gold feathers."
Psa68:14 God All-Powerful, you scattered the kings like snow falling on Mount Zalmon.
Psa68:15 Our Lord and our God, Bashan is a mighty mountain covered with peaks.
Psa68:16 Why is it jealous of Zion, the mountain you chose as your home forever?
Psa68:17 When you, Lord God, appeared to your people at Sinai, you came with thousands of mighty chariots.
Psa68:18 When you climbed the high mountain, you took prisoners with you and were given gifts. Your enemies didn't want you to live there, but they gave you gifts.
Psa68:19 We praise you, Lord God! You treat us with kindness day after day, and you rescue us.
Psa68:20 You always protect us and save us from death.
Psa68:21 Our Lord and our God, your terrible enemies are ready for war, but you will crush their skulls.
Psa68:22 You promised to bring them from Bashan and from the deepest sea.
Psa68:23 Then we could stomp on their blood, and our dogs could chew on their bones.
Psa68:24 We have seen crowds marching to your place of worship, our God and King.
Psa68:25 The singers come first, and then the musicians, surrounded by young women playing tambourines.
Psa68:26 They come shouting, "People of Israel, praise the Lord God!"
Psa68:27 The small tribe of Benjamin leads the way, followed by the leaders from Judah. Then come the leaders from Zebulun and Naphtali.
Psa68:28 Our God, show your strength! Show us once again.
Psa68:29 Then kings will bring gifts to your temple in Jerusalem.
Psa68:30 Punish that animal that lives in the swamp! Punish that nation whose leaders and people are like wild bulls. Make them come crawling with gifts of silver. Scatter those nations that enjoy making war.
Psa68:31 Force the Egyptians to bring gifts of bronze; make the Ethiopians hurry to offer presents.
Psa68:32 Now sing praises to God! Every kingdom on earth, sing to the Lord!
Psa68:33 Praise the one who rides across the ancient skies; listen as he speaks with a mighty voice.
Psa68:34 Tell about God's power! He is honored in Israel, and he rules the skies.
Psa68:35 The God of Israel is fearsome in his temple, and he makes us strong. Let's praise our God!
Psa69:1 Save me, God! I am about to drown.
Psa69:2 I am sinking deep in the mud, and my feet are slipping. I am about to be swept under by a mighty flood.
Psa69:3 I am worn out from crying, and my throat is dry. I have waited for you till my eyes are blurred.
Psa69:4 There are more people who hate me for no reason than there are hairs on my head. Many terrible enemies want to destroy me, God. Am I supposed to give back something I didn't steal?
Psa69:5 You know my foolish sins. Not one is hidden from you.
Psa69:6 Lord God All-Powerful, ruler of Israel, don't let me embarrass anyone who trusts and worships you.
Psa69:7 It is for your sake alone that I am insulted and blush with shame.
Psa69:8 I am like a stranger to my relatives and like a foreigner to my own family.
Psa69:9 My love for your house burns in me like a fire, and when others insulted you, they insulted me as well.
Psa69:10 I cried and went without food, but they still insulted me.
Psa69:11 They sneered at me for wearing sackcloth to show my sorrow.
Psa69:12 Rulers and judges gossip about me, and drunkards make up songs to mock me.
Psa69:13 But I pray to you, Lord . So when the time is right, answer me and help me with your wonderful love.
Psa69:14 Don't let me sink in the mud, but save me from my enemies and from the deep water.
Psa69:15 Don't let me be swept away by a flood or drowned in the ocean or swallowed by death.
Psa69:16 Answer me, Lord ! You are kind and good. Pay attention to me! You are truly merciful.
Psa69:17 Don't turn away from me. I am your servant, and I am in trouble. Please hurry and help!
Psa69:18 Come and save me from my enemies.
Psa69:19 You know how I am insulted, mocked, and disgraced; you know every one of my enemies.
Psa69:20 I am crushed by insults, and I feel sick. I had hoped for mercy and pity, but there was none.
Psa69:21 Enemies poisoned my food, and when I was thirsty, they gave me vinegar.
Psa69:22 Make their table a trap for them and their friends.
Psa69:23 Blind them with darkness and make them tremble.
Psa69:24 Show them how angry you are! Be furious and catch them.
Psa69:25 Destroy their camp and don't let anyone live in their tents.
Psa69:26 They cause trouble for people you have already punished; their gossip hurts those you have wounded.
Psa69:27 Make them guiltier than ever and don't forgive them.
Psa69:28 Wipe their names from the book of the living; remove them from the list of the innocent.
Psa69:29 I am mistreated and in pain. Protect me, God, and keep me safe!
Psa69:30 I will praise the Lord God with a song and a thankful heart.
Psa69:31 This will please the Lord better than offering an ox or a full-grown bull.
Psa69:32 When those in need see this, they will be happy, and the Lord 's worshipers will be encouraged.
Psa69:33 The Lord will listen when the homeless cry out, and he will never forget his people in prison.
Psa69:34 Heaven and earth will praise our God, and so will the oceans and everything in them.
Psa69:35 God will rescue Jerusalem, and he will rebuild the towns of Judah. His people will live there on their own land,
Psa69:36 and when the time comes, their children will inherit the land. Then everyone who loves God will also settle there.
Psa70:1 Save me, Lord God! Hurry and help.
Psa70:2 Disappoint and confuse all who want to kill me. Turn away and disgrace all who want to hurt me.
Psa70:3 Embarrass and shame those who say, "We told you so!"
Psa70:4 Let your worshipers celebrate and be glad because of you. They love your saving power, so let them always say, "God is wonderful!"
Psa70:5 I am poor and needy, but you, the Lord God, care about me. You are the one who saves me. Please hurry and help!
Psa71:1 I run to you, Lord , for protection. Don't disappoint me.
Psa71:2 You do what is right, so come to my rescue. Listen to my prayer and keep me safe.
Psa71:3 Be my mighty rock, the place where I can always run for protection. Save me by your command! You are my mighty rock and my fortress.
Psa71:4 Come and save me, Lord God, from vicious and cruel and brutal enemies!
Psa71:5 I depend on you, and I have trusted you since I was young.
Psa71:6 I have relied on you from the day I was born. You brought me safely through birth, and I always praise you.
Psa71:7 Many people think of me as something evil. But you are my mighty protector,
Psa71:8 and I praise and honor you all day long.
Psa71:9 Don't throw me aside when I am old; don't desert me when my strength is gone.
Psa71:10 My enemies are plotting because they want me dead.
Psa71:11 They say, "Now we'll catch you! God has deserted you, and no one can save you."
Psa71:12 Come closer, God! Please hurry and help.
Psa71:13 Embarrass and destroy all who want me dead; disgrace and confuse all who want to hurt me.
Psa71:14 I will never give up hope or stop praising you.
Psa71:15 All day long I will tell the wonderful things you do to save your people. But you have done much more than I could possibly know.
Psa71:16 I will praise you, Lord God, for your mighty deeds and your power to save.
Psa71:17 You have taught me since I was a child, and I never stop telling about your marvelous deeds.
Psa71:18 Don't leave me when I am old and my hair turns gray. Let me tell future generations about your mighty power.
Psa71:19 Your deeds of kindness are known in the heavens. No one is like you!
Psa71:20 You made me suffer a lot, but you will bring me back from this deep pit and give me new life.
Psa71:21 You will make me truly great and take my sorrow away.
Psa71:22 I will praise you, God, the Holy One of Israel. You are faithful. I will play the harp and sing your praises.
Psa71:23 You have rescued me! I will celebrate and shout, singing praises to you with all my heart.
Psa71:24 All day long I will announce your power to save. I will tell how you disgraced and disappointed those who wanted to hurt me.
Psa72:1 Please help the king to be honest and fair just like you, our God.
Psa72:2 Let him be honest and fair with all your people, especially the poor.
Psa72:3 Let peace and justice rule every mountain and hill.
Psa72:4 Let the king defend the poor, rescue the homeless, and crush everyone who hurts them.
Psa72:5 Let the king live forever like the sun and the moon.
Psa72:6 Let him be as helpful as rain that refreshes the meadows and the ground.
Psa72:7 Let the king be fair with everyone, and let there be peace until the moon falls from the sky.
Psa72:8 Let his kingdom reach from sea to sea, from the Euphrates River across all the earth.
Psa72:9 Force the desert tribes to accept his rule, and make his enemies crawl in the dirt.
Psa72:10 Force the rulers of Tarshish and of the islands to pay taxes to him. Make the kings of Sheba and of Seba bring gifts.
Psa72:11 Make other rulers bow down and all nations serve him.
Psa72:12 Do this because the king rescues the homeless when they cry out, and he helps everyone who is poor and in need.
Psa72:13 The king has pity on the weak and the helpless and protects those in need.
Psa72:14 He cares when they hurt, and he saves them from cruel and violent deaths.
Psa72:15 Long live the king! Give him gold from Sheba. Always pray for the king and praise him each day.
Psa72:16 Let cities overflow with food and hills be covered with grain, just like Mount Lebanon. Let the people in the cities prosper like wild flowers.
Psa72:17 May the glory of the king shine brightly forever like the sun in the sky. Let him make nations prosper and learn to praise him.
Psa72:18 Lord God of Israel, we praise you. Only you can work miracles.
Psa72:19 We will always praise your glorious name. Let your glory be seen everywhere on earth. Amen and amen.
Psa72:20 This ends the prayers of David, the son of Jesse.
Psa73:1 God is truly good to Israel, especially to everyone with a pure heart.
Psa73:2 But I almost stumbled and fell,
Psa73:3 because it made me jealous to see proud and evil people and to watch them prosper.
Psa73:4 They never have to suffer, they stay healthy,
Psa73:5 and they don't have troubles like everyone else.
Psa73:6 Their pride is like a necklace, and they commit sin more often than they dress themselves.
Psa73:7 Their eyes poke out with fat, and their minds are flooded with foolish thoughts.
Psa73:8 They sneer and say cruel things, and because of their pride, they make violent threats.
Psa73:9 They dare to speak against God and to order others around.
Psa73:10 God will bring his people back, and they will drink the water he so freely gives.
Psa73:11 Only evil people would say, "God Most High cannot know everything!"
Psa73:12 Yet all goes well for them, and they live in peace.
Psa73:13 What good did it do me to keep my thoughts pure and refuse to do wrong?
Psa73:14 I am sick all day, and I am punished each morning.
Psa73:15 If I had said evil things, I would not have been loyal to your people.
Psa73:16 It was hard for me to understand all this!
Psa73:17 Then I went to your temple, and there I understood what will happen to my enemies.
Psa73:18 You will make them stumble, never to get up again.
Psa73:19 They will be terrified, suddenly swept away and no longer there.
Psa73:20 They will disappear, Lord, despised like a bad dream the morning after.
Psa73:21 Once I was bitter and brokenhearted.
Psa73:22 I was stupid and ignorant, and I treated you as a wild animal would.
Psa73:23 But I never really left you, and you hold my right hand.
Psa73:24 Your advice has been my guide, and later you will welcome me in glory.
Psa73:25 In heaven I have only you, and on this earth you are all I want.
Psa73:26 My body and mind may fail, but you are my strength and my choice forever.
Psa73:27 Powerful Lord God, all who stay far from you will be lost, and you will destroy those who are unfaithful.
Psa73:28 It is good for me to be near you. I choose you as my protector, and I will tell about your wonderful deeds.
Psa74:1 Our God, why have you completely rejected us? Why are you so angry with the ones you care for?
Psa74:2 Remember the people you rescued long ago, the tribe you chose to be your very own. Think of Mount Zion, your home;
Psa74:3 walk over to the temple left in ruins forever by those who hate us.
Psa74:4 Your enemies roared like lions in your holy temple, and they have placed their banners there.
Psa74:5 It looks like a forest chopped to pieces.
Psa74:6 They used axes and hatchets to smash the carvings.
Psa74:7 They burned down your temple and badly disgraced it.
Psa74:8 They said to themselves, "We'll crush them!" Then they burned every one of your meeting places all over the country.
Psa74:9 There are no more miracles and no more prophets. Who knows how long it will be like this?
Psa74:10 Our God, how much longer will our enemies sneer? Won't they ever stop insulting you?
Psa74:11 Why don't you punish them? Why are you holding back?
Psa74:12 Our God and King, you have ruled since ancient times; you have won victories everywhere on this earth.
Psa74:13 By your power you made a path through the sea, and you smashed the heads of sea monsters.
Psa74:14 You crushed the heads of the monster Leviathan, then fed him to wild creatures in the desert.
Psa74:15 You opened the ground for streams and springs and dried up mighty rivers.
Psa74:16 You rule the day and the night, and you put the moon and the sun in place.
Psa74:17 You made summer and winter and gave them to the earth.
Psa74:18 Remember your enemies, Lord ! They foolishly sneer and won't respect you.
Psa74:19 You treat us like pet doves, but they mistreat us. Don't keep forgetting us and letting us be fed to those wild animals.
Psa74:20 Remember the agreement you made with us. Violent enemies are hiding in every dark corner of the earth.
Psa74:21 Don't disappoint those in need or make them turn from you, but help the poor and homeless to shout your praises.
Psa74:22 Do something, God! Defend yourself. Remember how those fools sneer at you all day long.
Psa74:23 Don't forget the loud shouts of your enemies.
Psa75:1 Our God, we thank you for being so near to us! Everyone celebrates your wonderful deeds.
Psa75:2 You have set a time to judge with fairness.
Psa75:3 The earth trembles, and its people shake; you alone keep its foundations firm.
Psa75:4 You tell every bragger, "Stop bragging!" And to the wicked you say, "Don't boast of your power!
Psa75:5 Stop bragging! Quit telling me how great you are."
Psa75:6 Our Lord and our God, victory doesn't come from the east or the west or from the desert.
Psa75:7 You are the one who judges. You can take away power and give it to others.
Psa75:8 You hold in your hand a cup filled with wine, strong and foaming. You will pour out some for every sinful person on this earth, and they will have to drink until it is gone.
Psa75:9 But I will always tell about you, the God of Jacob, and I will sing your praise.
Psa75:10 Our Lord, you will destroy the power of evil people, but you will give strength to those who are good.
Psa76:1 You, our God, are famous in Judah and honored in Israel.
Psa76:2 Your home is on Mount Zion in the city of peace.
Psa76:3 There you destroyed fiery arrows, shields, swords, and all the other weapons.
Psa76:4 You are more glorious than the eternal mountains.
Psa76:5 Brave warriors were robbed of what they had taken, and now they lie dead, unable to lift an arm.
Psa76:6 God of Jacob, when you roar, enemy chariots and horses drop dead in their tracks.
Psa76:7 Our God, you are fearsome, and no one can oppose you when you are angry.
Psa76:8 From heaven you announced your decisions as judge! And all who live on this earth were terrified and silent
Psa76:9 when you took over as judge, ready to rescue everyone in need.
Psa76:10 Even the most angry people will praise you when you are furious.
Psa76:11 Everyone, make your promises to the Lord your God and do what you promise. The Lord is fearsome, and all of his servants should bring him gifts.
Psa76:12 God destroys the courage of rulers and kings and makes cowards of them.
Psa77:1 I pray to you, Lord God, and I beg you to listen.
Psa77:2 In days filled with trouble, I search for you. And at night I tirelessly lift my hands in prayer, refusing comfort.
Psa77:3 When I think of you, I feel restless and weak.
Psa77:4 Because of you, Lord God, I can't sleep. I am restless and can't even talk.
Psa77:5 I think of times gone by, of those years long ago.
Psa77:6 Each night my mind is flooded with questions:
Psa77:7 "Have you rejected me forever? Won't you be kind again?
Psa77:8 Is this the end of your love and your promises?
Psa77:9 Have you forgotten how to have pity? Do you refuse to show mercy because of your anger?"
Psa77:10 Then I said, "God Most High, what hurts me most is that you no longer help us with your mighty arm."
Psa77:11 Our Lord , I will remember the things you have done, your miracles of long ago.
Psa77:12 I will think about each one of your mighty deeds.
Psa77:13 Everything you do is right, and no other god compares with you.
Psa77:14 You alone work miracles, and you have let nations see your mighty power.
Psa77:15 With your own arm you rescued your people, the descendants of Jacob and Joseph.
Psa77:16 The ocean looked at you, God, and it trembled deep down with fear.
Psa77:17 Water flowed from the clouds. Thunder was heard above as your arrows of lightning flashed about.
Psa77:18 Your thunder roared like chariot wheels. The world was made bright by lightning, and all the earth trembled.
Psa77:19 You walked through the water of the mighty sea, but your footprints were never seen.
Psa77:20 You guided your people like a flock of sheep, and you chose Moses and Aaron to be their leaders.
Psa78:1 My friends, I beg you to listen as I teach.
Psa78:2 I will give instruction and explain the mystery of what happened long ago.
Psa78:3 These are things we learned from our ancestors,
Psa78:4 and we will tell them to the next generation. We won't keep secret the glorious deeds and the mighty miracles of the Lord .
Psa78:5 God gave his Law to Jacob's descendants, the people of Israel. And he told our ancestors to teach their children,
Psa78:6 so that each new generation would know his Law and tell it to the next.
Psa78:7 Then they would trust God and obey his teachings, without forgetting anything God had done.
Psa78:8 They would be different from their ancestors, who were stubborn, rebellious, and unfaithful to God.
Psa78:9 The warriors from Ephraim were armed with arrows, but they ran away when the battle began.
Psa78:10 They broke their agreement with God, and they turned their backs on his teaching.
Psa78:11 They forgot all he had done, even the mighty miracles
Psa78:12 he did for their ancestors near Zoan in Egypt.
Psa78:13 God made a path in the sea and piled up the water as he led them across.
Psa78:14 He guided them during the day with a cloud, and each night he led them with a flaming fire.
Psa78:15 God made water flow from rocks he split open in the desert, and his people drank freely, as though from a lake.
Psa78:16 He made streams gush out like rivers from rocks.
Psa78:17 But in the desert, the people of God Most High kept sinning and rebelling.
Psa78:18 They stubbornly tested God and demanded from him what they wanted to eat.
Psa78:19 They challenged God by saying, "Can God provide food out here in the desert?
Psa78:20 It's true God struck the rock and water gushed out like a river, but can he give his people bread and meat?"
Psa78:21 When the Lord heard this, he was angry and furious with Jacob's descendants, the people of Israel.
Psa78:22 They had refused to trust him, and they had doubted his saving power.
Psa78:23 But God gave a command to the clouds, and he opened the doors in the skies.
Psa78:24 From heaven he sent grain that they called manna.
Psa78:25 He gave them more than enough, and each one of them ate this special food.
Psa78:26 God's mighty power brought a strong wind from the southeast,
Psa78:27 and it brought birds that covered the ground, like sand on the beach.
Psa78:28 Then God made the birds fall in the camp of his people near their tents.
Psa78:29 God gave his people all they wanted, and each of them ate until they were full.
Psa78:30 But before they had swallowed the last bite,
Psa78:31 God became angry and killed the strongest and best from the families of Israel.
Psa78:32 But the rest kept on sinning and would not trust God's miracles.
Psa78:33 So he cut their lives short and made them terrified.
Psa78:34 After he killed some of them, the others turned to him with all their hearts.
Psa78:35 They remembered God Most High, the mighty rock that kept them safe.
Psa78:36 But they tried to flatter God, and they told him lies;
Psa78:37 they were unfaithful and broke their promises.
Psa78:38 Yet God was kind. He kept forgiving their sins and didn't destroy them. He often became angry, but never lost his temper.
Psa78:39 God remembered that they were made of flesh and were like a wind that blows once and then dies down.
Psa78:40 While they were in the desert, they often rebelled and made God sad.
Psa78:41 They kept testing him and caused terrible pain for the Holy One of Israel.
