Psa135:4 He chose the family of Jacob and the people of Israel for his very own.
Psa135:5 The Lord is much greater than any other god.
Psa135:6 He does as he chooses in heaven and on earth and deep in the sea.
Psa135:7 The Lord makes the clouds rise from far across the earth, and he makes lightning to go with the rain. Then from his secret place he sends out the wind.
Psa135:8 The Lord killed the first-born of people and animals in the land of Egypt.
Psa135:9 God used miracles and wonders to fight the king of Egypt and all of his officials.
Psa135:10 He destroyed many nations and killed powerful kings,
Psa135:11 including King Sihon of the Amorites and King Og of Bashan. He conquered every kingdom in the land of Canaan
Psa135:12 and gave their property to his people Israel.
Psa135:13 The name of the Lord will be remembered forever, and he will be famous for all time to come.
Psa135:14 The Lord will bring justice and show mercy to all who serve him.
Psa135:15 Idols of silver and gold are made and worshiped in other nations.
Psa135:16 They have a mouth and eyes, but they can't speak or see.
Psa135:17 They are completely deaf, and they can't breathe.
Psa135:18 Everyone who makes idols and all who trust them will end up as helpless as their idols.
Psa135:19 Everyone in Israel, come praise the Lord ! All the family of Aaron
Psa135:20 and all the tribe of Levi, come praise the Lord ! All of his worshipers, come praise the Lord .
Psa135:21 Praise the Lord from Zion! He lives here in Jerusalem. Shout praises to the Lord !
Psa136:1 Praise the Lord ! He is good. God's love never fails.
Psa136:2 Praise the God of all gods. God's love never fails.
Psa136:3 Praise the Lord of lords. God's love never fails.
Psa136:4 Only God works great miracles. God's love never fails.
Psa136:5 With wisdom he made the sky. God's love never fails.
Psa136:6 The Lord stretched the earth over the ocean. God's love never fails.
Psa136:7 He made the bright lights in the sky. God's love never fails.
Psa136:8 He lets the sun rule each day. God's love never fails.
Psa136:9 He lets the moon and the stars rule each night. God's love never fails.
Psa136:10 God struck down the first-born in every Egyptian family. God's love never fails.
Psa136:11 He rescued Israel from Egypt. God's love never fails.
Psa136:12 God used his great strength and his powerful arm. God's love never fails.
Psa136:13 He split the Red Sea apart. God's love never fails.
Psa136:14 The Lord brought Israel safely through the sea. God's love never fails.
Psa136:15 He destroyed the Egyptian king and his army there. God's love never fails.
Psa136:16 The Lord led his people through the desert. God's love never fails.
Psa136:17 Our God defeated mighty kings. God's love never fails.
Psa136:18 And he killed famous kings. God's love never fails.
Psa136:19 One of them was Sihon, king of the Amorites. God's love never fails.
Psa136:20 Another was King Og of Bashan. God's love never fails.
Psa136:21 God took away their land. God's love never fails.
Psa136:22 He gave their land to Israel, the people who serve him. God's love never fails.
Psa136:23 God saw the trouble we were in. God's love never fails.
Psa136:24 He rescued us from our enemies. God's love never fails.
Psa136:25 He gives food to all who live. God's love never fails.
Psa136:26 Praise God in heaven! God's love never fails.
Psa137:1 Beside the rivers of Babylon we thought about Jerusalem, and we sat down and cried.
Psa137:2 We hung our small harps on the willow trees.
Psa137:3 Our enemies had brought us here as their prisoners, and now they wanted us to sing and entertain them. They insulted us and shouted, "Sing about Zion!"
Psa137:4 Here in a foreign land, how can we sing about the Lord ?
Psa137:5 Jerusalem, if I forget you, let my right hand go limp.
Psa137:6 Let my tongue stick to the roof of my mouth, if I don't think about you above all else.
Psa137:7 Our Lord , punish the Edomites! Because the day Jerusalem fell, they shouted, "Completely destroy the city! Tear down every building!"
Psa137:8 Babylon, you are doomed! I pray the Lord's blessings on anyone who punishes you for what you did to us.
Psa137:9 May the Lord bless everyone who beats your children against the rocks!
Psa138:1 With all my heart I praise you, Lord . In the presence of angels I sing your praises.
Psa138:2 I worship at your holy temple and praise you for your love and your faithfulness. You were true to your word and made yourself more famous than ever before.
Psa138:3 When I asked for your help, you answered my prayer and gave me courage.
Psa138:4 All kings on this earth have heard your promises, Lord , and they will praise you.
Psa138:5 You are so famous that they will sing about the things you have done.
Psa138:6 Though you are above us all, you care for humble people, and you keep a close watch on everyone who is proud.
Psa138:7 I am surrounded by trouble, but you protect me against my angry enemies. With your own powerful arm you keep me safe.
Psa138:8 You, Lord , will always treat me with kindness. Your love never fails. You have made us what we are. Don't give up on us now!
Psa139:1 You have looked deep into my heart, Lord , and you know all about me.
Psa139:2 You know when I am resting or when I am working, and from heaven you discover my thoughts.
Psa139:3 You notice everything I do and everywhere I go.
Psa139:4 Before I even speak a word, you know what I will say,
Psa139:5 and with your powerful arm you protect me from every side.
Psa139:6 I can't understand all of this! Such wonderful knowledge is far above me.
Psa139:7 Where could I go to escape from your Spirit or from your sight?
Psa139:8 If I were to climb up to the highest heavens, you would be there. If I were to dig down to the world of the dead you would also be there.
Psa139:9 Suppose I had wings like the dawning day and flew across the ocean.
Psa139:10 Even then your powerful arm would guide and protect me.
Psa139:11 Or suppose I said, "I'll hide in the dark until night comes to cover me over."
Psa139:12 But you see in the dark because daylight and dark are all the same to you.
Psa139:13 You are the one who put me together inside my mother's body,
Psa139:14 and I praise you because of the wonderful way you created me. Everything you do is marvelous! Of this I have no doubt.
Psa139:15 Nothing about me is hidden from you! I was secretly woven together deep in the earth below,
Psa139:16 but with your own eyes you saw my body being formed. Even before I was born, you had written in your book everything I would do.
Psa139:17 Your thoughts are far beyond my understanding, much more than I could ever imagine.
Psa139:18 I try to count your thoughts, but they outnumber the grains of sand on the beach. And when I awake, I will find you nearby.
Psa139:19 How I wish that you would kill all cruel and heartless people and protect me from them!
Psa139:20 They are always rebelling and speaking evil of you.
Psa139:21 You know I hate anyone who hates you, Lord , and refuses to obey.
Psa139:22 They are my enemies too, and I truly hate them.
Psa139:23 Look deep into my heart, God, and find out everything I am thinking.
Psa139:24 Don't let me follow evil ways, but lead me in the way that time has proven true.
Psa140:1 Rescue me from cruel and violent enemies, Lord !
Psa140:2 They think up evil plans and always cause trouble.
Psa140:3 Their words bite deep like the poisonous fangs of a snake.
Psa140:4 Protect me, Lord , from cruel and brutal enemies, who want to destroy me.
Psa140:5 Those proud people have hidden traps and nets to catch me as I walk.
Psa140:6 You, Lord , are my God! Please listen to my prayer.
Psa140:7 You have the power to save me, and you keep me safe in every battle.
Psa140:8 Don't let the wicked succeed in doing what they want, or else they might never stop planning evil.
Psa140:9 They have me surrounded, but make them the victims of their own vicious lies.
Psa140:10 Dump flaming coals on them and throw them into pits where they can't climb out.
Psa140:11 Chase those cruel liars away! Let trouble hunt them down.
Psa140:12 Our Lord , I know that you defend the homeless and see that the poor are given justice.
Psa140:13 Your people will praise you and will live with you because they do right.
Psa141:1 I pray to you, Lord ! Please listen when I pray and hurry to help me.
Psa141:2 Think of my prayer as sweet-smelling incense, and think of my lifted hands as an evening sacrifice.
Psa141:3 Help me to guard my words whenever I say something.
Psa141:4 Don't let me want to do evil or waste my time doing wrong with wicked people. Don't let me even taste the good things they offer.
Psa141:5 Let your faithful people correct and punish me. My prayers condemn the deeds of those who do wrong, so don't let me be friends with any of them.
Psa141:6 Everyone will admit that I was right when their rulers are thrown down a rocky cliff,
Psa141:7 and their bones lie scattered like broken rocks on top of a grave.
Psa141:8 You are my Lord and God, and I look to you for safety. Don't let me be harmed.
Psa141:9 Protect me from the traps of those violent people,
Psa141:10 and make them fall into their own traps while you help me escape.
Psa142:1 I pray to you, Lord . I beg for mercy.
Psa142:2 I tell you all of my worries and my troubles,
Psa142:3 and whenever I feel low, you are there to guide me. A trap has been hidden along my pathway.
Psa142:4 Even if you look, you won't see anyone who cares enough to walk beside me. There is no place to hide, and no one who really cares.
Psa142:5 I pray to you, Lord ! You are my place of safety, and you are my choice in the land of the living. Please answer my prayer. I am completely helpless.
Psa142:6 Help! They are chasing me, and they are too strong.
Psa142:7 Rescue me from this prison, so I can praise your name. And when your people notice your wonderful kindness to me, they will rush to my side.
Psa143:1 Listen, Lord , as I pray! You are faithful and honest and will answer my prayer.
Psa143:2 I am your servant. Don't try me in your court, because no one is innocent by your standards.
Psa143:3 My enemies are chasing me, crushing me in the ground. I am in total darkness, like someone long dead.
Psa143:4 I have given up all hope, and I feel numb all over.
Psa143:5 I remember to think about the many things you did in years gone by.
Psa143:6 Then I lift my hands in prayer, because my soul is a desert, thirsty for water from you.
Psa143:7 Please hurry, Lord , and answer my prayer. I feel hopeless. Don't turn away and leave me here to die.
Psa143:8 Each morning let me learn more about your love because I trust you. I come to you in prayer, asking for your guidance.
Psa143:9 Please rescue me from my enemies, Lord ! I come to you for safety.
Psa143:10 You are my God. Show me what you want me to do, and let your gentle Spirit lead me in the right path.
Psa143:11 Be true to your name, Lord , and keep my life safe. Use your saving power to protect me from trouble.
Psa143:12 I am your servant. Show how much you love me by destroying my enemies.
Psa144:1 I praise you, Lord ! You are my mighty rock, and you teach me how to fight my battles.
Psa144:2 You are my friend, and you are my fortress where I am safe. You are my shield, and you made me the ruler of our people.
Psa144:3 Why do we humans mean anything to you, our Lord ? Why do you care about us?
Psa144:4 We disappear like a breath; we last no longer than a faint shadow.
Psa144:5 Open the heavens like a curtain and come down, Lord . Touch the mountains and make them send up smoke.
Psa144:6 Use your lightning as arrows to scatter my enemies and make them run away.
Psa144:7 Reach down from heaven and set me free. Save me from the mighty flood
Psa144:8 of those lying foreigners who can't tell the truth.
Psa144:9 In praise of you, our God, I will sing a new song, while playing my harp.
Psa144:10 By your power, kings win wars, and your servant David is saved from deadly swords.
Psa144:11 Won't you keep me safe from those lying foreigners who can't tell the truth?
Psa144:12 Let's pray that our young sons will grow like strong plants and that our daughters will be as lovely as columns in the corner of a palace.
Psa144:13 May our barns be filled with all kinds of crops. May our fields be covered with sheep by the thousands,
Psa144:14 and every cow have calves. Don't let our city be captured or any of us be taken away, and don't let cries of sorrow be heard in our streets.
Psa144:15 Our Lord and our God, you give these blessings to all who worship you.
Psa145:1 I will praise you, my God and King, and always honor your name.
Psa145:2 I will praise you each day and always honor your name.
Psa145:3 You are wonderful, Lord , and you deserve all praise, because you are much greater than anyone can understand.
Psa145:4 Each generation will announce to the next your wonderful and powerful deeds.
Psa145:5 I will keep thinking about your marvelous glory and your mighty miracles.
Psa145:6 Everyone will talk about your fearsome deeds, and I will tell all nations how great you are.
Psa145:7 They will celebrate and sing about your matchless mercy and your power to save.
Psa145:8 You are merciful, Lord ! You are kind and patient and always loving.
Psa145:9 You are good to everyone, and you take care of all your creation.
Psa145:10 All creation will thank you, and your loyal people will praise you.
Psa145:11 They will tell about your marvelous kingdom and your power.
Psa145:12 Then everyone will know about the mighty things you do and your glorious kingdom.
Psa145:13 Your kingdom will never end, and you will rule forever. Our Lord , you keep your word and do everything you say.
Psa145:14 When someone stumbles or falls, you give a helping hand.
Psa145:15 Everyone depends on you, and when the time is right, you provide them with food.
Psa145:16 By your own hand you satisfy the desires of all who live.
Psa145:17 Our Lord , everything you do is kind and thoughtful,
Psa145:18 and you are near to everyone whose prayers are sincere.
Psa145:19 You satisfy the desires of all your worshipers, and you come to save them when they ask for help.
Psa145:20 You take care of everyone who loves you, but you destroy the wicked.
Psa145:21 I will praise you, Lord , and everyone will respect your holy name forever.
Psa146:1 Shout praises to the Lord ! With all that I am, I will shout his praises.
Psa146:2 I will sing and praise the Lord God for as long as I live.
Psa146:3 You can't depend on anyone, not even a great leader.
Psa146:4 Once they die and are buried, that will be the end of all their plans.
Psa146:5 The Lord God of Jacob blesses everyone who trusts him and depends on him.
Psa146:6 God made heaven and earth; he created the sea and everything else. God always keeps his word.
Psa146:7 He gives justice to the poor and food to the hungry. The Lord sets prisoners free
Psa146:8 and heals blind eyes. He gives a helping hand to everyone who falls. The Lord loves good people
Psa146:9 and looks after strangers. He defends the rights of orphans and widows, but destroys the wicked.
Psa146:10 The Lord God of Zion will rule forever! Shout praises to the Lord !
Psa147:1 Shout praises to the Lord ! Our God is kind, and it is right and good to sing praises to him.
Psa147:2 The Lord rebuilds Jerusalem and brings the people of Israel back home again.
Psa147:3 He renews our hopes and heals our bodies.
Psa147:4 He decided how many stars there would be in the sky and gave each one a name.
Psa147:5 Our Lord is great and powerful! He understands everything.
Psa147:6 The Lord helps the poor, but he smears the wicked in the dirt.
Psa147:7 Celebrate and sing! Play your harps for the Lord our God.
Psa147:8 He fills the sky with clouds and sends rain to the earth, so that the hills will be green with grass.
Psa147:9 He provides food for cattle and for the young ravens, when they cry out.
Psa147:10 The Lord doesn't care about the strength of horses or powerful armies.
Psa147:11 The Lord is pleased only with those who worship him and trust his love.
Psa147:12 Everyone in Jerusalem, come and praise the Lord your God!
Psa147:13 He makes your city gates strong and blesses your people by giving them children.
Psa147:14 God lets you live in peace, and he gives you the very best wheat.
Psa147:15 As soon as God speaks, the earth obeys.
Psa147:16 He covers the ground with snow like a blanket of wool, and he scatters frost like ashes on the ground.
Psa147:17 God sends down hailstones like chips of rocks. Who can stand the cold?
Psa147:18 At his command the ice melts, the wind blows, and streams begin to flow.
Psa147:19 God gave his laws and teachings to the descendants of Jacob, the nation of Israel.
Psa147:20 But he has not given his laws to any other nation. Shout praises to the Lord !
Psa148:1 Shout praises to the Lord ! Shout the Lord 's praises in the highest heavens.
Psa148:2 All of you angels, and all who serve him above, come and offer praise.
Psa148:3 Sun and moon, and all of you bright stars, come and offer praise.
Psa148:4 Highest heavens, and the water above the highest heavens, come and offer praise.
Psa148:5 Let all things praise the name of the Lord , because they were created at his command.
Psa148:6 He made them to last forever, and nothing can change what he has done.
Psa148:7 All creatures on earth, you obey his commands, so come praise the Lord !
Psa148:8 Sea monsters and the deep sea, fire and hail, snow and frost, and every stormy wind, come praise the Lord !
Psa148:9 All mountains and hills, fruit trees and cedars,
Psa148:10 every wild and tame animal, all reptiles and birds, come praise the Lord !
Psa148:11 Every king and every ruler, all nations on earth,
Psa148:12 every man and every woman, young people and old, come praise the Lord !
Psa148:13 All creation, come praise the name of the Lord . Praise his name alone. The glory of God is greater than heaven and earth.
Psa148:14 Like a bull with mighty horns, the Lord protects his faithful nation Israel, because they belong to him. Shout praises to the Lord !
Psa149:1 Shout praises to the Lord ! Sing him a new song of praise when his loyal people meet.
Psa149:2 People of Israel, rejoice because of your Creator. People of Zion, celebrate because of your King.
Psa149:3 Praise his name by dancing and playing music on harps and tambourines.
Psa149:4 The Lord is pleased with his people, and he gives victory to those who are humble.
Psa149:5 All of you faithful people, praise our glorious Lord! Celebrate and worship.
Psa149:6 Praise God with songs on your lips and a sword in your hand.
Psa149:7 Take revenge and punish the nations.
Psa149:8 Put chains of iron on their kings and rulers.
Psa149:9 Punish them as they deserve; this is the privilege of God's faithful people. Shout praises to the Lord !
Psa150:1 Shout praises to the Lord ! Praise God in his temple. Praise him in heaven, his mighty fortress.
Psa150:2 Praise our God! His deeds are wonderful, too marvelous to describe.
Psa150:3 Praise God with trumpets and all kinds of harps.
Psa150:4 Praise him with tambourines and dancing, with stringed instruments and woodwinds.
Psa150:5 Praise God with cymbals, with clashing cymbals.
Psa150:6 Let every living creature praise the Lord . Shout praises to the Lord !
Prv1:1 These are the proverbs of King Solomon of Israel, the son of David.
Prv1:2 Proverbs will teach you wisdom and self-control and how to understand sayings with deep meanings.
Prv1:3 You will learn what is right and honest and fair.
Prv1:4 From these, an ordinary person can learn to be smart, and young people can gain knowledge and good sense.
Prv1:5 If you are already wise, you will become even wiser. And if you are smart, you will learn to understand
Prv1:6 proverbs and sayings, as well as words of wisdom and all kinds of riddles.
Prv1:7 Respect and obey the Lord ! This is the beginning of knowledge. Only a fool rejects wisdom and good advice.
Prv1:8 My child, obey the teachings of your parents,
Prv1:9 and wear their teachings as you would a lovely hat or a pretty necklace.
Prv1:10 Don't be tempted by sinners or listen
Prv1:11 when they say, "Come on! Let's gang up and kill somebody, just for the fun of it!
Prv1:12 They're well and healthy now, but we'll finish them off once and for all.
Prv1:13 We'll take their valuables and fill our homes with stolen goods.
Prv1:14 If you join our gang, you'll get your share."
Prv1:15 Don't follow anyone like that or do what they do.
Prv1:16 They are in a big hurry to commit some crime, perhaps even murder.
Prv1:17 They are like a bird that sees the bait, but ignores the trap.
Prv1:18 They gang up to murder someone, but they are the victims.
Prv1:19 The wealth you get from crime robs you of your life.
Prv1:20 Wisdom shouts in the streets wherever crowds gather.
Prv1:21 She shouts in the marketplaces and near the city gates as she says to the people,
Prv1:22 "How much longer will you enjoy being stupid fools? Won't you ever stop sneering and laughing at knowledge?
Prv1:23 Listen as I correct you and tell you what I think.
Prv1:24 You completely ignored me and refused to listen;
Prv1:25 you rejected my advice and paid no attention when I warned you.
Prv1:26 "So when you are struck by some terrible disaster,
Prv1:27 or when trouble and distress surround you like a whirlwind, I will laugh and make fun.
Prv1:28 You will ask for my help, but I won't listen; you will search, but you won't find me.
Prv1:29 No, you would not learn, and you refused to respect the Lord .
Prv1:30 You rejected my advice and paid no attention when I warned you.
Prv1:31 "Now you will eat the fruit of what you have done, until you are stuffed full with your own schemes.
Prv1:32 Sin and self-satisfaction bring destruction and death to stupid fools.
Prv1:33 But if you listen to me, you will be safe and secure without fear of disaster."
Prv2:1 My child, you must follow and treasure my teachings and my instructions.
Prv2:2 Keep in tune with wisdom and think what it means to have common sense.
Prv2:3 Beg as loud as you can for good common sense.
Prv2:4 Search for wisdom as you would search for silver or hidden treasure.
Prv2:5 Then you will understand what it means to respect and to know the Lord God.
Prv2:6 All wisdom comes from the Lord , and so do common sense and understanding.
Prv2:7 God gives helpful advice to everyone who obeys him and protects all of those who live as they should.
Prv2:8 God sees that justice is done, and he watches over everyone who is faithful to him.
Prv2:9 With wisdom you will learn what is right and honest and fair.
Prv2:10 Wisdom will control your mind, and you will be pleased with knowledge.
Prv2:11 Sound judgment and good sense will watch over you.
Prv2:12 Wisdom will protect you from evil schemes and from those liars
Prv2:13 who turned from doing good to live in the darkness.
Prv2:14 Most of all they enjoy being mean and deceitful.
Prv2:15 They are dishonest themselves, and all they do is crooked.
Prv2:16 Wisdom will protect you from the smooth talk of a sinful woman,
Prv2:17 who breaks her wedding vows and leaves the man she married when she was young.
Prv2:18 The road to her house leads down to the dark world of the dead.
Prv2:19 Visit her, and you will never find the road to life again.
Prv2:20 Follow the example of good people and live an honest life.
Prv2:21 If you are honest and innocent, you will keep your land;
Prv2:22 if you do wrong and can never be trusted, you will be rooted out.
Prv3:1 My child, remember my teachings and instructions and obey them completely.
Prv3:2 They will help you live a long and prosperous life.
Prv3:3 Let love and loyalty always show like a necklace, and write them in your mind.
Prv3:4 God and people will like you and consider you a success.
Prv3:5 With all your heart you must trust the Lord and not your own judgment.
Prv3:6 Always let him lead you, and he will clear the road for you to follow.
Prv3:7 Don't ever think that you are wise enough, but respect the Lord and stay away from evil.
Prv3:8 This will make you healthy, and you will feel strong.
Prv3:9 Honor the Lord by giving him your money and the first part of all your crops.
Prv3:10 Then you will have more grain and grapes than you will ever need.
Prv3:11 My child, don't turn away or become bitter when the Lord corrects you.
Prv3:12 The Lord corrects everyone he loves, just as parents correct their favorite child.
Prv3:13 God blesses everyone who has wisdom and common sense.
Prv3:14 Wisdom is worth more than silver; it makes you much richer than gold.
Prv3:15 Wisdom is more valuable than precious jewels; nothing you want compares with her.
Prv3:16 In her right hand Wisdom holds a long life, and in her left hand are wealth and honor.
Prv3:17 Wisdom makes life pleasant and leads us safely along.
Prv3:18 Wisdom is a life-giving tree, the source of happiness for all who hold on to her.
Prv3:19 By his wisdom and knowledge the Lord created heaven and earth.
Prv3:20 By his understanding he let the ocean break loose and clouds release the rain.
Prv3:21 My child, use common sense and sound judgment! Always keep them in mind.
Prv3:22 They will help you to live a long and beautiful life.
Prv3:23 You will walk safely and never stumble;
Prv3:24 you will rest without a worry and sleep soundly.
Prv3:25 So don't be afraid of sudden disasters or storms that strike those who are evil.
Prv3:26 You can be sure that the Lord will protect you from harm.
Prv3:27 Do all you can for everyone who deserves your help.
Prv3:28 Don't tell your neighbor to come back tomorrow, if you can help today.
Prv3:29 Don't try to be mean to neighbors who trust you.
Prv3:30 Don't argue just to be arguing, when you haven't been hurt.
Prv3:31 Don't be jealous of cruel people or follow their example.
Prv3:32 The Lord doesn't like anyone who is dishonest, but he lets good people be his friends.
Prv3:33 He places a curse on the home of everyone who is evil, but he blesses the home of every good person.
Prv3:34 The Lord sneers at those who sneer at him, but he is kind to everyone who is humble.
Prv3:35 You will be praised if you are wise, but you will be disgraced if you are a stubborn fool.
Prv4:1 My child, listen closely to my teachings and learn common sense.
Prv4:2 My advice is useful, so don't turn away.
Prv4:3 When I was still very young and my mother's favorite child, my father
Prv4:4 said to me: "If you follow my teachings and keep them in mind, you will live.
Prv4:5 Be wise and learn good sense; remember my teachings and do what I say.
Prv4:6 If you love Wisdom and don't reject her, she will watch over you.
Prv4:7 The best thing about Wisdom is Wisdom herself; good sense is more important than anything else.
Prv4:8 If you value Wisdom and hold tightly to her, great honors will be yours.
Prv4:9 It will be like wearing a glorious crown of beautiful flowers.
Prv4:10 My child, if you listen and obey my teachings, you will live a long time.
Prv4:11 I have shown you the way that makes sense; I have guided you along the right path.
Prv4:12 Your road won't be blocked, and you won't stumble when you run.
Prv4:13 Hold firmly to my teaching and never let go. It will mean life for you.
Prv4:14 Don't follow the bad example of cruel and evil people.
Prv4:15 Turn aside and keep going. Stay away from them.
Prv4:16 They can't sleep or rest until they do wrong or harm some innocent victim.
Prv4:17 Their food and drink are violence and cruelty.
Prv4:18 The lifestyle of good people is like sunlight at dawn that keeps getting brighter until broad daylight.
Prv4:19 The lifestyle of the wicked is like total darkness, and they will never know what makes them stumble.
Prv4:20 My child, listen carefully to everything I say.
Prv4:21 Don't forget a single word, but think about it all.
Prv4:22 Knowing these teachings will mean true life and good health for you.
Prv4:23 Carefully guard your thoughts because they are the source of true life.
Prv4:24 Never tell lies or be deceitful in what you say.
Prv4:25 Keep looking straight ahead, without turning aside.
Prv4:26 Know where you are headed, and you will stay on solid ground.
Prv4:27 Don't make a mistake by turning to the right or the left.
Prv5:1 My son, if you listen closely to my wisdom and good sense,
Prv5:2 you will have sound judgment, and you will always know the right thing to say.
Prv5:3 The words of an immoral woman may be as sweet as honey and as smooth as olive oil.
Prv5:4 But all that you really get from being with her is bitter poison and pain.
Prv5:5 If you follow her, she will lead you down to the world of the dead.
Prv5:6 She has missed the path that leads to life and doesn't even know it.
Prv5:7 My son, listen to me and do everything I say.
Prv5:8 Stay away from a bad woman! Don't even go near the door of her house.
Prv5:9 You will lose your self-respect and end up in debt to some cruel person for the rest of your life.
Prv5:10 Strangers will get your money and everything else you have worked for.
Prv5:11 When it's all over, your body will waste away, as you groan
Prv5:12 and shout, "I hated advice and correction!
Prv5:13 I paid no attention to my teachers,
Prv5:14 and now I am disgraced in front of everyone."
Prv5:15 You should be faithful to your wife, just as you take water from your own well.
Prv5:16 And don't be like a stream from which just any woman may take a drink.
Prv5:17 Save yourself for your wife and don't have sex with other women.
Prv5:18 Be happy with the wife you married when you were young.
Prv5:19 She is beautiful and graceful, just like a deer; you should be attracted to her and stay deeply in love.
Prv5:20 Don't go crazy over a woman who is unfaithful to her own husband!
Prv5:21 The Lord sees everything, and he watches us closely.
Prv5:22 Sinners are trapped and caught by their own evil deeds.
Prv5:23 They get lost and die because of their foolishness and lack of self-control.
Prv6:1 My child, suppose you agree to pay the debt of someone, who cannot repay a loan.
Prv6:2 Then you are trapped by your own words,
Prv6:3 and you are now in the power of someone else. Here is what you should do: Go and beg for permission to call off the agreement.
Prv6:4 Do this before you fall asleep or even get sleepy.
Prv6:5 Save yourself, just as a deer or a bird tries to escape from a hunter.
Prv6:6 You lazy people can learn by watching an anthill.
Prv6:7 Ants don't have leaders,
Prv6:8 but they store up food during harvest season.
Prv6:9 How long will you lie there doing nothing at all? When are you going to get up and stop sleeping?
Prv6:10 Sleep a little. Doze a little. Fold your hands and twiddle your thumbs.
Prv6:11 Suddenly, everything is gone, as though it had been taken by an armed robber.
Prv6:12 Worthless liars go around
Prv6:13 winking and giving signals to deceive others.
Prv6:14 They are always thinking up something cruel and evil, and they stir up trouble.
Prv6:15 But they will be struck by sudden disaster and left without a hope.
Prv6:16 There are six or seven kinds of people the Lord doesn't like:
Prv6:17 Those who are too proud or tell lies or murder,
Prv6:18 those who make evil plans or are quick to do wrong,
Prv6:19 those who tell lies in court or stir up trouble in a family.
Prv6:20 Obey the teaching of your parents - 
Prv6:21 always keep it in mind and never forget it.
Prv6:22 Their teaching will guide you when you walk, protect you when you sleep, and talk to you when you are awake.
Prv6:23 The Law of the Lord is a lamp, and its teachings shine brightly. Correction and self-control will lead you through life.
Prv6:24 They will protect you from the flattering words of someone else's wife.
Prv6:25 Don't let yourself be attracted by the charm and lovely eyes of someone like that.
Prv6:26 A woman who sells her love can be bought for as little as the price of a meal. But making love to another man's wife will cost you everything.
Prv6:27 If you carry burning coals, you burn your clothes;
Prv6:28 if you step on hot coals, you burn your feet.
Prv6:29 And if you go to bed with another man's wife, you pay the price.
Prv6:30 We don't put up with thieves, not even with one who steals for something to eat.
Prv6:31 And thieves who get caught must pay back seven times what was stolen and lose everything.
Prv6:32 But if you go to bed with another man's wife, you will destroy yourself by your own stupidity.
Prv6:33 You will be beaten and forever disgraced,
Prv6:34 because a jealous husband can be furious and merciless when he takes revenge.
Prv6:35 He won't let you pay him off, no matter what you offer.
Prv7:1 My son, pay close attention and don't forget what I tell you to do.
Prv7:2 Obey me, and you will live! Let my instructions be your greatest treasure.
Prv7:3 Keep them at your fingertips and write them in your mind.
Prv7:4 Let wisdom be your sister and make common sense your closest friend.
Prv7:5 They will protect you from the flattering words of someone else's wife.
Prv7:6 From the window of my house, I once happened to see
Prv7:7 some foolish young men.
Prv7:8 It was late in the evening, sometime after dark.
Prv7:9 One of these young men turned the corner and was walking by the house of an unfaithful wife.
Prv7:10 She was dressed fancy like a woman of the street with only one thing in mind.
Prv7:11 She was one of those women who are loud and restless and never stay at home,
Prv7:12 who walk street after street, waiting to trap a man.
Prv7:13 She grabbed him and kissed him, and with no sense of shame, she said:
Prv7:14 "I had to offer a sacrifice, and there is enough meat left over for a feast.
Prv7:15 So I came looking for you, and here you are!
Prv7:16 The sheets on my bed are bright-colored cloth from Egypt.
Prv7:17 And I have covered it with perfume made of myrrh, aloes, and cinnamon.
Prv7:18 "Let's go there and make love all night.
Prv7:19 My husband is traveling, and he's far away.
Prv7:20 He took a lot of money along, and he won't be back home before the middle of the month."
Prv7:21 And so, she tricked him with all of her sweet talk and her flattery.
Prv7:22 Right away he followed her like an ox on the way to be slaughtered, or like a fool on the way to be punished
Prv7:23 and killed with arrows. He was no more than a bird rushing into a trap, without knowing it would cost him his life.
Prv7:24 My son, pay close attention to what I have said.
Prv7:25 Don't even think about that kind of woman or let yourself be misled by someone like her.
Prv7:26 Such a woman has caused the downfall and destruction of a lot of men.
Prv7:27 Her house is a one-way street leading straight down to the world of the dead.
Prv8:1 With great understanding, Wisdom is calling out
Prv8:2 as she stands at the crossroads and on every hill.
Prv8:3 She stands by the city gate where everyone enters the city, and she shouts:
Prv8:4 "I am calling out to each one of you!
Prv8:5 Good sense and sound judgment can be yours.
Prv8:6 Listen, because what I say is worthwhile and right.
Prv8:7 I always speak the truth and refuse to tell a lie.
Prv8:8 Every word I speak is honest, not one is misleading or deceptive.
Prv8:9 "If you have understanding, you will see that my words are just what you need.
Prv8:10 Let instruction and knowledge mean more to you than silver or the finest gold.
Prv8:11 Wisdom is worth much more than precious jewels or anything else you desire."
Prv8:12 I am Wisdom  - Common Sense is my closest friend; I possess knowledge and sound judgment.
Prv8:13 If you respect the Lord , you will hate evil. I hate pride and conceit and deceitful lies.
Prv8:14 I am strong, and I offer sensible advice and sound judgment.
Prv8:15 By my power kings govern, and rulers make laws that are fair.
Prv8:16 Every honest leader rules with help from me.
Prv8:17 I love everyone who loves me, and I will be found by all who honestly search.
Prv8:18 I can make you rich and famous, important and successful.
Prv8:19 What you receive from me is more valuable than even the finest gold or the purest silver.
Prv8:20 I always do what is right,
Prv8:21 and I give great riches to everyone who loves me.
Prv8:22 From the beginning, I was with the Lord . I was there before he began
Prv8:23 to create the earth. At the very first, the Lord gave life to me.
Prv8:24 When I was born, there were no oceans or springs of water.
Prv8:25 My birth was before mountains were formed or hills were put in place.
Prv8:26 It happened long before God had made the earth or any of its fields or even the dust.
Prv8:27 I was there when the Lord put the heavens in place and stretched the sky over the surface of the sea.
Prv8:28 I was with him when he placed the clouds in the sky and created the springs that fill the ocean.
Prv8:29 I was there when he set boundaries for the sea to make it obey him, and when he laid foundations to support the earth.
Prv8:30 I was right beside the Lord , helping him plan and build. I made him happy each day, and I was happy at his side.
Prv8:31 I was pleased with his world and pleased with its people.
Prv8:32 Pay attention, my children! Follow my advice, and you will be happy.
Prv8:33 Listen carefully to my instructions, and you will be wise.
Prv8:34 Come to my home each day and listen to me. You will find happiness.
Prv8:35 By finding me, you find life, and the Lord will be pleased with you.
Prv8:36 But if you don't find me, you hurt only yourself, and if you hate me, you are in love with death.
Prv9:1 Wisdom has built her house with its seven columns.
Prv9:2 She has prepared the meat and set out the wine. Her feast is ready.
Prv9:3 She has sent her servant women to announce her invitation from the highest hills:
Prv9:4 "Everyone who is ignorant or foolish is invited!
Prv9:5 All of you are welcome to my meat and wine.
Prv9:6 If you want to live, give up your foolishness and let understanding guide your steps."
Prv9:7 Correct a worthless bragger, and all you will get are insults and injuries.
Prv9:8 Any bragger you correct will only hate you. But if you correct someone who has common sense, you will be loved.
Prv9:9 If you have good sense, instruction will help you to have even better sense. And if you live right, education will help you to know even more.
Prv9:10 Respect and obey the Lord ! This is the beginning of wisdom. To have understanding, you must know the Holy God.
Prv9:11 I am Wisdom. If you follow me, you will live a long time.
Prv9:12 Good sense is good for you, but if you brag, you hurt yourself.
Prv9:13 Stupidity is reckless, senseless, and foolish.
Prv9:14 She sits in front of her house and on the highest hills in the town.
Prv9:15 She shouts to everyone who passes by,
Prv9:16 "If you are stupid, come on inside!" And to every fool she says,
Prv9:17 "Stolen water tastes best, and the food you eat in secret tastes best of all."
Prv9:18 None who listen to Stupidity understand that her guests are as good as dead.
Prv10:1 Here are some proverbs of Solomon: Children with good sense make their parents happy, but foolish children make them sad.
Prv10:2 What you gain by doing evil won't help you at all, but being good can save you from death.
Prv10:3 If you obey the Lord , you won't go hungry; if you are wicked, God won't let you have what you want.
Prv10:4 Laziness leads to poverty; hard work makes you rich.
Prv10:5 At harvest season it's smart to work hard, but stupid to sleep.
Prv10:6 Everyone praises good people, but evil hides behind the words of the wicked.
Prv10:7 Good people are remembered long after they are gone, but the wicked are soon forgotten.
Prv10:8 If you have good sense, you will listen and obey; if all you do is talk, you will destroy yourself.
Prv10:9 You will be safe, if you always do right, but you will get caught, if you are dishonest.
Prv10:10 Deceit causes trouble, and foolish talk will bring you to ruin.
Prv10:11 The words of good people are a source of life, but evil hides behind the words of the wicked.
Prv10:12 Hatred stirs up trouble; love overlooks the wrongs that others do.
Prv10:13 If you have good sense, it will show when you speak. But if you are stupid, you will be beaten with a stick.
Prv10:14 If you have good sense, you will learn all you can, but foolish talk will soon destroy you.
Prv10:15 Great wealth can be a fortress, but poverty is no protection at all.
Prv10:16 If you live right, the reward is a good life; if you are evil, all you have is sin.
Prv10:17 Accept correction, and you will find life; reject correction, and you will miss the road.
Prv10:18 You can hide your hatred by telling lies, but you are a fool to spread lies.
Prv10:19 You will say the wrong thing if you talk too much -  so be sensible and watch what you say.
Prv10:20 The words of a good person are like pure silver, but the thoughts of an evil person are almost worthless.
Prv10:21 Many are helped by useful instruction, but fools are killed by their own stupidity.
Prv10:22 When the Lord blesses you with riches, you have nothing to regret.
Prv10:23 Fools enjoy doing wrong, but anyone with good sense enjoys acting wisely.
Prv10:24 What evil people dread most will happen to them, but good people will get what they want most.
Prv10:25 Those crooks will disappear when a storm strikes, but God will keep safe all who obey him.
Prv10:26 Having a lazy person on the job is like a mouth full of vinegar or smoke in your eyes.
Prv10:27 If you respect the Lord , you will live longer; if you keep doing wrong, your life will be cut short.
Prv10:28 If you obey the Lord, you will be happy, but there is no future for the wicked.
Prv10:29 The Lord protects everyone who lives right, but he destroys anyone who does wrong.
Prv10:30 Good people will stand firm, but the wicked will lose their land.
Prv10:31 Honest people speak sensibly, but deceitful liars will be silenced.
Prv10:32 If you obey the Lord, you will always know the right thing to say. But no one will trust you if you tell lies.
Prv11:1 The Lord hates anyone who cheats, but he likes everyone who is honest.
Prv11:2 Too much pride can put you to shame. It's wiser to be humble.
Prv11:3 If you do the right thing, honesty will be your guide. But if you are crooked, you will be trapped by your own dishonesty.
Prv11:4 When God is angry, money won't help you. Obeying God is the only way to be saved from death.
Prv11:5 If you are truly good, you will do right; if you are wicked, you will be destroyed by your own sin.
Prv11:6 Honesty can keep you safe, but if you can't be trusted, you trap yourself.
Prv11:7 When the wicked die, their hopes die with them.
Prv11:8 Trouble goes right past the Lord 's people and strikes the wicked.
Prv11:9 Dishonest people use gossip to destroy their neighbors; good people are protected by their own good sense.
Prv11:10 When honest people prosper and the wicked disappear, the whole city celebrates.
Prv11:11 When God blesses his people, their city prospers, but deceitful liars can destroy a city.
Prv11:12 It's stupid to say bad things about your neighbors. If you are sensible, you will keep quiet.
Prv11:13 A gossip tells everything, but a true friend will keep a secret.
Prv11:14 A city without wise leaders will end up in ruin; a city with many wise leaders will be kept safe.
Prv11:15 It's a dangerous thing to guarantee payment for someone's debts. Don't do it!
Prv11:16 A gracious woman will be respected, but a man must work hard to get rich.
Prv11:17 Kindness is rewarded -  but if you are cruel, you hurt yourself.
Prv11:18 Meanness gets you nowhere, but goodness is rewarded.
Prv11:19 Always do the right thing, and you will live; keep on doing wrong, and you will die.
Prv11:20 The Lord hates sneaky people, but he likes everyone who lives right.
Prv11:21 You can be sure of this: All crooks will be punished, but God's people won't.
Prv11:22 A beautiful woman who acts foolishly is like a gold ring on the snout of a pig.
Prv11:23 Good people want what is best, but troublemakers hope to stir up trouble.
Prv11:24 Sometimes you can become rich by being generous or poor by being greedy.
Prv11:25 Generosity will be rewarded: Give a cup of water, and you will receive a cup of water in return.
Prv11:26 Charge too much for grain, and you will be cursed; sell it at a fair price, and you will be praised.
Prv11:27 Try hard to do right, and you will win friends; go looking for trouble, and you will find it.
Prv11:28 Trust in your wealth, and you will be a failure, but God's people will prosper like healthy plants.
Prv11:29 Fools who cause trouble in the family won't inherit a thing. They will end up as slaves of someone with good sense.
Prv11:30 Live right, and you will eat from the life-giving tree. And if you act wisely, others will follow.
Prv11:31 If good people are rewarded here on this earth, all who are cruel and mean will surely be punished.
Prv12:1 To accept correction is wise, to reject it is stupid.
Prv12:2 The Lord likes everyone who lives right, but he punishes everyone who makes evil plans.
Prv12:3 Sin cannot offer security! But if you live right, you will be as secure as a tree with deep roots.
Prv12:4 A helpful wife is a jewel for her husband, but a shameless wife will make his bones rot.
Prv12:5 Good people have kind thoughts, but you should never trust the advice of someone evil.
Prv12:6 Bad advice is a deadly trap, but good advice is like a shield.
Prv12:7 Once the wicked are defeated, they are gone forever, but no one who obeys God will ever be thrown down.
Prv12:8 Good sense is worthy of praise, but stupidity is a curse.
Prv12:9 It's better to be ordinary and have only one servant than to think you are somebody and starve to death.
Prv12:10 Good people are kind to their animals, but a mean person is cruel.
Prv12:11 Hard working farmers have more than enough food; daydreamers are nothing more than stupid fools.
Prv12:12 An evil person tries to hide behind evil; good people are like trees with deep roots.
Prv12:13 We trap ourselves by telling lies, but we stay out of trouble by living right.
Prv12:14 We are rewarded or punished for what we say and do.
Prv12:15 Fools think they know what is best, but a sensible person listens to advice.
Prv12:16 Losing your temper is foolish; ignoring an insult is smart.
Prv12:17 An honest person tells the truth in court, but a dishonest person tells nothing but lies.
Prv12:18 Sharp words cut like a sword, but words of wisdom heal.
Prv12:19 Truth will last forever; lies are soon found out.
Prv12:20 An evil mind is deceitful, but gentle thoughts bring happiness.
Prv12:21 Good people never have trouble, but troublemakers have more than enough.
Prv12:22 The Lord hates every liar, but he is the friend of all who can be trusted.
Prv12:23 Be sensible and don't tell everything you know -  only fools spread foolishness everywhere.
Prv12:24 Work hard, and you will be a leader; be lazy, and you will end up a slave.
Prv12:25 Worry is a heavy burden, but a kind word always brings cheer.
Prv12:26 You are better off to do right, than to lose your way by doing wrong.
Prv12:27 Anyone too lazy to cook will starve, but a hard worker is a valuable treasure.
Prv12:28 Follow the road to life, and you won't be bothered by death.
Prv13:1 Children with good sense accept correction from their parents, but stubborn children ignore it completely.
Prv13:2 You will be well rewarded for saying something kind, but all some people think about is how to be cruel and mean.
Prv13:3 Keep what you know to yourself, and you will be safe; talk too much, and you are done for.
Prv13:4 No matter how much you want, laziness won't help a bit, but hard work will reward you with more than enough.
Prv13:5 A good person hates deceit, but those who are evil cause shame and disgrace.
Prv13:6 Live right, and you are safe! But sin will destroy you.
Prv13:7 Some who have nothing may pretend to be rich, and some who have everything may pretend to be poor.
Prv13:8 The rich may have to pay a ransom, but the poor don't have that problem.
Prv13:9 The lamp of a good person keeps on shining; the lamp of an evil person soon goes out.
Prv13:10 Too much pride causes trouble. Be sensible and take advice.
Prv13:11 Money wrongly gotten will disappear bit by bit; money earned little by little will grow and grow.
Prv13:12 Not getting what you want can make you feel sick, but a wish that comes true is a life-giving tree.
Prv13:13 If you reject God's teaching, you will pay the price; if you obey his commands, you will be rewarded.
Prv13:14 Sensible instruction is a life-giving fountain that helps you escape all deadly traps.
Prv13:15 Sound judgment is praised, but people without good sense are on the way to disaster.
Prv13:16 If you have good sense, you will act sensibly, but fools act like fools.
Prv13:17 Whoever delivers your message can make things better or worse for you.
Prv13:18 All who refuse correction will be poor and disgraced; all who accept correction will be praised.
Prv13:19 It's a good feeling to get what you want, but only a stupid fool hates to turn from evil.
Prv13:20 Wise friends make you wise, but you hurt yourself by going around with fools.
Prv13:21 You are in for trouble if you sin, but you will be rewarded if you live right.
Prv13:22 If you obey God, you will have something to leave your grandchildren. If you don't obey God, those who live right will get what you leave.
Prv13:23 Even when the land of the poor produces good crops, they get cheated out of what they grow.
Prv13:24 If you love your children, you will correct them; if you don't love them, you won't correct them.
Prv13:25 If you live right, you will have plenty to eat; if you don't live right, you will go away empty.
Prv14:1 A woman's family is held together by her wisdom, but it can be destroyed by her foolishness.
Prv14:2 By living right, you show that you respect the Lord ; by being deceitful, you show that you despise him.
Prv14:3 Proud fools are punished for their stupid talk, but sensible talk can save your life.
Prv14:4 Without the help of an ox there can be no crop, but with a strong ox a big crop is possible.
Prv14:5 An honest witness tells the truth; a dishonest witness tells nothing but lies.
Prv14:6 Make fun of wisdom, and you will never find it. But if you have understanding, knowledge comes easily.
Prv14:7 Stay away from fools, or you won't learn a thing.
Prv14:8 Wise people have enough sense to find their way, but stupid fools get lost.
Prv14:9 Fools don't care if they are wrong, but God is pleased when people do right.
Prv14:10 No one else can really know how sad or happy you are.
Prv14:11 The tent of a good person stands longer than the house of someone evil.
Prv14:12 You may think you are on the right road and still end up dead.
Prv14:13 Sorrow may hide behind laughter, and happiness may end in sorrow.
Prv14:14 You harvest what you plant, whether good or bad.
Prv14:15 Don't be stupid and believe all you hear; be smart and know where you are headed.
Prv14:16 Only a stupid fool is never cautious -  so be extra careful and stay out of trouble.
Prv14:17 Fools have quick tempers, and no one likes you if you can't be trusted.
Prv14:18 Stupidity leads to foolishness; be smart and learn.
Prv14:19 The wicked will come crawling to those who obey God.
Prv14:20 You have no friends if you are poor, but you have lots of friends if you are rich.
Prv14:21 It's wrong to hate others, but God blesses everyone who is kind to the poor.
Prv14:22 It's a mistake to make evil plans, but you will have loyal friends if you want to do right.
Prv14:23 Hard work is worthwhile, but empty talk will make you poor.
Prv14:24 Wisdom can make you rich, but foolishness leads to more foolishness.
Prv14:25 An honest witness can save your life, but liars can't be trusted.
Prv14:26 If you respect the Lord , you and your children have a strong fortress
Prv14:27 and a life-giving fountain that keeps you safe from deadly traps.
Prv14:28 Rulers of powerful nations are held in honor; rulers of weak nations are nothing at all.
Prv14:29 It's smart to be patient, but it's stupid to lose your temper.
Prv14:30 It's healthy to be content, but envy can eat you up.
Prv14:31 If you mistreat the poor, you insult your Creator; if you are kind to them, you show him respect.
Prv14:32 In times of trouble the wicked are destroyed, but even at death the innocent have faith.
Prv14:33 Wisdom is found in the minds of people with good sense, but fools don't know it.
Prv14:34 Doing right brings honor to a nation, but sin brings disgrace.
Prv14:35 Kings reward servants who act wisely, but they punish those who act foolishly.
Prv15:1 A kind answer soothes angry feelings, but harsh words stir them up.
Prv15:2 Words of wisdom come from the wise, but fools speak foolishness.
Prv15:3 The Lord sees everything, whether good or bad.
Prv15:4 Kind words are good medicine, but deceitful words can really hurt.
Prv15:5 Don't be a fool and disobey your parents. Be smart! Accept correction.
Prv15:6 Good people become wealthy, but those who are evil will lose what they have.
Prv15:7 Words of wisdom make good sense; the thoughts of a fool make no sense at all.
Prv15:8 The Lord is disgusted by gifts from the wicked, but it makes him happy when his people pray.
Prv15:9 The Lord is disgusted with all who do wrong, but he loves everyone who does right.
Prv15:10 If you turn from the right way, you will be punished; if you refuse correction, you will die.
Prv15:11 If the Lord can see everything in the world of the dead, he can see in our hearts.
Prv15:12 Those who sneer at others don't like to be corrected, and they won't ask help from someone with sense.
Prv15:13 Happiness makes you smile; sorrow can crush you.
Prv15:14 Anyone with good sense is eager to learn more, but fools are hungry for foolishness.
Prv15:15 The poor have a hard life, but being content is as good as an endless feast.
Prv15:16 It's better to obey the Lord and have only a little, than to be very rich and terribly confused.
Prv15:17 A simple meal with love is better than a feast where there is hatred.
Prv15:18 Losing your temper causes a lot of trouble, but staying calm settles arguments.
Prv15:19 Being lazy is like walking in a thorn patch, but everyone who does right walks on a smooth road.
Prv15:20 Children with good sense make their parents happy, but foolish children are hateful to them.
Prv15:21 Stupidity brings happiness to senseless fools, but everyone with good sense follows the straight path.
Prv15:22 Without good advice everything goes wrong -  it takes careful planning for things to go right.
Prv15:23 Giving the right answer at the right time makes everyone happy.
Prv15:24 All who are wise follow a road that leads upward to life and away from death.
Prv15:25 The Lord destroys the homes of those who are proud, but he protects the property of widows.
Prv15:26 The Lord hates evil thoughts, but kind words please him.
Prv15:27 Being greedy causes trouble for your family, but you protect yourself by refusing bribes.
Prv15:28 Good people think before they answer, but the wicked speak evil without ever thinking.
Prv15:29 The Lord never even hears the prayers of the wicked, but he answers the prayers of all who obey him.
Prv15:30 A friendly smile makes you happy, and good news makes you feel strong.
Prv15:31 Healthy correction is good, and if you accept it, you will be wise.
Prv15:32 You hurt only yourself by rejecting instruction, but it makes good sense to accept it.
Prv15:33 Showing respect to the Lord will make you wise, and being humble will bring honor to you.
Prv16:1 We humans make plans, but the Lord has the final word.
Prv16:2 We may think we know what is right, but the Lord is the judge of our motives.
Prv16:3 Share your plans with the Lord , and you will succeed.
Prv16:4 The Lord has a reason for everything he does, and he lets evil people live only to be punished.
Prv16:5 The Lord doesn't like anyone who is conceited -  you can be sure they will be punished.
Prv16:6 If we truly love God, our sins will be forgiven; if we show him respect, we will keep away from sin.
Prv16:7 When we please the Lord , even our enemies make friends with us.
Prv16:8 It's better to be honest and poor than to be dishonest and rich.
Prv16:9 We make our own plans, but the Lord decides where we will go.
Prv16:10 Rulers speak with authority and are never wrong.
Prv16:11 The Lord doesn't like it when we cheat in business.
Prv16:12 Justice makes rulers powerful. They should hate evil
Prv16:13 and like honesty and truth.
Prv16:14 An angry ruler can put you to death. So be wise! Don't make one angry.
Prv16:15 When a ruler is happy and pleased with you, it's like refreshing rain, and you will live.
Prv16:16 It's much better to be wise and sensible than to be rich.
Prv16:17 God's people avoid evil ways, and they protect themselves by watching where they go.
Prv16:18 Too much pride will destroy you.
Prv16:19 You are better off to be humble and poor than to get rich from what you take by force.
Prv16:20 If you know what you're doing, you will prosper. God blesses everyone who trusts him.
Prv16:21 Good judgment proves that you are wise, and if you speak kindly, you can teach others.
Prv16:22 Good sense is a fountain that gives life, but fools are punished by their foolishness.
Prv16:23 You can persuade others if you are wise and speak sensibly.
Prv16:24 Kind words are like honey -  they cheer you up and make you feel strong.
Prv16:25 Sometimes what seems right is really a road to death.
Prv16:26 The hungrier you are, the harder you work.
Prv16:27 Worthless people plan trouble. Even their words burn like a flaming fire.
Prv16:28 Gossip is no good! It causes hard feelings and comes between friends.
Prv16:29 Don't trust violent people. They will mislead you to do the wrong thing.
Prv16:30 When someone winks or grins behind your back, trouble is on the way.
Prv16:31 Gray hair is a glorious crown worn by those who have lived right.
Prv16:32 Controlling your temper is better than being a hero who captures a city.
Prv16:33 We make our own decisions, but the Lord alone determines what happens.
Prv17:1 A dry crust of bread eaten in peace and quiet is better than a feast eaten where everyone argues.
Prv17:2 A hard-working slave will be placed in charge of a no-good child, and that slave will be given the same inheritance that each child receives.
Prv17:3 Silver and gold are tested by flames of fire; our thoughts are tested by the Lord .
Prv17:4 Troublemakers listen to troublemakers, and liars listen to liars.
Prv17:5 By insulting the poor, you insult your Creator. You will be punished if you make fun of someone in trouble.
Prv17:6 Grandparents are proud of their grandchildren, and children should be proud of their parents.
Prv17:7 It sounds strange for a fool to talk sensibly, but it's even worse for a ruler to tell lies.
Prv17:8 A bribe works miracles like a magic charm that brings good luck.
Prv17:9 You will keep your friends if you forgive them, but you will lose your friends if you keep talking about what they did wrong.
Prv17:10 A sensible person accepts correction, but you can't beat sense into a fool.
Prv17:11 Cruel people want to rebel, and so vicious attackers will be sent against them.
Prv17:12 A bear robbed of her cubs is far less dangerous than a stubborn fool.
Prv17:13 You will always have trouble if you are mean to those who are good to you.
Prv17:14 The start of an argument is like a water leak -  so stop it before real trouble breaks out.
Prv17:15 The Lord doesn't like those who defend the guilty or condemn the innocent.
Prv17:16 Why should fools have money for an education when they refuse to learn?
Prv17:17 A friend is always a friend, and relatives are born to share our troubles.
Prv17:18 It's stupid to guarantee someone else's loan.
Prv17:19 The wicked and the proud love trouble and keep begging to be hurt.
Prv17:20 Dishonesty does you no good, and telling lies will get you in trouble.
Prv17:21 It's never pleasant to be the parent of a fool and have nothing but pain.
Prv17:22 If you are cheerful, you feel good; if you are sad, you hurt all over.
Prv17:23 Crooks accept secret bribes to keep justice from being done.
Prv17:24 Anyone with wisdom knows what makes good sense, but fools can never make up their minds.
Prv17:25 Foolish children bring sorrow to their father and pain to their mother.
Prv17:26 It isn't fair to punish the innocent and those who do right.
Prv17:27 It makes a lot of sense to be a person of few words and to stay calm.
Prv17:28 Even fools seem smart when they are quiet.
Prv18:1 It's selfish and stupid to think only of yourself and to sneer at people who have sense.
Prv18:2 Fools have no desire to learn; they would much rather give their own opinion.
Prv18:3 Wrongdoing leads to shame and disgrace.
Prv18:4 Words of wisdom are a stream that flows from a deep fountain.
Prv18:5 It's wrong to favor the guilty and keep the innocent from getting justice.
Prv18:6 Foolish talk will get you into a lot of trouble.
Prv18:7 Saying foolish things is like setting a trap to destroy yourself.
Prv18:8 There's nothing so delicious as the taste of gossip! It melts in your mouth.
Prv18:9 Being lazy is no different from being a troublemaker.
Prv18:10 The Lord is a mighty tower where his people can run for safety - 
Prv18:11 the rich think their money is a wall of protection.
Prv18:12 Pride leads to destruction; humility leads to honor.
Prv18:13 It's stupid and embarrassing to give an answer before you listen.
Prv18:14 Being cheerful helps when we are sick, but nothing helps when we give up.
Prv18:15 Everyone with good sense wants to learn.
Prv18:16 A gift will get you in to see anyone.
Prv18:17 You may think you have won your case in court, until your opponent speaks.
Prv18:18 Drawing straws is one way to settle a difficult case.
Prv18:19 Making up with a friend you have offended is harder than breaking through a city wall.
Prv18:20 Make your words good -  you will be glad you did.
Prv18:21 Words can bring death or life! Talk too much, and you will eat everything you say.
Prv18:22 A man's greatest treasure is his wife -  she is a gift from the Lord .
Prv18:23 The poor must beg for help, but the rich can give a harsh reply.
Prv18:24 Some friends don't help, but a true friend is closer than your own family.
Prv19:1 It's better to be poor and live right than to be a stupid liar.
Prv19:2 Willingness and stupidity don't go well together. If you are too eager, you will miss the road.
Prv19:3 We are ruined by our own stupidity, though we blame the Lord .
Prv19:4 The rich have many friends; the poor have none.
Prv19:5 Dishonest witnesses and liars won't escape punishment.
Prv19:6 Everyone tries to be friends of those who can help them.
Prv19:7 If you are poor, your own relatives reject you, and your friends are worse. When you really need them, they are not there.
Prv19:8 Do yourself a favor by having good sense -  you will be glad you did.
Prv19:9 Dishonest witnesses and liars will be destroyed.
Prv19:10 It isn't right for a fool to live in luxury or for a slave to rule in place of a king.
Prv19:11 It's wise to be patient and show what you are like by forgiving others.
Prv19:12 An angry king roars like a lion, but when a king is pleased, it's like dew on the crops.
Prv19:13 A foolish son brings disgrace to his father. A nagging wife goes on and on like the drip, drip, drip of the rain.
Prv19:14 You may inherit all you own from your parents, but a sensible wife is a gift from the Lord .
Prv19:15 If you are lazy and sleep your time away, you will starve.
Prv19:16 Obey the Lord's teachings and you will live -  disobey and you will die.
Prv19:17 Caring for the poor is lending to the Lord , and you will be well repaid.
Prv19:18 Correct your children before it's too late; if you don't punish them, you are destroying them.
Prv19:19 People with bad tempers are always in trouble, and they need help over and over again.
Prv19:20 Pay attention to advice and accept correction, so you can live sensibly.
Prv19:21 We may make a lot of plans, but the Lord will do what he has decided.
Prv19:22 What matters most is loyalty. It's better to be poor than to be a liar.
Prv19:23 Showing respect to the Lord brings true life -  if you do it, you can relax without fear of danger.
Prv19:24 Some people are too lazy to lift a hand to feed themselves.
Prv19:25 Stupid fools learn good sense by seeing others punished; a sensible person learns by being corrected.
Prv19:26 Children who bring disgrace rob their father and chase their mother away.
Prv19:27 If you stop learning, you will forget what you already know.
Prv19:28 A lying witness makes fun of the court system, and criminals think crime is really delicious.
Prv19:29 Every stupid fool is just waiting to be punished.
Prv20:1 It isn't smart to get drunk! Drinking makes a fool of you and leads to fights.
Prv20:2 An angry ruler is like a roaring lion -  make either one angry, and you are dead.
Prv20:3 It makes you look good when you avoid a fight -  only fools love to quarrel.
Prv20:4 If you are too lazy to plow, don't expect a harvest.
Prv20:5 Someone's thoughts may be as deep as the ocean, but if you are smart, you will discover them.
Prv20:6 There are many who say, "You can trust me!" But can they be trusted?
Prv20:7 Good people live right, and God blesses the children who follow their example.
Prv20:8 When rulers decide cases, they weigh the evidence.
Prv20:9 Can any of us really say, "My thoughts are pure, and my sins are gone"?
Prv20:10 Two things the Lord hates are dishonest scales and dishonest measures.
Prv20:11 The good or bad that children do shows what they are like.
Prv20:12 Hearing and seeing are gifts from the Lord .
Prv20:13 If you sleep all the time, you will starve; if you get up and work, you will have enough food.
Prv20:14 Everyone likes to brag about getting a bargain.
Prv20:15 Sensible words are better than gold or jewels.
Prv20:16 You deserve to lose your coat if you loan it to someone to guarantee payment for the debt of a stranger.
Prv20:17 The food you get by cheating may taste delicious, but it turns to gravel.
Prv20:18 Be sure you have sound advice before making plans or starting a war.
Prv20:19 Stay away from gossips -  they tell everything.
Prv20:20 Children who curse their parents will go to the land of darkness long before their time.
Prv20:21 Getting rich quick may turn out to be a curse.
Prv20:22 Don't try to get even. Trust the Lord , and he will help you.
Prv20:23 The Lord hates dishonest scales and dishonest weights. So don't cheat!
Prv20:24 How can we know what will happen to us when the Lord alone decides?
Prv20:25 Don't fall into the trap of making promises to God before you think!
Prv20:26 A wise ruler severely punishes every criminal.
Prv20:27 Our inner thoughts are a lamp from the Lord , and they search our hearts.
Prv20:28 Rulers are protected by God's mercy and loyalty, but they must be merciful for their kingdoms to last.
Prv20:29 Young people take pride in their strength, but the gray hairs of wisdom are even more beautiful.
Prv20:30 A severe beating can knock all of the evil out of you!
Prv21:1 The Lord controls rulers, just as he determines the course of rivers.
Prv21:2 We may think we are doing the right thing, but the Lord always knows what is in our hearts.
Prv21:3 Doing what is right and fair pleases the Lord more than an offering.
Prv21:4 Evil people are proud and arrogant, but sin is the only crop they produce.
Prv21:5 If you plan and work hard, you will have plenty; if you get in a hurry, you will end up poor.
Prv21:6 Cheating to get rich is a foolish dream and no less than suicide.
Prv21:7 You destroy yourself by being cruel and violent and refusing to live right.
Prv21:8 All crooks are liars, but anyone who is innocent will do right.
Prv21:9 It's better to stay outside on the roof of your house than to live inside with a nagging wife.
Prv21:10 Evil people want to do wrong, even to their friends.
Prv21:11 An ignorant fool learns by seeing others punished; a sensible person learns by being instructed.
Prv21:12 God is always fair! He knows what the wicked do and will punish them.
Prv21:13 If you won't help the poor, don't expect to be heard when you cry out for help.
Prv21:14 A secret bribe will save you from someone's fierce anger.
Prv21:15 When justice is done, good citizens are glad and crooks are terrified.
Prv21:16 If you stop using good sense, you will find yourself in the grave.
Prv21:17 Heavy drinkers and others who live only for pleasure will lose all they have.
Prv21:18 God's people will escape, but all who are wicked will pay the price.
Prv21:19 It's better out in the desert than at home with a nagging, complaining wife.
Prv21:20 Be sensible and store up precious treasures -  don't waste them like a fool.
Prv21:21 If you try to be kind and good, you will be blessed with life and goodness and honor.
Prv21:22 One wise person can defeat a city full of soldiers and capture their fortress.
Prv21:23 Watching what you say can save you a lot of trouble.
Prv21:24 If you are proud and conceited, everyone will say, "You're a snob!"
Prv21:25 If you want too much and are too lazy to work, it could be fatal.
Prv21:26 But people who obey God are always generous.
Prv21:27 The Lord despises the offerings of wicked people with evil motives.
Prv21:28 If you tell lies in court, you are done for; only a reliable witness can do the job.
Prv21:29 Wicked people bluff their way, but God's people think before they take a step.
Prv21:30 No matter how much you know or what plans you make, you can't defeat the Lord .
Prv21:31 Even if your army has horses ready for battle, the Lord will always win.
Prv22:1 A good reputation and respect are worth much more than silver and gold.
Prv22:2 The rich and the poor are all created by the Lord .
Prv22:3 When you see trouble coming, don't be stupid and walk right into it -  be smart and hide.
Prv22:4 Respect and serve the Lord ! Your reward will be wealth, a long life, and honor.
Prv22:5 Crooks walk down a road full of thorny traps. Stay away from there!
Prv22:6 Teach your children right from wrong, and when they are grown they will still do right.
Prv22:7 The poor are ruled by the rich, and those who borrow are slaves of moneylenders.
Prv22:8 Troublemakers get in trouble, and their terrible anger will get them nowhere.
Prv22:9 The Lord blesses everyone who freely gives food to the poor.
Prv22:10 Arguments and fights will come to an end, if you chase away those who insult others.
Prv22:11 The king is the friend of all who are sincere and speak with kindness.
Prv22:12 The Lord watches over everyone who shows good sense, but he frustrates the plans of deceitful liars.
Prv22:13 Don't be so lazy that you say, "If I go to work, a lion will eat me!"
Prv22:14 The words of a bad woman are like a deep pit; if you make the Lord angry, you will fall right in.
Prv22:15 All children are foolish, but firm correction will make them change.
Prv22:16 Cheat the poor to make profit or give gifts to the rich -  either way you lose.
Prv22:17 Here are some sayings of people with wisdom, so listen carefully as I teach.
Prv22:18 You will be glad that you know these sayings and can recite them.
Prv22:19 I am teaching them today, so that you may trust the Lord .
Prv22:20 I have written thirty sayings filled with sound advice.
Prv22:21 You can trust them completely to give you the right words for those in charge of you.
Prv22:22 Don't take advantage of the poor or cheat them in court.
Prv22:23 The Lord is their defender, and what you do to them, he will do to you.
Prv22:24 Don't make friends with anyone who has a bad temper.
Prv22:25 You might turn out like them and get caught in a trap.
Prv22:26 Don't guarantee to pay someone else's debt.
Prv22:27 If you don't have the money, you might lose your bed.
Prv22:28 Don't move a boundary marker set up by your ancestors.
Prv22:29 If you do your job well, you will work for a ruler and never be a slave.
Prv23:1 When you are invited to eat with a king, use your best manners.
Prv23:2 Don't go and stuff yourself! That would be just the same as cutting your throat.
Prv23:3 Don't be greedy for all of that fancy food! It may not be so tasty.
Prv23:4 Give up trying so hard to get rich.
Prv23:5 Your money flies away before you know it, just like an eagle suddenly taking off.
Prv23:6 Don't accept an invitation to eat a selfish person's food, no matter how good it is.
Prv23:7 People like that take note of how much you eat. They say, "Take all you want!" But they don't mean it.
Prv23:8 Each bite will come back up, and all your kind words will be wasted.
Prv23:9 Don't talk to fools -  they will just make fun.
Prv23:10 Don't move a boundary marker or take the land that belongs to orphans.
Prv23:11 God All-Powerful is there to defend them against you.
Prv23:12 Listen to instruction and do your best to learn.
Prv23:13 Don't fail to correct your children. You won't kill them by being firm,
Prv23:14 and it may even save their lives.
Prv23:15 My children, if you show good sense, I will be happy,
Prv23:16 and if you are truthful, I will really be glad.
Prv23:17 Don't be jealous of sinners, but always honor the Lord .
Prv23:18 Then you will truly have hope for the future.
Prv23:19 Listen to me, my children! Be wise and have enough sense to follow the right path.
Prv23:20 Don't be a heavy drinker or stuff yourself with food.
Prv23:21 It will make you feel drowsy, and you will end up poor with only rags to wear.
Prv23:22 Pay attention to your father, and don't neglect your mother when she grows old.
Prv23:23 Invest in truth and wisdom, discipline and good sense, and don't part with them.
Prv23:24 Make your father truly happy by living right and showing sound judgment.
Prv23:25 Make your parents proud, especially your mother.
Prv23:26 My son, pay close attention, and gladly follow my example.
Prv23:27 Bad women and unfaithful wives are like a deep pit - 
Prv23:28 they are waiting to attack you like a gang of robbers with victim after victim.
Prv23:29 Who is always in trouble? Who argues and fights? Who has cuts and bruises? Whose eyes are red?
Prv23:30 Everyone who stays up late, having just one more drink.
Prv23:31 Don't even look at that colorful stuff bubbling up in the glass! It goes down so easily,
Prv23:32 but later it bites like a poisonous snake.
Prv23:33 You will see weird things, and your mind will play tricks on you.
Prv23:34 You will feel tossed about like someone trying to sleep on a ship in a storm.
Prv23:35 You will be bruised all over, without even remembering how it all happened. And you will lie awake asking, "When will morning come, so I can drink some more?"
Prv24:1 Don't be jealous of crooks or want to be their friends.
Prv24:2 All they think about and talk about is violence and cruelty.
Prv24:3 Use wisdom and understanding to establish your home;
Prv24:4 let good sense fill the rooms with priceless treasures.
Prv24:5 Wisdom brings strength, and knowledge gives power.
Prv24:6 Battles are won by listening to advice and making a lot of plans.
Prv24:7 Wisdom is too much for fools! Their advice is no good.
Prv24:8 No one but troublemakers think up trouble.
Prv24:9 Everyone hates senseless fools who think up ways to sin.
Prv24:10 Don't give up and be helpless in times of trouble.
Prv24:11 Don't fail to rescue those who are doomed to die.
Prv24:12 Don't say, "I didn't know it!" God can read your mind. He watches each of us and knows our thoughts. And God will pay us back for what we do.
Prv24:13 Honey is good for you, my children, and it tastes sweet.
Prv24:14 Wisdom is like honey for your life -  if you find it, your future is bright.
Prv24:15 Don't be a cruel person who attacks good people and hurts their families.
Prv24:16 Even if good people fall seven times, they will get back up. But when trouble strikes the wicked, that's the end of them.
Prv24:17 Don't be happy to see your enemies trip and fall down.
Prv24:18 The Lord will find out and be unhappy. Then he will stop being angry with them.
Prv24:19 Don't let evil people worry you or make you jealous.
Prv24:20 They will soon be gone like the flame of a lamp that burns out.
Prv24:21 My children, you must respect the Lord and the king, and you must not make friends with anyone who rebels against either of them.
Prv24:22 Who knows what sudden disaster the Lord or a ruler might bring?
Prv24:23 Here are some more sayings that make good sense: When you judge, you must be fair.
Prv24:24 If you let the guilty go free, people of all nations will hate and curse you.
Prv24:25 But if you punish the guilty, things will go well for you, and you will prosper.
Prv24:26 Giving an honest answer is a sign of true friendship.
Prv24:27 Get your fields ready and plant your crops before starting a home.
Prv24:28 Don't accuse anyone who isn't guilty. Don't ever tell a lie
Prv24:29 or say to someone, "I'll get even with you!"
Prv24:30 I once walked by the field and the vineyard of a lazy fool.
Prv24:31 Thorns and weeds were everywhere, and the stone wall had fallen down.
Prv24:32 When I saw this, it taught me a lesson:
Prv24:33 Sleep a little. Doze a little. Fold your hands and twiddle your thumbs.
Prv24:34 Suddenly poverty hits you and everything is gone!
Prv25:1 Here are more of Solomon's proverbs. They were copied by the officials of King Hezekiah of Judah.
Prv25:2 God is praised for being mysterious; rulers are praised for explaining mysteries.
Prv25:3 Who can fully understand the thoughts of a ruler? They reach beyond the sky and go deep in the earth.
Prv25:4 Silver must be purified before it can be used to make something of value.
Prv25:5 Evil people must be removed before anyone can rule with justice.
Prv25:6 Don't try to seem important in the court of a ruler.
Prv25:7 It's better for the ruler to give you a high position than for you to be embarrassed in front of royal officials. Be sure you are right
Prv25:8 before you sue someone, or you might lose your case and be embarrassed.
Prv25:9 When you and someone else can't get along, don't gossip about it.
Prv25:10 Others will find out, and your reputation will then be ruined.
Prv25:11 The right word at the right time is like precious gold set in silver.
Prv25:12 Listening to good advice is worth much more than jewelry made of gold.
Prv25:13 A messenger you can trust is just as refreshing as cool water in summer.
Prv25:14 Broken promises are worse than rain clouds that don't bring rain.
Prv25:15 Patience and gentle talk can convince a ruler and overcome any problem.
Prv25:16 Eating too much honey can make you sick.
Prv25:17 Don't visit friends too often, or they will get tired of it and start hating you.
Prv25:18 Telling lies about friends is like attacking them with clubs and swords and sharp arrows.
Prv25:19 A friend you can't trust in times of trouble is like having a toothache or a sore foot.
Prv25:20 Singing to someone in deep sorrow is like pouring vinegar in an open cut.
Prv25:21 If your enemies are hungry, give them something to eat. And if they are thirsty, give them something to drink.
Prv25:22 This will be the same as piling burning coals on their heads. And the Lord will reward you.
Prv25:23 As surely as rain blows in from the north, anger is caused by cruel words.
Prv25:24 It's better to stay outside on the roof of your house than to live inside with a nagging wife.
Prv25:25 Good news from far away refreshes like cold water when you are thirsty.
Prv25:26 When a good person gives in to the wicked, it's like dumping garbage in a stream of clear water.
Prv25:27 Don't eat too much honey or always want praise.
Prv25:28 Losing self-control leaves you as helpless as a city without a wall.
Prv26:1 Expecting snow in summer and rain in the dry season makes more sense than honoring a fool.
Prv26:2 A curse you don't deserve will take wings and fly away like a sparrow or a swallow.
Prv26:3 Horses and donkeys must be beaten and bridled -  and so must fools.
Prv26:4 Don't make a fool of yourself by answering a fool.
Prv26:5 But if you answer any fools, show how foolish they are, so they won't feel smart.
Prv26:6 Sending a message by a fool is like chopping off your foot and drinking poison.
Prv26:7 A fool with words of wisdom is like an athlete with legs that can't move.
Prv26:8 Are you going to honor a fool? Why not shoot a slingshot with the rock tied tight?
Prv26:9 A thornbush waved around in the hand of a drunkard is no worse than a proverb in the mouth of a fool.
Prv26:10 It's no smarter to shoot arrows at every passerby than it is to hire a bunch of worthless nobodies.
Prv26:11 Dogs return to eat their vomit, just as fools repeat their foolishness.
Prv26:12 There is more hope for a fool than for someone who says, "I'm really smart!"
Prv26:13 Don't be lazy and keep saying, "There's a lion outside!"
Prv26:14 A door turns on its hinges, but a lazy person just turns over in bed.
Prv26:15 Some of us are so lazy that we won't lift a hand to feed ourselves.
Prv26:16 A lazy person says, "I am smarter than everyone else."
Prv26:17 It's better to take hold of a mad dog by the ears than to take part in someone else's argument.
Prv26:18 It's no crazier to shoot sharp and flaming arrows
Prv26:19 than to cheat someone and say, "I was only fooling!"
Prv26:20 Where there is no fuel a fire goes out; where there is no gossip arguments come to an end.
Prv26:21 Troublemakers start trouble, just as sparks and fuel start a fire.
Prv26:22 There is nothing so delicious as the taste of gossip! It melts in your mouth.
Prv26:23 Hiding hateful thoughts behind smooth talk is like coating a clay pot with a cheap glaze.
Prv26:24 The pleasant talk of an enemy hides more evil plans
Prv26:25 than can be counted -  so don't believe a word!
Prv26:26 Everyone will see through those evil plans.
Prv26:27 If you dig a pit, you will fall in; if you start a stone rolling, it will roll back on you.
Prv26:28 Watch out for anyone who tells lies and flatters -  they are out to get you.
Prv27:1 Don't brag about tomorrow! Each day brings its own surprises.
Prv27:2 Don't brag about yourself -  let others praise you.
Prv27:3 Stones and sand are heavy, but trouble caused by a fool is a much heavier load.
Prv27:4 An angry person is dangerous, but a jealous person is even worse.
Prv27:5 A truly good friend will openly correct you.
Prv27:6 You can trust a friend who corrects you, but kisses from an enemy are nothing but lies.
Prv27:7 If you have had enough to eat, honey doesn't taste good, but if you are really hungry, you will eat anything.
Prv27:8 When you are far from home, you feel like a bird without a nest.
Prv27:9 The sweet smell of incense can make you feel good, but true friendship is better still.
Prv27:10 Don't desert an old friend of your family or visit your relatives when you are in trouble. A friend nearby is better than relatives far away.
Prv27:11 My child, show good sense! Then I will be happy and able to answer anyone who criticizes me.
Prv27:12 Be cautious and hide when you see danger -  don't be stupid and walk right into trouble.
Prv27:13 Don't loan money to a stranger unless you are given something to guarantee payment.
Prv27:14 A loud greeting early in the morning is the same as a curse.
Prv27:15 The steady dripping of rain and the nagging of a wife are one and the same.
Prv27:16 It's easier to catch the wind or hold olive oil in your hand than to stop a nagging wife.
Prv27:17 Just as iron sharpens iron, friends sharpen the minds of each other.
Prv27:18 Take care of a tree, and you will eat its fruit; look after your master, and you will be praised.
Prv27:19 You see your face in a mirror and your thoughts in the minds of others.
Prv27:20 Death and the grave are never satisfied, and neither are we.
Prv27:21 Gold and silver are tested in a red-hot furnace, but we are tested by praise.
Prv27:22 No matter how hard you beat a fool, you can't pound out the foolishness.
Prv27:23 You should take good care of your sheep and goats,
Prv27:24 because wealth and honor don't last forever.
Prv27:25 After the hay is cut and the new growth appears and the harvest is over,
Prv27:26 you can sell lambs and goats to buy clothes and land.
Prv27:27 From the milk of the goats, you can make enough cheese to feed your family and all your servants.
Prv28:1 Wicked people run away when no one chases them, but those who live right are as brave as lions.
Prv28:2 In time of civil war there are many leaders, but a sensible leader restores law and order.
Prv28:3 When someone poor takes over and mistreats the poor, it's like a heavy rain destroying the crops.
Prv28:4 Lawbreakers praise criminals, but law-abiding citizens always oppose them.
Prv28:5 Criminals don't know what justice means, but all who respect the Lord understand it completely.
Prv28:6 It's better to be poor and live right, than to be rich and dishonest.
Prv28:7 It makes good sense to obey the Law of God, but you disgrace your parents if you make friends with worthless nobodies.
Prv28:8 If you make money by charging high interest rates, you will lose it all to someone who cares for the poor.
Prv28:9 God cannot stand the prayers of anyone who disobeys his Law.
Prv28:10 By leading good people to sin, you dig a pit for yourself, but all who live right will have a bright future.
Prv28:11 The rich think highly of themselves, but anyone poor and sensible sees right through them.
Prv28:12 When an honest person wins, it's time to celebrate; when crooks are in control, it's best to hide.
Prv28:13 If you don't confess your sins, you will be a failure. But God will be merciful if you confess your sins and give them up.
Prv28:14 The Lord blesses everyone who is afraid to do evil, but if you are cruel, you will end up in trouble.
Prv28:15 A ruler who mistreats the poor is like a roaring lion or a bear hunting for food.
Prv28:16 A heartless leader is a fool, but anyone who refuses to get rich by cheating others will live a long time.
Prv28:17 Don't give help to murderers! Make them stay on the run for as long as they live.
Prv28:18 Honesty will keep you safe, but everyone who is crooked will suddenly fall.
Prv28:19 Work hard, and you will have a lot of food; waste time, and you will have a lot of trouble.
Prv28:20 God blesses his loyal people, but punishes all who want to get rich quick.
Prv28:21 It isn't right to be unfair, but some people can be bribed with only a piece of bread.
Prv28:22 Don't be selfish and eager to get rich -  you will end up worse off than you can imagine.
Prv28:23 Honest correction is appreciated more than flattery.
Prv28:24 If you cheat your parents and don't think it's wrong, you are a common thief.
Prv28:25 Selfish people cause trouble, but you will live a full life if you trust the Lord .
Prv28:26 Only fools would trust what they alone think, but if you live by wisdom, you will do all right.
Prv28:27 Giving to the poor will keep you from poverty, but if you close your eyes to their needs, everyone will curse you.
Prv28:28 When crooks are in control, everyone tries to hide, but when they lose power, good people are everywhere.
Prv29:1 If you keep being stubborn after many warnings, you will suddenly discover you have gone too far.
Prv29:2 When justice rules a nation, everyone is glad; when injustice rules, everyone groans.
Prv29:3 If you love wisdom your parents will be glad, but chasing after bad women will cost you everything.
Prv29:4 An honest ruler makes the nation strong; a ruler who takes bribes will bring it to ruin.
Prv29:5 Flattery is nothing less than setting a trap.
Prv29:6 Your sins will catch you, but everyone who lives right will sing and celebrate.
Prv29:7 The wicked don't care about the rights of the poor, but good people do.
Prv29:8 Sneering at others is a spark that sets a city on fire; using good sense can put out the flames of anger.
Prv29:9 Be wise and don't sue a fool. You won't get satisfaction, because all the fool will do is sneer and shout.
Prv29:10 A murderer hates everyone who is honest and lives right.
Prv29:11 Don't be a fool and quickly lose your temper -  be sensible and patient.
Prv29:12 A ruler who listens to lies will have corrupt officials.
Prv29:13 The poor and all who abuse them must each depend on God for light.
Prv29:14 Kings who are fair to the poor will rule forever.
Prv29:15 Correct your children, and they will be wise; children out of control disgrace their mothers.
Prv29:16 Crime increases when crooks are in power, but law-abiding citizens will see them fall.
Prv29:17 If you correct your children, they will bring you peace and happiness.
Prv29:18 Without guidance from God law and order disappear, but God blesses everyone who obeys his Law.
Prv29:19 Even when servants are smart, it takes more than words to make them obey.
Prv29:20 There is more hope for a fool than for someone who speaks without thinking.
Prv29:21 Slaves that you treat kindly from their childhood will cause you sorrow.
Prv29:22 A person with a quick temper stirs up arguments and commits a lot of sins.
Prv29:23 Too much pride brings disgrace; humility leads to honor.
Prv29:24 If you take part in a crime you are your worst enemy, because even under oath you can't tell the truth.
Prv29:25 Don't fall into the trap of being a coward -  trust the Lord , and you will be safe.
Prv29:26 Many try to make friends with a ruler, but justice comes from the Lord .
Prv29:27 Good people and criminals can't stand each other.
Prv30:1 These are the sayings and the message of Agur son of Jakeh. Someone cries out to God, "I am completely worn out! How can I last?
Prv30:2 I am far too stupid to be considered human.
Prv30:3 I never was wise, and I don't understand what God is like."
Prv30:4 Has anyone gone up to heaven and come back down? Has anyone grabbed hold of the wind? Has anyone wrapped up the sea or marked out boundaries for the earth? If you know of any who have done such things, then tell me their names and their children's names.
Prv30:5 Everything God says is true -  and it's a shield for all who come to him for safety.
Prv30:6 Don't change what God has said! He will correct you and show that you are a liar.
Prv30:7 There are two things, Lord, I want you to do for me before I die:
Prv30:8 Make me absolutely honest and don't let me be too poor or too rich. Give me just what I need.
Prv30:9 If I have too much to eat, I might forget about you; if I don't have enough, I might steal and disgrace your name.
Prv30:10 Don't tell a slave owner something bad about one of the slaves. That slave will curse you, and you will be in trouble.
Prv30:11 Some people curse their father and even their mother;
Prv30:12 others think they are perfect, but they are stained by sin.
Prv30:13 Some people are stuck-up and act like snobs;
Prv30:14 others are so greedy that they gobble down the poor and homeless.
Prv30:15 Greed has twins, each named "Give me!" There are three or four things that are never satisfied:
Prv30:16 The world of the dead and a childless wife, the thirsty earth and a flaming fire.
Prv30:17 Don't make fun of your father or disobey your mother -  crows will peck out your eyes, and buzzards will eat the rest of you.
Prv30:18 There are three or four things I cannot understand:
Prv30:19 How eagles fly so high or snakes crawl on rocks, how ships sail the ocean or people fall in love.
Prv30:20 An unfaithful wife says, "Sleeping with another man is as natural as eating."
Prv30:21 There are three or four things that make the earth tremble and are unbearable:
Prv30:22 A slave who becomes king, a fool who eats too much,
Prv30:23 a hateful woman who finds a husband, and a slave who takes the place of the woman who owns her.
Prv30:24 On this earth four things are small but very wise:
Prv30:25 Ants, who seem to be feeble, but store up food all summer long;
Prv30:26 badgers, who seem to be weak, but live among the rocks;
Prv30:27 locusts, who have no king, but march like an army;
Prv30:28 lizards, which can be caught in your hand, but sneak into palaces.
Prv30:29 Three or four creatures really strut around:
Prv30:30 Those fearless lions who rule the jungle,
Prv30:31 those proud roosters, those mountain goats, and those rulers who have no enemies.
Prv30:32 If you are foolishly bragging or planning something evil, then stop it now!
Prv30:33 If you churn milk you get butter; if you pound on your nose, you get blood -  and if you stay angry, you get in trouble.
Prv31:1 These are the sayings that King Lemuel of Massa was taught by his mother.
Prv31:2 My son Lemuel, you were born in answer to my prayers, so listen carefully.
Prv31:3 Don't waste your life chasing after women! This has ruined many kings.
Prv31:4 Kings and leaders should not get drunk or even want to drink.
Prv31:5 Drinking makes you forget your responsibilities, and you mistreat the poor.
Prv31:6 Beer and wine are only for the dying or for those who have lost all hope.
Prv31:7 Let them drink and forget how poor and miserable they feel.
Prv31:8 But you must defend those who are helpless and have no hope.
Prv31:9 Be fair and give justice to the poor and homeless.
Prv31:10 A truly good wife is the most precious treasure a man can find!
Prv31:11 Her husband depends on her, and she never lets him down.
Prv31:12 She is good to him every day of her life,
Prv31:13 and with her own hands she gladly makes clothes.
Prv31:14 She is like a sailing ship that brings food from across the sea.
Prv31:15 She gets up before daylight to prepare food for her family and for her servants.
Prv31:16 She knows how to buy land and how to plant a vineyard,
Prv31:17 and she always works hard.
Prv31:18 She knows when to buy or sell, and she stays busy until late at night.
Prv31:19 She spins her own cloth,
Prv31:20 and she helps the poor and the needy.
Prv31:21 Her family has warm clothing, and so she doesn't worry when it snows.
Prv31:22 She does her own sewing, and everything she wears is beautiful.
Prv31:23 Her husband is a well-known and respected leader in the city.
Prv31:24 She makes clothes to sell to the shop owners.
Prv31:25 She is strong and graceful, as well as cheerful about the future.
Prv31:26 Her words are sensible, and her advice is thoughtful.
Prv31:27 She takes good care of her family and is never lazy.
Prv31:28 Her children praise her, and with great pride her husband says,
Prv31:29 "There are many good women, but you are the best!"
Prv31:30 Charm can be deceiving, and beauty fades away, but a woman who honors the Lord deserves to be praised.
Prv31:31 Show her respect -  praise her in public for what she has done.
Eccl1:1 When the son of David was king in Jerusalem, he was known to be very wise, and he said:
Eccl1:2 Nothing makes sense! Everything is nonsense. I have seen it all -  nothing makes sense!
Eccl1:3 What is there to show for all of our hard work here on this earth?
Eccl1:4 People come, and people go, but still the world never changes.
Eccl1:5 The sun comes up, the sun goes down; it hurries right back to where it started from.
Eccl1:6 The wind blows south, the wind blows north; round and round it blows over and over again.
Eccl1:7 All rivers empty into the sea, but it never spills over; one by one the rivers return to their source.
Eccl1:8 All of life is far more boring than words could ever say. Our eyes and our ears are never satisfied with what we see and hear.
Eccl1:9 Everything that happens has happened before; nothing is new, nothing under the sun.
Eccl1:10 Someone might say, "Here is something new!" But it happened before, long before we were born.
Eccl1:11 No one who lived in the past is remembered anymore, and everyone yet to be born will be forgotten too.
Eccl1:12 I said these things when I lived in Jerusalem as king of Israel.
Eccl1:13 With all my wisdom I tried to understand everything that happens here on earth. And God has made this so hard for us humans to do.
Eccl1:14 I have seen it all, and everything is just as senseless as chasing the wind.
Eccl1:15 If something is crooked, it can't be made straight; if something isn't there, it can't be counted.
Eccl1:16 I said to myself, "You are by far the wisest person who has ever lived in Jerusalem. You are eager to learn, and you have learned a lot."
Eccl1:17 Then I decided to find out all I could about wisdom and foolishness. Soon I realized that this too was as senseless as chasing the wind. 
Eccl1:18 The more you know, the more you hurt; the more you understand, the more you suffer.
Eccl2:1 I said to myself, "Have fun and enjoy yourself!" But this didn't make sense.
Eccl2:2 Laughing and having fun is crazy. What good does it do?
Eccl2:3 I wanted to find out what was best for us during the short time we have on this earth. So I decided to make myself happy with wine and find out what it means to be foolish, without really being foolish myself.
Eccl2:4 I did some great things. I built houses and planted vineyards.
Eccl2:5 I had flower gardens and orchards full of fruit trees.
Eccl2:6 And I had pools where I could get water for the trees.
Eccl2:7 I owned slaves, and their sons and daughters became my slaves. I had more sheep and goats than anyone who had ever lived in Jerusalem.
Eccl2:8 Foreign rulers brought me silver, gold, and precious treasures. Men and women sang for me, and I had many wives who gave me great pleasure.
Eccl2:9 I was the most famous person who had ever lived in Jerusalem, and I was very wise.
Eccl2:10 I got whatever I wanted and did whatever made me happy. But most of all, I enjoyed my work.
Eccl2:11 Then I thought about everything I had done, including the hard work, and it was simply chasing the wind. Nothing on earth is worth the trouble.
Eccl2:12 I asked myself, "What can the next king do that I haven't done?" Then I decided to compare wisdom with foolishness and stupidity.
Eccl2:13 And I discovered that wisdom is better than foolishness, just as light is better than darkness.
Eccl2:14 Wisdom is like having two good eyes; foolishness leaves you in the dark. But wise or foolish, we all end up the same.
Eccl2:15 Finally, I said to myself, "Being wise got me nowhere! The same thing will happen to me that happens to fools. Nothing makes sense.
Eccl2:16 Wise or foolish, we all die and are soon forgotten."
Eccl2:17 This made me hate life. Everything we do is painful; it's just as senseless as chasing the wind.
Eccl2:18 Suddenly I realized that others would someday get everything I had worked for so hard, then I started hating it all.
Eccl2:19 Who knows if those people will be sensible or stupid? Either way, they will own everything I have earned by hard work and wisdom. It doesn't make sense.
Eccl2:20 I thought about all my hard work, and I felt depressed.
Eccl2:21 When we use our wisdom, knowledge, and skill to get what we own, why do we have to leave it to someone who didn't work for it? This is senseless and wrong.
Eccl2:22 What do we really gain from all of our hard work?
Eccl2:23 Our bodies ache during the day, and work is torture. Then at night our thoughts are troubled. It just doesn't make sense.
Eccl2:24 The best thing we can do is to enjoy eating, drinking, and working. I believe these are God's gifts to us,
Eccl2:25 and no one enjoys eating and living more than I do.
Eccl2:26 If we please God, he will make us wise, understanding, and happy. But if we sin, God will make us struggle for a living, then he will give all we own to someone who pleases him. This makes no more sense than chasing the wind.
Eccl3:1 Everything on earth has its own time and its own season.
Eccl3:2 There is a time for birth and death, planting and reaping,
Eccl3:3 for killing and healing, destroying and building,
Eccl3:4 for crying and laughing, weeping and dancing,
Eccl3:5 for throwing stones and gathering stones, embracing and parting.
Eccl3:6 There is a time for finding and losing, keeping and giving,
Eccl3:7 for tearing and sewing, listening and speaking.
Eccl3:8 There is also a time for love and hate, for war and peace.
Eccl3:9 What do we gain by all of our hard work?
Eccl3:10 I have seen what difficult things God demands of us.
Eccl3:11 God makes everything happen at the right time. Yet none of us can ever fully understand all he has done, and he puts questions in our minds about the past and the future.
Eccl3:12 I know the best thing we can do is to always enjoy life,
Eccl3:13 because God's gift to us is the happiness we get from our food and drink and from the work we do.
Eccl3:14 Everything God has done will last forever; nothing he does can ever be changed. God has done all this, so that we will worship him.
Eccl3:15 Everything that happens has happened before, and all that will be has already been -  God does everything over and over again.
Eccl3:16 Everywhere on earth I saw violence and injustice instead of fairness and justice.
Eccl3:17 So I told myself that God has set a time and a place for everything. He will judge everyone, both the wicked and the good.
Eccl3:18 I know that God is testing us to show us that we are merely animals.
Eccl3:19 Like animals we breathe and die, and we are no better off than they are. It just doesn't make sense.
Eccl3:20 All living creatures go to the same place. We are made from earth, and we return to the earth.
Eccl3:21 Who really knows if our spirits go up and the spirits of animals go down into the earth?
Eccl3:22 We were meant to enjoy our work, and that's the best thing we can do. We can never know the future.
Eccl4:1 I looked again and saw people being mistreated everywhere on earth. They were crying, but no one was there to offer comfort, and those who mistreated them were powerful.
Eccl4:2 I said to myself, "The dead are better off than the living.
Eccl4:3 But those who have never been born are better off than anyone else, because they have never seen the terrible things that happen on this earth."
Eccl4:4 Then I realized that we work and do wonderful things just because we are jealous of others. This makes no more sense than chasing the wind.
Eccl4:5 Fools will fold their hands and starve to death.
Eccl4:6 Yet a very little food eaten in peace is better than twice as much earned from overwork and chasing the wind.
Eccl4:7 Once again I saw that nothing on earth makes sense.
Eccl4:8 For example, some people don't have friends or family. But they are never satisfied with what they own, and they never stop working to get more. They should ask themselves, "Why am I always working to have more? Who will get what I leave behind?" What a senseless and miserable life!
Eccl4:9 You are better off to have a friend than to be all alone, because then you will get more enjoyment out of what you earn.
Eccl4:10 If you fall, your friend can help you up. But if you fall without having a friend nearby, you are really in trouble.
Eccl4:11 If you sleep alone, you won't have anyone to keep you warm on a cold night.
Eccl4:12 Someone might be able to beat up one of you, but not both of you. As the saying goes, "A rope made from three strands of cord is hard to break."
Eccl4:13 You may be poor and young. But if you are wise, you are better off than a foolish old king who won't listen to advice.
Eccl4:14 Even if you were not born into the royal family and have been a prisoner and poor, you can still be king.
Eccl4:15 I once saw everyone in the world follow a young leader who came to power after the king was gone.
Eccl4:16 His followers could not even be counted. But years from now, no one will praise him - this makes no more sense than chasing the wind. 
Eccl5:1 Be careful what you do when you enter the house of God. Some fools go there to offer sacrifices, even though they haven't sinned. But it's best just to listen when you go to worship.
Eccl5:2 Don't talk before you think or make promises to God without thinking them through. God is in heaven, and you are on earth, so don't talk too much.
Eccl5:3 If you keep thinking about something, you will dream about it. If you talk too much, you will say the wrong thing.
Eccl5:4 God doesn't like fools. So don't be slow to keep your promises to God.
Eccl5:5 It's better not to make a promise at all than to make one and not keep it.
Eccl5:6 Don't let your mouth get you in trouble! And don't say to the worship leader, "I didn't mean what I said." God can destroy everything you have worked for, so don't say something that makes God angry.
Eccl5:7 Respect and obey God! Daydreaming leads to a lot of senseless talk.
Eccl5:8 Don't be surprised if the poor of your country are abused, and injustice takes the place of justice. After all, the lower officials must do what the higher ones order them to do.
Eccl5:9 And since the king is the highest official, he benefits most from the taxes paid on the land.
Eccl5:10 If you love money and wealth, you will never be satisfied with what you have. This doesn't make sense either.
Eccl5:11 The more you have, the more everyone expects from you. Your money won't do you any good - others will just spend it for you.
Eccl5:12 If you have to work hard for a living, you can rest well at night, even if you don't have much to eat. But if you are rich, you can't even sleep.
Eccl5:13 I have seen something terribly unfair. People get rich, but it does them no good.
Eccl5:14 Suddenly they lose everything in a bad business deal, then have nothing to leave for their children.
Eccl5:15 They came into this world naked, and when they die, they will be just as naked. They can't take anything with them, and they won't have anything to show for all their work.
Eccl5:16 That's terribly unfair. They leave the world just as they came into it. They gained nothing from running after the wind.
Eccl5:17 Besides all this, they are always gloomy at mealtime, and they are troubled, sick, and bitter.
Eccl5:18 What is the best thing to do in the short life that God has given us? I think we should enjoy eating, drinking, and working hard. This is what God intends for us to do.
Eccl5:19 Suppose you are very rich and able to enjoy everything you own. Then go ahead and enjoy working hard - this is God's gift to you.
Eccl5:20 God will keep you so happy that you won't have time to worry about each day.
Eccl6:1 There is something else terribly unfair, and it troubles everyone on earth.
Eccl6:2 God may give you everything you want - money, property, and wealth. Then God doesn't let you enjoy it, and someone you don't even know gets it all. That's senseless and terribly unfair!
Eccl6:3 You may live a long time and have a hundred children. But a child born dead is better off than you, unless you enjoy life and have a decent burial.
Eccl6:4 That child will never live to see the sun or to have a name, and it will go straight to the world of darkness. But it will still find more rest than you,
Eccl6:5 ...
Eccl6:6 even if you live two thousand years and don't enjoy life. As you know, we all end up in the same place.
Eccl6:7 We struggle just to have enough to eat, but we are never satisfied.
Eccl6:8 We may be sensible, yet we are no better off than a fool. And if we are poor, it still doesn't do us any good to try to live right.
Eccl6:9 It's better to enjoy what we have than to always want something else, because that makes no more sense than chasing the wind.
Eccl6:10 Everything that happens was decided long ago. We humans know what we are like, and we can't argue with God, because he is too strong for us.
Eccl6:11 The more we talk, the less sense we make, so what good does it do to talk?
Eccl6:12 Life is short and meaningless, and it fades away like a shadow. Who knows what is best for us? Who knows what will happen after we are gone?
Eccl7:1 A good reputation at the time of death is better than loving care at the time of birth.
Eccl7:2 It's better to go to a funeral than to attend a feast; funerals remind us that we all must die.
Eccl7:3 Choose sorrow over laughter because a sad face may hide a happy heart.
Eccl7:4 A sensible person mourns, but fools always laugh.
Eccl7:5 Harsh correction is better than the songs of a fool.
Eccl7:6 Foolish laughter is stupid. It sounds like thorns crackling in a fire.
Eccl7:7 Corruption makes fools of sensible people, and bribes can ruin you.
Eccl7:8 Something completed is better than something just begun; patience is better than too much pride.
Eccl7:9 Only fools get angry quickly and hold a grudge.
Eccl7:10 It isn't wise to ask, "Why is everything worse than it used to be?"
Eccl7:11 Having wisdom is better than an inheritance.
Eccl7:12 Wisdom will protect you just like money; knowledge with good sense will lead you to life.
Eccl7:13 Think of what God has done! If God makes something crooked, can you make it straight?
Eccl7:14 When times are good, you should be cheerful; when times are bad, think what it means. God makes them both to keep us from knowing what will happen next.
Eccl7:15 I have seen everything during this senseless life of mine. I have seen good citizens die for doing the right thing, and I have seen criminals live to a ripe old age.
Eccl7:16 So don't destroy yourself by being too good or acting too smart!
Eccl7:17 Don't die before your time by being too evil or acting like a fool.
Eccl7:18 Keep to the middle of the road. You can do this if you truly respect God.
Eccl7:19 Wisdom will make you stronger than the ten most powerful leaders in your city.
Eccl7:20 No one in this world always does right.
Eccl7:21 Don't listen to everything that everyone says, or you might hear your servant cursing you.
Eccl7:22 Haven't you cursed many others?
Eccl7:23 I told myself that I would be smart and try to understand all of this, but it was too much for me.
Eccl7:24 The truth is beyond us. It's far too deep.
Eccl7:25 So I decided to learn everything I could and become wise enough to discover what life is all about. At the same time, I wanted to understand why it's stupid and senseless to be an evil fool.
Eccl7:26 Here is what I discovered: A bad woman is worse than death. She is a trap, reaching out with body and soul to catch you. But if you obey God, you can escape. If you don't obey, you are done for.
Eccl7:27 With all my wisdom I have tried to find out how everything fits together,
Eccl7:28 but so far I have not been able to. I do know there is one good man in a thousand, but never have I found a good woman.
Eccl7:29 I did learn one thing: We were completely honest when God created us, but now we have twisted minds.
Eccl8:1 Who is smart enough to explain everything? Wisdom makes you cheerful and gives you a smile.
Eccl8:2 If you promised God that you would be loyal to the king, I advise you to keep that promise.
Eccl8:3 Don't quickly oppose the king or argue when he has already made up his mind.
Eccl8:4 The king's word is law. No one can ask him, "Why are you doing this?"
Eccl8:5 If you obey the king, you will stay out of trouble. So be smart and learn what to do and when to do it.
Eccl8:6 Life is hard, but there is a time and a place for everything,
Eccl8:7 though no one can tell the future.
Eccl8:8 We cannot control the wind or determine the day of our death. There is no escape in time of war, and no one can hide behind evil.
Eccl8:9 I noticed all this and thought seriously about what goes on in the world. Why does one person have the power to hurt another?
Eccl8:10 I saw the wicked buried with honor, but God's people had to leave the holy city and were forgotten. None of this makes sense.
Eccl8:11 When we see criminals commit crime after crime without being punished, it makes us want to start a life of crime.
Eccl8:12 They commit hundreds of crimes and live to a ripe old age, in spite of the saying: Everyone who lives right and respects God will prosper,
Eccl8:13 but no one who sins and rejects God will prosper or live very long.
Eccl8:14 There is something else that doesn't make sense to me. Good citizens are treated as criminals, while criminals are honored as though they were good citizens.
Eccl8:15 So I think we should get as much out of life as we possibly can. There is nothing better than to enjoy our food and drink and to have a good time. Then we can make it through this troublesome life that God has given us here on earth.
Eccl8:16 Day and night I went without sleep, trying to understand what goes on in this world.
Eccl8:17 I saw everything God does, and I realized that no one can really understand what happens. We may be very wise, but no matter how much we try or how much we claim to know, we cannot understand it all.
Eccl9:1 I thought about these things. Then I understood that God has power over everyone, even those of us who are wise and live right. Anything can happen to any of us, and so we never know if life will be good or bad.
Eccl9:2 But exactly the same thing will finally happen to all of us, whether we live right and respect God or sin and don't respect God. Yes, the same thing will happen if we offer sacrifices to God or if we don't, if we keep our promises or break them.
Eccl9:3 It's terribly unfair for the same thing to happen to each of us. We are mean and foolish while we live, and then we die.
Eccl9:4 As long as we are alive, we still have hope, just as a live dog is better off than a dead lion.
Eccl9:5 We know that we will die, but the dead don't know a thing. Nothing good will happen to them - they are gone and forgotten.
Eccl9:6 Their loves, their hates, and their jealous feelings have all disappeared with them. They will never again take part in anything that happens on this earth.
Eccl9:7 Be happy and enjoy eating and drinking! God decided long ago that this is what you should do.
Eccl9:8 Dress up, comb your hair, and look your best.
Eccl9:9 Life is short, and you love your wife, so enjoy being with her. This is what you are supposed to do as you struggle through life on this earth.
Eccl9:10 Work hard at whatever you do. You will soon go to the world of the dead, where no one works or thinks or reasons or knows anything.
Eccl9:11 Here is something else I have learned: The fastest runners and the greatest heroes don't always win races and battles. Wisdom, intelligence, and skill don't always make you healthy, rich, or popular. We each have our share of bad luck.
Eccl9:12 None of us know when we might fall victim to a sudden disaster and find ourselves like fish in a net or birds in a trap.
Eccl9:13 Once I saw what people really think of wisdom.
Eccl9:14 It happened when a powerful ruler surrounded and attacked a small city where only a few people lived. The enemy army was getting ready to break through the city walls.
Eccl9:15 But the city was saved by the wisdom of a poor person who was soon forgotten.
Eccl9:16 So I decided that wisdom is better than strength. Yet if you are poor, no one pays any attention to you, no matter how smart you are.
Eccl9:17 Words of wisdom spoken softly make much more sense than the shouts of a ruler to a crowd of fools.
Eccl9:18 Wisdom is more powerful than weapons, yet one mistake can destroy all the good you have done.
Eccl10:1 A few dead flies in perfume make all of it stink, and a little foolishness outweighs a lot of wisdom.
Eccl10:2 Sensible thoughts lead you to do right; foolish thoughts lead you to do wrong.
Eccl10:3 Fools show their stupidity by the way they live; it's easy to see they have no sense.
Eccl10:4 Don't give up your job when your boss gets angry. If you stay calm, you'll be forgiven.
Eccl10:5 Some things rulers do are terribly unfair:
Eccl10:6 They honor fools, but dishonor the rich;
Eccl10:7 they let slaves ride on horses, but force slave owners to walk.
Eccl10:8 If you dig a pit, you might fall in; if you break down a wall, a snake might bite you.
Eccl10:9 You could even get hurt by chiseling a stone or chopping a log.
Eccl10:10 If you don't sharpen your ax, it will be harder to use; if you are smart, you'll know what to do.
Eccl10:11 The power to charm a snake does you no good if it bites you anyway.
Eccl10:12 If you talk sensibly, you will have friends; if you talk foolishly, you will destroy yourself.
Eccl10:13 Fools begin with nonsense, and their stupid chatter ends with disaster.
Eccl10:14 They never tire of talking, but none of us really know what the future will bring.
Eccl10:15 Fools wear themselves out -  they don't know enough to find their way home.
Eccl10:16 A country is in for trouble when its ruler is childish, and its leaders party all day long.
Eccl10:17 But a nation will prosper when its ruler is mature, and its leaders don't party too much.
Eccl10:18 Some people are too lazy to fix a leaky roof -  then the house falls in.
Eccl10:19 Eating and drinking make you feel happy, and bribes can buy everything you need.
Eccl10:20 Don't even think about cursing the king; don't curse the rich, not even in secret. A little bird might hear and tell everything.
Eccl11:1 Be generous, and someday you will be rewarded.
Eccl11:2 Share what you have with seven or eight others, because you never know when disaster may strike.
Eccl11:3 Rain clouds always bring rain; trees always stay wherever they fall.
Eccl11:4 If you worry about the weather and don't plant seeds, you won't harvest a crop.
Eccl11:5 No one can explain how a baby breathes before it is born. So how can anyone explain what God does? After all, he created everything.
Eccl11:6 Plant your seeds early in the morning and keep working in the field until dark. Who knows? Your work might pay off, and your seeds might produce.
Eccl11:7 Nothing on earth is more beautiful than the morning sun.
Eccl11:8 Even if you live to a ripe old age, you should try to enjoy each day, because darkness will come and will last a long time. Nothing makes sense.
Eccl11:9 Be cheerful and enjoy life while you are young! Do what you want and find pleasure in what you see. But don't forget that God will judge you for everything you do.
Eccl11:10 Rid yourself of all worry and pain, because the wonderful moments of youth quickly disappear.
Eccl12:1 Keep your Creator in mind while you are young! In years to come, you will be burdened down with troubles and say, "I don't enjoy life anymore."
Eccl12:2 Someday the light of the sun and the moon and the stars will all seem dim to you. Rain clouds will remain over your head.
Eccl12:3 Your body will grow feeble, your teeth will decay, and your eyesight fail.
Eccl12:4 The noisy grinding of grain will be shut out by your deaf ears, but even the song of a bird will keep you awake.
Eccl12:5 You will be afraid to climb up a hill or walk down a road. Your hair will turn as white as almond blossoms. You will feel lifeless and drag along like an old grasshopper. We each go to our eternal home, and the streets are filled with those who mourn.
Eccl12:6 The silver cord snaps, the golden bowl breaks; the water pitcher is smashed, and the pulley at the well is shattered.
Eccl12:7 So our bodies return to the earth, and the life-giving breath returns to God.
Eccl12:8 Nothing makes sense. I have seen it all -  nothing makes sense.
Eccl12:9 I was a wise teacher with much understanding, and I collected a number of proverbs that I had carefully studied.
Eccl12:10 Then I tried to explain these things in the best and most accurate way.
Eccl12:11 Words of wisdom are like the stick a farmer uses to make animals move. These sayings come from God, our only shepherd, and they are like nails that fasten things together.
Eccl12:12 My child, I warn you to stay away from any teachings except these. There is no end to books, and too much study will wear you out.
Eccl12:13 Everything you were taught can be put into a few words: Respect and obey God! This is what life is all about.
Eccl12:14 God will judge everything we do, even what is done in secret, whether good or bad.
SSol1:1 This is Solomon's most beautiful song. She Speaks:
SSol1:2 Kiss me tenderly! Your love is better than wine,
SSol1:3 and you smell so sweet. All the young women adore you; the very mention of your name is like spreading perfume.
SSol1:4 Hurry, my king! Let's hurry.
SSol1:5 Take me to your home. The Young Women Speak: We are happy for you! And we praise your love even more than wine. She Speaks: Young women of Jerusalem, it is only right that you should adore him. My skin is dark and beautiful, like a tent in the desert or like Solomon's curtains.
SSol1:6 Don't stare at me just because the sun has darkened my skin. My brothers were angry with me; they made me work in the vineyard, and so I neglected my complexion. Don't let the other shepherds think badly of me.
SSol1:7 I'm not one of those women who shamelessly follow after shepherds. My darling, I love you! Where do you feed your sheep and let them rest at noon? He Speaks:
SSol1:8 My dearest, if you don't know, just follow the path of the sheep. Then feed your young goats near the shepherds' tents.
SSol1:9 You move as gracefully as the pony that leads the chariot of the king.
SSol1:10 Earrings add to your beauty, and you wear a necklace of precious stones.
SSol1:11 Let's make you some jewelry of gold, woven with silver. She Speaks:
SSol1:12 My king, while you were on your couch, my love was a magic charm.
SSol1:13 My darling, you are perfume between my breasts;
SSol1:14 you are flower blossoms from the gardens of En-Gedi. He Speaks:
SSol1:15 My darling, you are lovely, so very lovely -  your eyes are those of a dove. She Speaks:
SSol1:16 My love, you are handsome, truly handsome -  the fresh green grass will be our wedding bed
SSol1:17 in the shade of cedar and cypress trees.
SSol2:1 I am merely a rose from the land of Sharon, a lily from the valley. He Speaks:
SSol2:2 My darling, when compared with other young women, you are a lily among thorns. She Speaks:
SSol2:3 And you, my love, are an apple tree among trees of the forest. Your shade brought me pleasure; your fruit was sweet.
SSol2:4 You led me to your banquet room and showered me with love.
SSol2:5 Refresh and strengthen me with raisins and apples. I am hungry for love!
SSol2:6 Put your left hand under my head and embrace me with your right arm.
SSol2:7 Young women of Jerusalem, promise me by the power of deer and gazelles never to awaken love before it is ready. She Speaks:
SSol2:8 I hear the voice of the one I love, as he comes leaping over mountains and hills
SSol2:9 like a deer or a gazelle. Now he stands outside our wall, looking through the window
SSol2:10 and speaking to me. He Speaks: My darling, I love you! Let's go away together.
SSol2:11 Winter is past, the rain has stopped;
SSol2:12 flowers cover the earth, it's time to sing. The cooing of doves is heard in our land.
SSol2:13 Fig trees are bearing fruit, while blossoms on grapevines fill the air with perfume. My darling, I love you! Let's go away together.
SSol2:14 You are my dove hiding among the rocks on the side of a cliff. Let me see how lovely you are! Let me hear the sound of your melodious voice.
SSol2:15 Our vineyards are in blossom; we must catch the little foxes that destroy the vineyards. She Speaks:
SSol2:16 My darling, I am yours, and you are mine, as you feed your sheep among the lilies.
SSol2:17 Pretend to be a young deer dancing on mountain slopes until daylight comes and shadows fade away.
SSol3:1 While in bed at night, I reached for the one I love with heart and soul. I looked for him, but he wasn't there.
SSol3:2 So I searched through the town for the one I love. I looked on every street, but he wasn't there.
SSol3:3 I even asked the guards patrolling the town, "Have you seen the one I love so much?"
SSol3:4 Right after that, I found him. I held him and would not let go until I had taken him to the home of my mother.
SSol3:5 Young women of Jerusalem, promise me by the power of deer and gazelles, never to awaken love before it is ready. Their Friends Speak:
SSol3:6 What do we see approaching from the desert like a cloud of smoke? With it comes the sweet smell of spices, including myrrh and frankincense.
SSol3:7 It is King Solomon carried on a throne, surrounded by sixty of Israel's best soldiers.
SSol3:8 Each of them wears a sword. They are experts at fighting, even in the dark.
SSol3:9 The throne is made of trees from Lebanon.
SSol3:10 Its posts are silver, the back is gold, and the seat is covered with purple cloth. You women of Jerusalem have taken great care to furnish the inside.
SSol3:11 Now come and see the crown given to Solomon by his mother on his happy wedding day.
SSol4:1 My darling, you are lovely, so very lovely -  as you look through your veil, your eyes are those of a dove. Your hair tosses about as gracefully as goats coming down from Gilead.
SSol4:2 Your teeth are whiter than sheep freshly washed; they match perfectly, not one is missing.
SSol4:3 Your lips are crimson cords, your mouth is shapely; behind your veil are hidden beautiful rosy cheeks.
SSol4:4 Your neck is more graceful than the tower of David, decorated with thousands of warriors' shields.
SSol4:5 Your breasts are perfect; they are twin deer feeding among lilies.
SSol4:6 I will hasten to those hills sprinkled with sweet perfume and stay there till sunrise.
SSol4:7 My darling, you are lovely in every way.
SSol4:8 My bride, together we will leave Lebanon! We will say good-by to the peaks of Mount Amana, Senir, and Hermon, where lions and leopards live in the caves.
SSol4:9 My bride, my very own, you have stolen my heart! With one glance from your eyes and the glow of your necklace, you have stolen my heart.
SSol4:10 Your love is sweeter than wine; the smell of your perfume is more fragrant than spices.
SSol4:11 Your lips are a honeycomb; milk and honey flow from your tongue. Your dress has the aroma of cedar trees from Lebanon.
SSol4:12 My bride, my very own, you are a garden, a fountain closed off to all others.
SSol4:13 Your arms are vines, covered with delicious fruits and all sorts of spices -  henna, nard,
SSol4:14 saffron, calamus, cinnamon, frankincense, myrrh, and aloes  - all the finest spices.
SSol4:15 You are a spring in the garden, a fountain of pure water, and a refreshing stream from Mount Lebanon. She Speaks:
SSol4:16 Let the north wind blow, the south wind too! Let them spread the aroma of my garden, so the one I love may enter and taste its delicious fruits.
SSol5:1 My bride, my very own, I come to my garden and enjoy its spices. I eat my honeycomb and honey; I drink my wine and milk. Their Friends Speak: Eat and drink until you are drunk with love. She Speaks:
SSol5:2 I was asleep, but dreaming: The one I love was at the door, knocking and saying, "My darling, my very own, my flawless dove, open the door for me! My head is drenched with evening dew."
SSol5:3 But I had already undressed and bathed my feet. Should I dress again and get my feet dirty?
SSol5:4 Then my darling's hand reached to open the latch, and my heart stood still.
SSol5:5 When I rose to open the door, my hands and my fingers dripped with perfume.
SSol5:6 My heart stood still while he spoke to me, but when I opened the door, my darling had disappeared. I searched and shouted, but I could not find him -  there was no answer.
SSol5:7 Then I was found by the guards patrolling the town and guarding the wall. They beat me up and stripped off my robe.
SSol5:8 Young women of Jerusalem, if you find the one I love, please say to him, "She is weak with desire." Their Friends Speak:
SSol5:9 Most beautiful of women, why is the one you love more special than others? Why do you ask us to tell him how you feel? She Speaks:
SSol5:10 He is handsome and healthy, the most outstanding among ten thousand.
SSol5:11 His head is purest gold; his hair is wavy, black as a raven.
SSol5:12 His eyes are a pair of doves bathing in a stream flowing with milk.
SSol5:13 His face is a garden of sweet-smelling spices; his lips are lilies dripping with perfume.
SSol5:14 His arms are branches of gold covered with jewels; his body is ivory decorated with sapphires.
SSol5:15 His legs are columns of marble on feet of gold. He stands there majestic like Mount Lebanon and its choice cedar trees.
SSol5:16 His kisses are sweet. I desire him so much! Young women of Jerusalem, he is my lover and friend.
SSol6:1 Most beautiful of women, tell us where he has gone. Let us help you find him. She Speaks:
SSol6:2 My darling has gone down to his garden of spices, where he will feed his sheep and gather lilies.
SSol6:3 I am his, and he is mine, as he feeds his sheep among the lilies. He Speaks:
SSol6:4 My dearest, the cities of Tirzah and Jerusalem are not as lovely as you. Your charms are more powerful than all of the stars in the heavens.
SSol6:5 Turn away your eyes -  they make me melt. Your hair tosses about as gracefully as goats coming down from Gilead.
SSol6:6 Your teeth are whiter than sheep freshly washed; they match perfectly, not one is missing.
SSol6:7 Behind your veil are hidden beautiful rosy cheeks.
SSol6:8 What if I could have sixty queens, eighty wives, and thousands of others!
SSol6:9 You would be my only choice, my flawless dove, the favorite child of your mother. The young women, the queens, and all the others tell how excited you are as they sing your praises:
SSol6:10 "You are as majestic as the morning sky -  glorious as the moon -  blinding as the sun! Your charms are more powerful than all the stars above." She Speaks:
SSol6:11 I went down to see if blossoms were on the walnut trees, grapevines, and fruit trees.
SSol6:12 But in my imagination I was suddenly riding on a glorious chariot. Their Friends Speak:
SSol6:13 Dance! Dance! Beautiful woman from Shulam, let us see you dance! She Speaks: Why do you want to see this woman from Shulam dancing with the others?
SSol7:1 You are a princess, and your feet are graceful in their sandals. Your thighs are works of art, each one a jewel;
SSol7:2 your navel is a wine glass filled to overflowing. Your body is full and slender like a bundle of wheat bound together by lilies.
SSol7:3 Your breasts are like twins of a deer.
SSol7:4 Your neck is like ivory, and your eyes sparkle like the pools of Heshbon by the gate of Bath-Rabbim. Your nose is beautiful like Mount Lebanon above the city of Damascus.
SSol7:5 Your head is held high like Mount Carmel; your hair is so lovely it holds a king prisoner.
SSol7:6 You are beautiful, so very desirable!
SSol7:7 You are tall and slender like a palm tree, and your breasts are full.
SSol7:8 I will climb that tree and cling to its branches. I will discover that your breasts are clusters of grapes, and that your breath is the aroma of apples.
SSol7:9 Kissing you is more delicious than drinking the finest wine. How wonderful and tasty! She Speaks:
SSol7:10 My darling, I am yours, and you desire me.
SSol7:11 Let's stroll through the fields and sleep in the villages.
SSol7:12 At dawn let's slip out and see if grapevines and fruit trees are covered with blossoms. When we are there, I will give you my love.
SSol7:13 Perfume from the magic flower fills the air, my darling. Right at our doorstep I have stored up for you all kinds of tasty fruits.
SSol8:1 If you were my brother, I could kiss you whenever we happen to meet, and no one would say I did wrong.
SSol8:2 I could take you to the home of my mother, who taught me all I know. I would give you delicious wine and fruit juice as well.
SSol8:3 Put your left hand under my head and embrace me with your right arm.
SSol8:4 Young women of Jerusalem, promise me by the power of deer and gazelles never to awaken love before it is ready. Their Friends Speak:
SSol8:5 Who is this young woman coming in from the desert and leaning on the shoulder of the one she loves? She Speaks: I stirred up your passions under the apple tree where you were born.
SSol8:6 Always keep me in your heart and wear this bracelet to remember me by. The passion of love bursting into flame is more powerful than death, stronger than the grave.
SSol8:7 Love cannot be drowned by oceans or floods; it cannot be bought, no matter what is offered. Their Friends Speak:
SSol8:8 We have a little sister whose breasts are not yet formed. If someone asks to marry her, what should we do?
SSol8:9 She isn't a wall that we can defend behind a silver shield. Neither is she a room that we can protect behind a wooden door. She Speaks:
SSol8:10 I am a wall around a city, my breasts are towers, and just looking at me brings him great pleasure.
SSol8:11 Solomon has a vineyard at Baal-Hamon, which he rents to others for a thousand pieces of silver each.
SSol8:12 My vineyard is mine alone! Solomon can keep his silver and the others can keep their share of the profits. He Speaks:
SSol8:13 You are in the garden with friends all around. Let me hear your voice! She Speaks:
SSol8:14 Hurry to me, my darling! Run faster than a deer to mountains of spices.
Isa1:1 I am Isaiah, the son of Amoz. And this is the message that I was given about Judah and Jerusalem when Uzziah, Jotham, Ahaz, and Hezekiah were the kings of Judah:
Isa1:2 The Lord has said, "Listen, heaven and earth! The children I raised have turned against me.
Isa1:3 Oxen and donkeys know who owns and feeds them, but my people won't ever learn."
Isa1:4 Israel, you are a sinful nation loaded down with guilt. You are wicked and corrupt and have turned from the Lord , the holy God of Israel.
Isa1:5 Why be punished more? Why not give up your sin? Your head is badly bruised, and you are weak all over.
Isa1:6 From your head to your toes there isn't a healthy spot. Bruises, cuts, and open sores go without care or oil to ease the pain.
Isa1:7 Your country lies in ruins; your towns are in ashes. Foreigners and strangers take and destroy your land while you watch.
Isa1:8 Enemies surround Jerusalem, alone like a hut in a vineyard or in a cucumber field.
Isa1:9 Zion would have disappeared like Sodom and Gomorrah, if the Lord All-Powerful had not let a few of its people survive.
Isa1:10 You are no better than the leaders and people of Sodom and Gomorrah! So listen to the Lord God:
Isa1:11 "Your sacrifices mean nothing to me. I am sick of your offerings of rams and choice cattle; I don't like the blood of bulls or lambs or goats.
Isa1:12 "Who asked you to bring all this when you come to worship me? Stay out of my temple!
Isa1:13 Your sacrifices are worthless, and incense is disgusting. I can't stand the evil you do on your New Moon Festivals or on your Sabbaths and other times of worship.
Isa1:14 I hate your New Moon Festivals and all others as well. They are a heavy burden I am tired of carrying.
Isa1:15 "No matter how much you pray, I won't listen. You are too violent.
Isa1:16 Wash yourselves clean! I am disgusted with your filthy deeds. Stop doing wrong
Isa1:17 and learn to live right. See that justice is done. Defend widows and orphans and help those in need."
Isa1:18 I, the Lord , invite you to come and talk it over. Your sins are scarlet red, but they will be whiter than snow or wool.
Isa1:19 If you willingly obey me, the best crops in the land will be yours.
Isa1:20 But if you turn against me, your enemies will kill you. I, the Lord , have spoken.
Isa1:21 Jerusalem, you are like an unfaithful wife. Once your judges were honest and your people lived right; now you are a city full of murderers.
Isa1:22 Your silver is fake, and your wine is watered down.
Isa1:23 Your leaders have rejected me to become friends of crooks; your rulers are looking for gifts and bribes. Widows and orphans never get a fair trial.
Isa1:24 I am the Lord All-Powerful, the mighty ruler of Israel, and I make you a promise: You are now my enemy, and I will show my anger by taking revenge on you.
Isa1:25 I will punish you terribly and burn away everything that makes you unfit to worship me.
Isa1:26 Jerusalem, I will choose judges and advisors like those you had before. Your new name will be "Justice and Faithfulness."
Isa1:27 Jerusalem, you will be saved by showing justice; Zion's people who turn to me will be saved by doing right.
Isa1:28 But those rebellious sinners who turn against me, the Lord , will all disappear.
Isa1:29 You will be made ashamed of those groves of trees where you worshiped idols.
Isa1:30 You will be like a grove of trees dying in a drought.
Isa1:31 Your strongest leaders will be like dry wood set on fire by their idols. No one will be able to help, as they all go up in flames.
Isa2:1 This is the message that I was given about Judah and Jerusalem:
Isa2:2 In the future, the mountain with the Lord 's temple will be the highest of all. It will reach above the hills; every nation will rush to it.
Isa2:3 Many people will come and say, "Let's go to the mountain of the Lord God of Jacob and worship in his temple." The Lord will teach us his Law from Jerusalem, and we will obey him.
Isa2:4 He will settle arguments between nations. They will pound their swords and their spears into rakes and shovels; they will never make war or attack one another.
Isa2:5 People of Israel, let's live by the light of the Lord .
Isa2:6 Our Lord , you have deserted your people, Israel, because they follow customs of nations from the east. They worship Philistine gods and are close friends of foreigners.
Isa2:7 They have endless treasures of silver and gold; they have countless horses and war chariots.
Isa2:8 Everywhere in the country they worship the idols they have made.
Isa2:9 And so, all of them will be ashamed and disgraced. Don't help them!
Isa2:10 Every one of you, go hide among the rocks and in the ground, because the Lord is fearsome, marvelous, and glorious.
Isa2:11 When the Lord comes, everyone who is proud will be made humble, and the Lord alone will be honored.
Isa2:12 The Lord All-Powerful has chosen a day when those who are proud and conceited will be put down.
Isa2:13 The tall and towering cedars of Lebanon will be destroyed. So will the oak trees of Bashan,
Isa2:14 all high mountains and hills,
Isa2:15 every strong fortress,
Isa2:16 all the seagoing ships, and every beautiful boat.
Isa2:17 When that day comes, everyone who is proud will be put down. Only the Lord will be honored.
Isa2:18 Idols will be gone for good.
Isa2:19 You had better hide in caves and holes -  the Lord will be fearsome, marvelous, and glorious when he comes to terrify people on earth.
Isa2:20 On that day everyone will throw to the rats and bats their idols of silver and gold they made to worship.
Isa2:21 The Lord will be fearsome, marvelous, and glorious when he comes to terrify people on earth -  they will hide in caves and in the hills.
Isa2:22 Stop trusting the power of humans. They are all going to die, so how can they help?
Isa3:1 The mighty Lord All-Powerful is going to take away from Jerusalem and Judah everything you need -  your bread and water,
Isa3:2 soldiers and heroes, judges and prophets, leaders and army officers,
Isa3:3 officials and advisors, fortunetellers and others who tell the future.
Isa3:4 He will let children and babies become your rulers.
Isa3:5 You will each be cruel to friends and neighbors. Young people will insult their elders; no one will show respect to those who deserve it.
Isa3:6 Some of you will grab hold of a relative and say, "You still have a coat. Be our leader and rule this pile of ruins."
Isa3:7 But the answer will be, "I can't do you any good. Don't make me your leader. There's no food or clothing left in my house."
Isa3:8 Jerusalem and Judah, you rebelled against your glorious Lord  -  your words and your actions, made you stumble and fall.
Isa3:9 The look on your faces shows that you are sinful as Sodom, and you don't try to hide it. You are in for trouble, and you have brought it all on yourselves.
Isa3:10 Tell those who obey God, "You're very fortunate -  you will be rewarded for what you have done."
Isa3:11 Tell those who disobey, "You're in big trouble -  what you did to others will come back to you."
Isa3:12 Though you are God's people, you are ruled and abused by women and children. You are confused by leaders who guide you down the wrong path.
Isa3:13 The Lord is ready to accuse and judge all nations.
Isa3:14 He will even judge you rulers and leaders of his own nation. You destroyed his vineyard and filled your houses by robbing the poor.
Isa3:15 The Lord All-Powerful says, "You have crushed my people and rubbed in the dirt the faces of the poor."
Isa3:16 The Lord says: The women of Jerusalem are proud and strut around, winking shamelessly. They wear anklets that jingle and call attention to the way they walk.
Isa3:17 But I, the Lord , will cover their heads with sores, and I will uncover their private parts.
Isa3:18 When that day comes, I will take away from those women all the fine jewelry they wear on their ankles, heads, necks, ears, arms, noses, fingers, and on their clothes. I will remove their veils, their belts, their perfume, their magic charms, their royal robes, and all their fancy dresses, hats, and purses.
Isa3:19 ...
Isa3:20 ...
Isa3:21 ...
Isa3:22 ...
Isa3:23 ...
Isa3:24 In place of perfume, there will be a stink; in place of belts, there will be ropes; in place of fancy hairdos, they will have bald heads. Instead of expensive clothes, they will wear sackcloth; instead of beauty, they will have ugly scars.
Isa3:25 The fighting men of Jerusalem will be killed in battle.
Isa3:26 The city will mourn and sit in the dirt, emptied of its people.
Isa4:1 When this happens, seven women will grab the same man, and each of them will say, "I'll buy my own food and clothes! Just marry me and take away my disgrace."
Isa4:2 The time is coming when the Lord will make his land fruitful and glorious again, and the people of Israel who survive will take great pride in what the land produces.
Isa4:3 Everyone who is left alive in Jerusalem will be called special,
Isa4:4 after the Lord sends a fiery judgment to clean the city and its people of their violent deeds.
Isa4:5 Then the Lord will cover the whole city and its meeting places with a thick cloud each day and with a flaming fire each night. God's own glory will be like a huge tent that covers everything.
Isa4:6 It will provide shade from the heat of the sun and a place of shelter and protection from storms and rain.
Isa5:1 I will sing a song about my friend's vineyard that was on the side of a fertile hill.
Isa5:2 My friend dug the ground, removed the stones, and planted the best vines. He built a watchtower and dug a pit in rocky ground for pressing the grapes. He hoped they would be sweet, but bitter grapes were all it produced.
Isa5:3 Listen, people of Jerusalem and of Judah! You be the judge of me and my vineyard.
Isa5:4 What more could I have done for my vineyard? I hoped for sweet grapes, but bitter grapes were all that grew.
Isa5:5 Now I will let you know what I am going to do. I will cut down the hedge and tear down the wall. My vineyard will be trampled and left in ruins.
Isa5:6 It will turn into a desert, neither pruned nor hoed; it will be covered with thorns and briars. I will command the clouds not to send rain.
Isa5:7 I am the Lord All-Powerful! Israel is the vineyard, and Judah is the garden I tended with care. I had hoped for honesty and for justice, but dishonesty and cries for mercy were all I found.
Isa5:8 You are in for trouble! You take over house after house and field after field, until there is no room left for anyone else in all the land.
Isa5:9 But the Lord All-Powerful has made this promise to me: Those large and beautiful homes will be left empty, with no one to take care of them.
Isa5:10 Ten acres of grapevines will produce only six gallons of juice, and five bushels of seed will produce merely a half-bushel of grain.
Isa5:11 You are in for trouble! You get up early to start drinking, and you keep it up late into the night.
Isa5:12 At your drinking parties you have the music of stringed instruments, tambourines, and flutes. But you never even think about all the Lord has done,
Isa5:13 and so his people know nothing about him. That's why many of you will be dragged off to foreign lands. Your leaders will starve to death, and everyone else will suffer from thirst.
Isa5:14 The world of the dead has opened its mouth wide and is eagerly waiting for the leaders of Jerusalem and for its noisy crowds, especially for those who take pride in that city.
Isa5:15 Its citizens have been put down, and its proud people have been brought to shame.
Isa5:16 But the holy Lord God All-Powerful is praised, because he has shown who he is by bringing justice.
Isa5:17 His people will be like sheep grazing in their own pasture, and they will take off what was left by others.
Isa5:18 You are in for trouble! The lies you tell are like ropes by which you drag along sin and evil.
Isa5:19 And you say, "Let the holy God of Israel hurry up and do what he has promised, so we can see it for ourselves."
Isa5:20 You are headed for trouble! You say wrong is right, darkness is light, and bitter is sweet.
Isa5:21 You think you are clever and smart.
Isa5:22 And you are great at drinking and mixing drinks. But you are in for trouble.
Isa5:23 You accept bribes to let the guilty go free, and you cheat the innocent out of a fair trial.
Isa5:24 You will go up in flames like straw and hay! You have rejected the teaching of the holy Lord God All-Powerful of Israel. Now your roots will rot, and your blossoms will turn to dust.
Isa5:25 You are the Lord 's people, but you made him terribly angry, and he struck you with his mighty arm. Mountains shook, and dead bodies covered the streets like garbage. The Lord is still angry, and he is ready to strike you again.
Isa5:26 The Lord has signaled for the foreign nations to come and attack you. He has already whistled, and they are coming as fast as they can.
Isa5:27 None of them are tired. They don't sleep or get drowsy, and they run without stumbling. Their belts don't come loose; their sandal straps don't break.
Isa5:28 Their arrows are sharp, and their bows are ready. The hoofs of their horses are hard as flint; the wheels of their war chariots turn as fast as a whirlwind.
Isa5:29 They roar and growl like fierce young lions as they grab their victims and drag them off where no one can rescue them.
Isa5:30 On the day they attack, they will roar like the ocean. And across the land you will see nothing but darkness and trouble, because the light of day will be covered by thick clouds.
Isa6:1 In the year that King Uzziah died, I had a vision of the Lord . He was on his throne high above, and his robe filled the temple.
Isa6:2 Flaming creatures with six wings each were flying over him. They covered their faces with two of their wings and their bodies with two more. They used the other two wings for flying,
Isa6:3 as they shouted, "Holy, holy, holy, Lord All-Powerful! The earth is filled with your glory."
Isa6:4 As they shouted, the doorposts of the temple shook, and the temple was filled with smoke.
Isa6:5 Then I cried out, "I'm doomed! Everything I say is sinful, and so are the words of everyone around me. Yet I have seen the King, the Lord All-Powerful."
Isa6:6 One of the flaming creatures flew over to me with a burning coal that it had taken from the altar with a pair of metal tongs.
Isa6:7 It touched my lips with the hot coal and said, "This has touched your lips. Your sins are forgiven, and you are no longer guilty."
Isa6:8 After this, I heard the Lord ask, "Is there anyone I can send? Will someone go for us?" "I'll go," I answered. "Send me!"
Isa6:9 Then the Lord told me to go and speak this message to the people: "You will listen and listen, but never understand. You will look and look, but never see." The Lord also said,
Isa6:10 "Make these people stubborn! Make them stop up their ears, cover their eyes, and fail to understand. Don't let them turn to me and be healed."
Isa6:11 Then I asked the Lord , "How long will this last?" The Lord answered: Until their towns are destroyed and their houses are deserted, until their fields are empty,
Isa6:12 and I have sent them far away, leaving their land in ruins.
Isa6:13 If only a tenth of the people are left, even they will be destroyed. But just as stumps remain after trees have been cut down, some of my chosen ones will be left.
Isa7:1 Ahaz, the son of Jotham and the grandson of Uzziah, was king of Judah when King Rezin of Syria and King Pekah son of Remaliah of Israel went to attack Jerusalem. But they were not able to do what they had planned.
Isa7:2 When news reached the royal palace that Syria had joined forces with Israel, King Ahaz and everyone in Judah were so terrified that they shook like trees in a windstorm.
Isa7:3 Then the Lord said to me: Take your son Shearjashub and go see King Ahaz. You will find him on the road near the cloth makers' shops at the end of the canal that brings water from the upper pool.
Isa7:4 Tell Ahaz to stop worrying. There's no need for him to be afraid of King Rezin and King Pekah. They are very angry, but they are nothing more than a dying fire. Ahaz doesn't need to fear
Isa7:5 their evil threats
Isa7:6 to invade and defeat Judah and Jerusalem and to let the son of Tabeel be king in his place.
Isa7:7 I, the Lord , promise that this will never happen.
Isa7:8 Damascus is just the capital of Syria, and King Rezin rules only in Damascus. Samaria is just the capital of Israel, and King Pekah rules only in Samaria. But in less than sixty-five years, Israel will be destroyed. And if Ahaz and his officials don't trust me, they will be defeated.
Isa7:9 ...
Isa7:10 Once again the Lord God spoke to King Ahaz. This time he said,
Isa7:11 "Ask me for proof that my promise will come true. Ask for something to happen deep in the world of the dead or high in the heavens above."
Isa7:12 "No, Lord ," Ahaz answered. "I won't test you!"
Isa7:13 Then I said: Listen, every one of you in the royal family of David. You have already tried my patience. Now you are trying God's patience by refusing to ask for proof.
Isa7:14 But the Lord will still give you proof. A virgin is pregnant; she will have a son and will name him Immanuel.
Isa7:15 Even before the boy is old enough to know how to choose between right and wrong, he will eat yogurt and honey, and the countries of the two kings you fear will be destroyed.
Isa7:16 ...
Isa7:17 But the Lord will make more trouble for your people and your kingdom than any of you have known since Israel broke away from Judah. He will even bring the king of Assyria to attack you.
Isa7:18 When that time comes, the Lord will whistle, and armies will come from Egypt like flies and from Assyria like bees.
Isa7:19 They will settle everywhere - in the deep valleys and between the rocks, on every bush and all over the pastureland.
Isa7:20 The Lord will pay the king of Assyria to bring a razor from across the Euphrates River and shave your head and every hair on your body, including your beard.
Isa7:21 No one will have more than one young cow and two sheep,
Isa7:22 but those who do will have enough milk to make yogurt. In fact, everyone left in the land will eat yogurt and honey.
Isa7:23 Vineyards that had a thousand vines and were worth a thousand pieces of silver will turn into thorn patches.
Isa7:24 You will go there to hunt with your bow and arrows, because the whole country will be covered with thornbushes.
Isa7:25 The hills where you once planted crops will be overgrown with thorns and thistles. You will be afraid to go there, and your cattle, sheep, and goats will be turned loose on those hills.
Isa8:1 The Lord said, "Isaiah, get something to write on. Then write in big clear letters the name, MAHER-SHALAL-HASH-BAZ.
Isa8:2 I will have Uriah the priest and Zechariah son of Jeberechiah serve as witnesses to this."
Isa8:3 Sometime later, my wife and I had a son, and the Lord said, "Name him Maher-Shalal-Hash-Baz.
Isa8:4 Because before he can say Mommy' or Daddy', the king of Assyria will attack and take everything of value from Damascus and Samaria."
Isa8:5 The Lord spoke to me again and said:
Isa8:6 These people have refused the gentle waters of Shiloah and have gladly gone over to the side of King Rezin and King Pekah.
Isa8:7 Now I will send the king of Assyria against them with his powerful army, which will attack like the mighty Euphrates River overflowing its banks.
Isa8:8 Enemy soldiers will cover Judah like a flood reaching up to your neck. But God is with us. He will spread his wings and protect our land.
Isa8:9 All of you foreign nations, go ahead and prepare for war, but you will be crushed.
Isa8:10 Get together and make plans, but you will fail because God is with us.
Isa8:11 The Lord took hold of me with his powerful hand and said: I'm warning you! Don't act like these people.
Isa8:12 Don't call something a rebellious plot, just because they do, and don't be afraid of something, just because they are.
Isa8:13 I am the one you should fear and respect. I am the holy God, the Lord All-Powerful!
Isa8:14 Run to me for protection. I am a rock that will make both Judah and Israel stumble and break their bones. I am a trap that will catch the people of Jerusalem - they will be captured and dragged away.
Isa8:15 ...
Isa8:16 My message and my teachings are to be sealed and given to my followers.
Isa8:17 Meanwhile, I patiently trust the Lord , even though he is no longer pleased with Israel.
Isa8:18 My children and I are warning signs to Israel from the Lord All-Powerful, who lives on Mount Zion.
Isa8:19 Someone may say to you, "Go to the fortunetellers who make soft chirping sounds or ask the spirits of the dead. After all, a nation ought to be able to ask its own gods
Isa8:20 what it should do." None of those who talk like that will live to see the light of day!
Isa8:21 They will go around in great pain and will become so hungry that they will angrily curse their king and their gods. And when they try to find help in heaven
Isa8:22 and on earth, they will find only trouble and darkness, terrible trouble and deepest darkness.
Isa9:1 But those who have suffered will no longer be in pain. The territories of Zebulun and Naphtali in Galilee were once hated. But this land of the Gentiles across the Jordan River and along the Mediterranean Sea will be greatly respected.
Isa9:2 Those who walked in the dark have seen a bright light. And it shines upon everyone who lives in the land of darkest shadows.
Isa9:3 Our Lord , you have made your nation stronger. Because of you, its people are glad and celebrate like workers at harvest time or like soldiers dividing up what they have taken.
Isa9:4 You have broken the power of those who abused and enslaved your people. You have rescued them just as you saved your people from Midian.
Isa9:5 The boots of marching warriors and the blood-stained uniforms have been fed to flames and eaten by fire.
Isa9:6 A child has been born for us. We have been given a son who will be our ruler. His names will be Wonderful Advisor and Mighty God, Eternal Father and Prince of Peace.
Isa9:7 His power will never end; peace will last forever. He will rule David's kingdom and make it grow strong. He will always rule with honesty and justice. The Lord All-Powerful will make certain that all of this is done.
Isa9:8 The Lord had warned the people of Israel,
Isa9:9 and all of them knew it, including everyone in the capital city of Samaria. But they were proud and stubborn and said,
Isa9:10 "Houses of brick and sycamore have fallen to the ground, but we will build houses with stones and cedar."
Isa9:11 The Lord made their enemies attack them.
Isa9:12 He sent the Arameans from the east and the Philistines from the west, and they swallowed up Israel. But even this did not stop him from being angry, so he kept on punishing them.
Isa9:13 The people of Israel still did not turn back to the Lord All-Powerful and worship him.
Isa9:14 In one day he cut off their head and tail, their leaves and branches.
Isa9:15 Their rulers and leaders were the head, and the lying prophets were the tail.
Isa9:16 They had led the nation down the wrong path, and the people were confused.
Isa9:17 The Lord was angry with his people and kept punishing them, because they had turned against him. They were evil and spoke foolishly. That's why he did not have pity on their young people or on their widows and orphans.
Isa9:18 Evil had spread like a raging forest fire sending thornbushes up in smoke.
Isa9:19 The Lord All-Powerful was angry and used the people as fuel for a fire that scorched the land. They turned against each other
Isa9:20 like wild animals attacking and eating everyone around them, even their own relatives. But still they were not satisfied.
Isa9:21 The tribes of Ephraim and Manasseh turned against each other, then joined forces to attack Judah. But the Lord was still angry and ready to punish the nation even more.
Isa10:1 You people are in for trouble! You have made cruel and unfair laws
Isa10:2 that let you cheat the poor and needy and rob widows and orphans.
Isa10:3 But what will you do when you are fiercely attacked and punished by foreigners? Where will you run for help? Where will you hide your valuables?
Isa10:4 How will you escape being captured or killed? The Lord is still angry, and he isn't through with you yet!
Isa10:5 The Lord says: I am furious! And I will use the king of Assyria as a club
Isa10:6 to beat down you godless people. I am angry with you, and I will send him to attack you. He will take what he wants and walk on you like mud in the streets.
Isa10:7 He has even bigger plans in mind, because he wants to destroy many nations.
Isa10:8 The king of Assyria says: My army commanders are kings!
Isa10:9 They have already captured the cities of Calno, Carchemish, Hamath, Arpad, Samaria, and Damascus.
Isa10:10 The gods of Jerusalem and Samaria are weaker than the gods of those powerful nations. And I will destroy Jerusalem, together with its gods and idols, just as I did Samaria.
Isa10:11 ...
Isa10:12 The Lord will do what he has planned against Jerusalem and Mount Zion. Then he will punish the proud and boastful king of Assyria,
Isa10:13 who says: I did these things by my own power because I am smart and clever. I attacked kings like a wild bull, and I took the land and the treasures of their nations.
Isa10:14 I have conquered the whole world! And it was easier than taking eggs from an unguarded nest. No one even flapped a wing or made a peep.
Isa10:15 King of Assyria, can an ax or a saw overpower the one who uses it? Can a wooden pole lift whoever holds it?
Isa10:16 The mighty Lord All-Powerful will send a terrible disease to strike down your army, and you will burn with fever under your royal robes.
Isa10:17 The holy God, who is the light of Israel, will turn into a fire, and in one day you will go up in flames, just like a thornbush.
Isa10:18 The Lord will make your beautiful forests and fertile fields slowly rot.
Isa10:19 There will be so few trees that even a young child can count them.
Isa10:20 A time is coming when the survivors from Israel and Judah will completely depend on the holy Lord of Israel, instead of the nation that defeated them.
Isa10:21 There were as many people as there are grains of sand along the seashore, but only a few will survive to come back to Israel's mighty God. This is because he has threatened to destroy their nation, just as they deserve.
Isa10:22 ...
Isa10:23 The Lord All-Powerful has promised that everyone on this earth will be punished.
Isa10:24 Now the Lord God All-Powerful says to his people in Jerusalem: The Assyrians will beat you with sticks and abuse you, just as the Egyptians did. But don't be afraid of them.
Isa10:25 Soon I will stop being angry with you, and I will punish them for their crimes.
Isa10:26 I will beat the Assyrians with a whip, as I did the people of Midian near the rock at Oreb. And I will show the same mighty power that I used when I made a path through the sea in Egypt.
Isa10:27 Then they will no longer rule your nation. All will go well for you, and your burden will be lifted.
Isa10:28 Enemy troops have reached the town of Aiath. They have gone through Migron, and they stored their supplies at Michmash,
Isa10:29 before crossing the valley and spending the night at Geba. The people of Ramah are terrified; everyone in Gibeah, the hometown of Saul, has run away.
Isa10:30 Loud crying can be heard in the towns of Gallim, Laishah, and sorrowful Anathoth.
Isa10:31 No one is left in Madmenah or Gebim.
Isa10:32 Today the enemy will camp at Nob and shake a threatening fist at Mount Zion in Jerusalem.
Isa10:33 But the Lord All-Powerful will use his fearsome might to bring down the tallest trees and chop off every branch.
Isa10:34 With an ax, the glorious Lord will destroy every tree in the forests of Lebanon.
Isa11:1 Like a branch that sprouts from a stump, someone from David's family will someday be king.
Isa11:2 The Spirit of the Lord will be with him to give him understanding, wisdom, and insight. He will be powerful, and he will know and honor the Lord .
Isa11:3 His greatest joy will be to obey the Lord . This king won't judge by appearances or listen to rumors.
Isa11:4 The poor and the needy will be treated with fairness and with justice. His word will be law everywhere in the land, and criminals will be put to death.
Isa11:5 Honesty and fairness will be his royal robes.
Isa11:6 Leopards will lie down with young goats, and wolves will rest with lambs. Calves and lions will eat together and be cared for by little children.
Isa11:7 Cows and bears will share the same pasture; their young will rest side by side. Lions and oxen will both eat straw.
Isa11:8 Little children will play near snake holes. They will stick their hands into dens of poisonous snakes and never be hurt.
Isa11:9 Nothing harmful will take place on the Lord 's holy mountain. Just as water fills the sea, the land will be filled with people who know and honor the Lord .
Isa11:10 The time is coming when one of David's descendants will be the signal for the people of all nations to come together. They will follow his advice, and his own nation will become famous.
Isa11:11 When that day comes, the Lord will again reach out his mighty arm and bring home his people who have survived in Assyria, Egypt, Pathros, Ethiopia, Elam, Shinar, Hamath, and the land along the coast.
Isa11:12 He will give a signal to the nations, and he will bring together the refugees from Judah and Israel, who have been scattered all over the earth.
Isa11:13 Israel will stop being jealous of Judah, and Judah will no longer be the enemy of Israel.
Isa11:14 Instead, they will get together and attack the Philistines in the west. Then they will defeat the Edomites, the Moabites, and the Ammonites in the east. They will rule those people and take from them whatever they want.
Isa11:15 The Lord will dry up the arm of the Red Sea near Egypt, and he will send a scorching wind to divide the Euphrates River into seven streams that anyone can step across.
Isa11:16 Then for his people who survive, there will be a good road from Assyria, just as there was a good road for their ancestors when they left Egypt.
Isa12:1 At that time you will say, "I thank you, Lord ! You were angry with me, but you stopped being angry and gave me comfort.
Isa12:2 I trust you to save me, Lord God, and I won't be afraid. My power and my strength come from you, and you have saved me."
Isa12:3 With great joy, you people will get water from the well of victory.
Isa12:4 At that time you will say, "Our Lord , we are thankful, and we worship only you. We will tell the nations how glorious you are and what you have done.
Isa12:5 Because of your wonderful deeds we will sing your praises everywhere on earth."
Isa12:6 Sing, people of Zion! Celebrate the greatness of the holy Lord of Israel. God is here to help you.
Isa13:1 This is the message that I was given about Babylon:
Isa13:2 From high on a barren hill give a signal, shout the orders, and point the way to enter the gates of Babylon's proud rulers.
Isa13:3 The Lord has commanded his very best warriors and his proud heroes to show how angry he is.
Isa13:4 Listen to the noisy crowds on the mountains! Kingdoms and nations are joining forces. The Lord All-Powerful is bringing together an army for battle.
Isa13:5 From a distant land the Lord is coming fierce and furious -  he brings his weapons to destroy the earth.
Isa13:6 Cry and weep! The day is coming when the mighty Lord will bring destruction.
Isa13:7 All people will be terrified. Hands will grow limp; courage will melt away.
Isa13:8 Everyone will tremble with pain like a woman giving birth; they will stare at each other with horror on their faces.
Isa13:9 I, the Lord , will show no mercy or pity when that time comes. In my anger I will destroy the earth and every sinner who lives on it.
Isa13:10 Light will disappear from the stars in the sky; the dawning sun will turn dark, and the moon will lose its glow.
Isa13:11 I will punish this evil world and its people because of their sins. I will crush the horrible pride of those who are cruel.
Isa13:12 Survivors will be harder to find than the purest gold.
Isa13:13 I, the Lord All-Powerful, am terribly angry -  I will make the sky tremble and the earth shake loose.
Isa13:14 Everyone will run to their homelands, just as hunted deer run, and sheep scatter when they have no shepherd.
Isa13:15 Those who are captured will be killed by a sword.
Isa13:16 They will see their children beaten against rocks, their homes robbed, and their wives abused.
Isa13:17 The Medes can't be bought off with silver or gold, and I'm sending them to attack Babylonia.
Isa13:18 Their arrows will slaughter the young men; no pity will be shown to babies and children.
Isa13:19 The city of Babylon is glorious and powerful, the pride of the nation. But it will be like the cities of Sodom and Gomorrah after I, the Lord, destroyed them.
Isa13:20 No one will live in Babylon. Even nomads won't camp nearby, and shepherds won't let their sheep rest there.
Isa13:21 Only desert creatures, hoot owls, and ostriches will live in its ruins, and goats will leap about.
Isa13:22 Hyenas and wolves will howl from Babylon's fortresses and beautiful palaces. Its time is almost up!
Isa14:1 The Lord will have mercy on Israel and will let them be his chosen people once again. He will bring them back to their own land, and foreigners will join them as part of Israel.
Isa14:2 Other nations will lead them home, and Israel will make slaves of them in the land that belongs to the Lord. Israel will rule over those who once governed and mistreated them.
Isa14:3 The Lord will set you free from your sorrow, suffering, and slavery.
Isa14:4 Then you will make fun of the King of Babylonia by singing this song: That cruel monster is done for! He won't attack us again.
Isa14:5 The Lord has crushed the power of those evil kings,
Isa14:6 who were furious and never stopped abusing the people of other nations.
Isa14:7 Now all the world is at peace; its people are celebrating with joyful songs.
Isa14:8 King of Babylonia, even the cypress trees and the cedars of Lebanon celebrate and say, "Since you were put down, no one comes along to chop us down."
Isa14:9 The world of the dead eagerly waits for you. With great excitement, the spirits of ancient rulers hear about your coming.
Isa14:10 Each one of them will say, "Now you are just as weak as any of us!
Isa14:11 Your pride and your music have ended here in the world of the dead. Worms are your blanket, maggots are your bed."
Isa14:12 You, the bright morning star, have fallen from the sky! You brought down other nations; now you are brought down.
Isa14:13 You said to yourself, "I'll climb to heaven and place my throne above the highest stars. I'll sit there with the gods far away in the north.
Isa14:14 I'll be above the clouds, just like God Most High."
Isa14:15 But now you are deep in the world of the dead.
Isa14:16 Those who see you will stare and wonder, "Is this the man who made the world tremble and shook up kingdoms?
Isa14:17 Did he capture every city and make earth a desert? Is he the one who refused to let prisoners go home?"
Isa14:18 When kings die, they are buried in glorious tombs.
Isa14:19 But you will be left unburied, just another dead body lying underfoot like a broken branch. You will be one of many killed in battle and gone down to the deep rocky pit.
Isa14:20 You won't be buried with kings; you ruined your country and murdered your people. You evil monster! We hope that your family will be forgotten forever.
Isa14:21 We will slaughter your sons to make them pay for the crimes of their ancestors. They won't take over the world or build cities anywhere on this earth.
Isa14:22 The Lord All-Powerful has promised to attack Babylonia and destroy everyone there, so that none of them will ever be remembered again.
Isa14:23 The Lord will sweep out the people, and the land will become a swamp for wild animals.
Isa14:24 The Lord All-Powerful has made this promise: Everything I have planned will happen just as I said.
Isa14:25 I will wipe out every Assyrian in my country, and I will crush those on my mountains. I will free my people from slavery to the Assyrians.
Isa14:26 I have planned this for the whole world, and my mighty arm controls every nation.
Isa14:27 I, the Lord All-Powerful, have made these plans. No one can stop me now!
Isa14:28 This message came from the Lord in the year King Ahaz died:
Isa14:29 Philistines, don't be happy just because the rod that punished you is broken. That rod will become a poisonous snake, and then a flying fiery dragon.
Isa14:30 The poor and needy will find pastures for their sheep and will live in safety. But I will starve some of you, and others will be killed.
Isa14:31 Cry and weep in the gates of your towns, you Philistines! Smoke blows in from the north, and every soldier is ready.
Isa14:32 If a messenger comes from a distant nation, you must say: "The Lord built Zion. Even the poorest of his people will find safety there."
Isa15:1 This is a message about Moab: The towns of Ar and Kir were destroyed in a night. Moab is left in ruins!
Isa15:2 Everyone in Dibon has gone up to the temple and the shrines to cry and weep. All of Moab is crying. Heads and beards are shaved because of what happened at Nebo and Medeba.
Isa15:3 In the towns and at home, everyone wears sackcloth and cries loud and long.
Isa15:4 From Heshbon and Elealeh, weeping is heard in Jahaz; Moab's warriors scream while trembling with fear.
Isa15:5 I pity Moab! Its people are running to Zoar and to Eglath-Shelishiyah. They cry on their way up to the town of Luhith; on the road to Horonaim they tell of disasters.
Isa15:6 The streams of Nimrim and the grasslands have dried up. Every plant is parched.
Isa15:7 The people of Moab are leaving, crossing over Willow Creek, taking everything they own and have worked for.
Isa15:8 In the towns of Eglaim and of Beerelim and everywhere else in Moab mournful cries are heard.
Isa15:9 The streams near Dimon are flowing with blood. But the Lord will bring even worse trouble to Dimon, because all in Moab who escape will be attacked by lions.
Isa16:1 Send lambs as gifts to the ruler of the land. Send them across the desert from Sela to Mount Zion.
Isa16:2 The women of Moab crossing the Arnon River are like a flock of birds scattered from their nests.
Isa16:3 Moab's messengers say to the people of Judah, "Be kind and help us! Shade us from the heat of the noonday sun. Hide our refugees! Don't turn them away.
Isa16:4 Let our people live in your country and find safety here." Moab, your cruel enemies will disappear; they will no longer attack and destroy your land.
Isa16:5 Then a kingdom of love will be set up, and someone from David's family will rule with fairness. He will do what is right and quickly bring justice.
Isa16:6 We have heard of Moab's pride. Its people strut and boast, but without reason.
Isa16:7 Tell everyone in Moab to mourn for their nation. Tell them to cry and weep for those fancy raisins of Kir-Hareseth.
Isa16:8 Vineyards near Heshbon and Sibmah have turned brown. The rulers of nations used to get drunk on wine from those vineyards that spread to Jazer, then across the desert and beyond the sea.
Isa16:9 Now I mourn like Jazer for the vineyards of Sibmah. I shed tears for Heshbon and for Elealeh. There will be no more harvest celebrations
Isa16:10 or joyful and happy times, while bringing in the crops. Singing and shouting are gone from the vineyards. There are no joyful shouts where grapes were pressed. God has silenced them all.
Isa16:11 Deep in my heart I hurt for Moab and Kir-Heres.
Isa16:12 It's useless for Moab's people to wear themselves out by going to their altars to worship and pray.
Isa16:13 The Lord has already said all of this about Moab.
Isa16:14 Now he says, "The contract of a hired worker is good for three years, but Moab's glory and greatness won't last any longer than that. Only a few of its people will survive, and they will be left helpless."
Isa17:1 This is a message about Damascus: Damascus is doomed! It will end up in ruins.
Isa17:2 The villages around Aroer will be deserted, with only sheep living there and no one to bother them.
Isa17:3 Israel will lose its fortresses. The kingdom of Damascus will be destroyed; its survivors will suffer the same fate as Israel. The Lord All-Powerful has promised this.
Isa17:4 When that time comes, the glorious nation of Israel will be brought down; its prosperous people will be skin and bones.
Isa17:5 Israel will be like wheat fields in Rephaim Valley picked clean of grain.
Isa17:6 It will be like an olive tree beaten with a stick, leaving two or three olives or maybe four or five on the highest or most fruitful branches. The Lord God of Israel has promised this.
Isa17:7 At that time the people will turn and trust their Creator, the holy God of Israel.
Isa17:8 They have built altars and places for burning incense to their goddess Asherah, and they have set up sacred poles for her. But they will stop worshiping at these places.
Isa17:9 Israel captured powerful cities and chased out the people who lived there. But these cities will lie in ruins, covered over with weeds and underbrush.
Isa17:10 Israel, you have forgotten the God who saves you, the one who is the mighty rock where you find protection. You plant the finest flowers to honor a foreign god.
Isa17:11 The plants may sprout and blossom that very same morning, but it will do you no good, because you will suffer endless agony.
Isa17:12 The nations are a noisy, thunderous sea.
Isa17:13 But even if they roar like a fearsome flood, God will give the command to turn them back. They will be like dust, or like a tumbleweed blowing across the hills in a windstorm.
Isa17:14 In the evening their attack is fierce, but by morning they are destroyed. This is what happens to those who raid and rob us.
Isa18:1 Downstream from Ethiopia lies the country of Egypt, swarming with insects.
Isa18:2 Egypt sends messengers up the Nile River on ships made of reeds. Send them fast to Ethiopia, whose people are tall and have smooth skin. Their land is divided by rivers; they are strong and brutal, feared all over the world.
Isa18:3 Everyone on this earth, listen with care! A signal will be given on the mountains, and you will hear a trumpet.
Isa18:4 The Lord said to me, "I will calmly look down from my home above -  as calmly as the sun at noon or clouds in the heat of harvest season."
Isa18:5 Before the blossoms can turn into grapes, God will cut off the sprouts and hack off the branches.
Isa18:6 Ethiopians will be food for mountain buzzards during the summer and for wild animals during the winter.
Isa18:7 Those Ethiopians are tall and their skin is smooth. They are feared all over the world, because they are strong and brutal. But at that time they will come from their land divided by rivers, and they will bring gifts to the Lord All-Powerful, who is worshiped on Mount Zion.
Isa19:1 This is a message about Egypt: The Lord comes to Egypt, riding swiftly on a cloud. The people are weak from fear. Their idols tremble as he approaches and says,
Isa19:2 "I will punish Egypt with civil war -  neighbors, cities, and kingdoms will fight each other.
Isa19:3 "Egypt will be discouraged when I confuse their plans. They will try to get advice from their idols, from the spirits of the dead, and from fortunetellers.
Isa19:4 I will put the Egyptians under the power of a cruel, heartless king. I, the Lord All-Powerful, have promised this."
Isa19:5 The Nile River will dry up and become parched land.
Isa19:6 Its streams will stink, Egypt will have no water, and the reeds and tall grass will dry up.
Isa19:7 Fields along the Nile will be completely barren; every plant will disappear.
Isa19:8 Those who fish in the Nile will be discouraged and mourn.
Isa19:9 None of the cloth makers will know what to do, and they will turn pale.
Isa19:10 Weavers will be confused; paid workers will cry and mourn.
Isa19:11 The king's officials in Zoan are foolish themselves and give stupid advice. How can they say to him, "We are very wise, and our families go back to kings of long ago?"
Isa19:12 Where are those wise men now? If they can, let them say what the Lord All-Powerful intends for Egypt.
Isa19:13 The royal officials in Zoan and in Memphis are foolish and deceived. The leaders in every state have given bad advice to the nation.
Isa19:14 The Lord has confused Egypt; its leaders have made it stagger and vomit like a drunkard.
Isa19:15 No one in Egypt can do a thing, no matter who they are.
Isa19:16 When the Lord All-Powerful punishes Egypt with his mighty arm, the Egyptians will become terribly weak and will tremble with fear.
Isa19:17 They will be so terrified of Judah that they will be frightened by the very mention of its name. This will happen because of what the Lord All-Powerful is planning against Egypt.
Isa19:18 The time is coming when Hebrew will be spoken in five Egyptian cities, and their people will become followers of the Lord . One of these cities will be called City of the Sun.
Isa19:19 In the heart of Egypt an altar will be set up for the Lord ; at its border a shrine will be built to honor him.
Isa19:20 These will remind the Egyptians that the Lord All-Powerful is with them. And when they are in trouble and ask for help, he will send someone to rescue them from their enemies.
Isa19:21 The Lord will show the Egyptians who he is, and they will know and worship the Lord . They will bring him sacrifices and offerings, and they will keep their promises to him.
Isa19:22 After the Lord has punished Egypt, the people will turn to him. Then he will answer their prayers, and the Egyptians will be healed.
Isa19:23 At that time a good road will run from Egypt to Assyria. The Egyptians and the Assyrians will travel back and forth from Egypt to Assyria, and they will worship together.
Isa19:24 Israel will join with these two countries. They will be a blessing to everyone on earth,
Isa19:25 then the Lord All-Powerful will bless them by saying, "The Egyptians are my people. I created the Assyrians and chose the Israelites."
Isa20:1 King Sargon of Assyria gave orders for his army commander to capture the city of Ashdod.
Isa20:2 About this same time the Lord had told me, "Isaiah, take off everything, including your sandals!" I did this and went around naked and barefoot
Isa20:3 for three years. Then the Lord said: What Isaiah has done is a warning to Egypt and Ethiopia.
Isa20:4 Everyone in these two countries will be led away naked and barefoot by the king of Assyria. Young or old, they will be taken prisoner, and Egypt will be disgraced.
Isa20:5 They will be confused and frustrated, because they depended on Ethiopia and bragged about Egypt.
Isa20:6 When this happens, the people who live along the coast will say, "Look what happened to them! We ran to them for safety, hoping they would protect us from the king of Assyria. But now, there is no escape for us."
Isa21:1 This is a message about a desert beside the sea: Enemies from a hostile nation attack like a whirlwind from the Southern Desert.
Isa21:2 What a horrible vision was shown to me -  a vision of betrayal and destruction. Tell Elam and Media to surround and attack the Babylonians. The Lord has sworn to end the suffering they caused.
Isa21:3 I'm in terrible pain like a woman giving birth. I'm shocked and hurt so much that I can't hear or see.
Isa21:4 My head spins; I'm horrified! Early evening, my favorite time, has become a nightmare.
Isa21:5 In Babylon the high officials were having a feast. They were eating and drinking, when someone shouted, "Officers, take your places! Grab your shields."
Isa21:6 The Lord said to me, "Send guards to find out what's going on.
Isa21:7 When they see cavalry troops and columns of soldiers on donkeys and camels, tell them to be ready!"
Isa21:8 Then a guard said, "I have stood day and night on this watchtower, Lord.
Isa21:9 Now I see column after column of cavalry troops." Right away someone shouted, "Babylon has fallen! Every idol in the city lies broken on the ground."
Isa21:10 Then I said, "My people, you have suffered terribly, but I have a message for you from the Lord All-Powerful, the God of Israel."
Isa21:11 This is a message about Dumah: From the country of Seir, someone shouts to me, "Guard, how much longer before daylight?"
Isa21:12 From my guard post, I answered, "Morning will soon be here, but night will return. If you want to know more, come back later."
Isa21:13 This is a message for Arabs who live in the barren desert in the region of Dedan: You must order your caravans
Isa21:14 to bring water for those who are thirsty. You people of Tema must bring food for the hungry refugees.
Isa21:15 They are worn out and weary from being chased by enemies with swords and arrows.
Isa21:16 The Lord said to me: A year from now the glory of the people of Kedar will all come to an end, just as a worker's contract ends after a year.
Isa21:17 Only a few of their warriors will be left with bows and arrows. This is a promise that I, the Lord God of Israel, have made.
Isa22:1 This is a message about Vision Valley: Why are you celebrating on the flat roofs of your houses?
Isa22:2 Your city is filled with noisy shouts. Those who lie drunk in your streets were not killed in battle.
Isa22:3 Your leaders ran away, but they were captured without a fight. No matter how far they ran, they were found and caught.
Isa22:4 Then I said, "Leave me alone! Let me cry bitter tears. My people have been destroyed, so don't try to comfort me."
Isa22:5 The Lord All-Powerful had chosen a time for noisy shouts and confusion to fill Vision Valley, and for everyone to beg the mountains for help.
Isa22:6 The people of Elam and Kir attacked with chariots and carried shields.
Isa22:7 Your most beautiful valleys were covered with chariots; your cities were surrounded by cavalry troops.
Isa22:8 Judah was left defenseless. At that time you trusted in the weapons you had stored in Forest Palace.
Isa22:9 You saw the holes in the outer wall of Jerusalem, and you brought water from the lower pool.
Isa22:10 You counted the houses in Jerusalem and tore down some of them, so you could get stones to repair the city wall.
Isa22:11 Then you built a large tank between the walls to store the water. But you refused to trust the God who planned this long ago and made it happen.
Isa22:12 When all of this happened, the Lord All-Powerful told you to weep and mourn, to shave your heads, and wear sackcloth.
Isa22:13 But instead, you celebrated by feasting on beef and lamb and by drinking wine, because you said, "Let's eat and drink! Tomorrow we may die."
Isa22:14 The Lord All-Powerful has spoken to me this solemn promise: "I won't forgive them for this, not as long as they live."
Isa22:15 The Lord All-Powerful is sending you with this message for Shebna, the prime minister:
Isa22:16 Shebna, what gives you the right to have a tomb carved out of rock in this burial place of royalty? None of your relatives are buried here.
Isa22:17 You may be powerful, but the Lord is about to snatch you up and throw you away.
Isa22:18 He will roll you into a ball and throw you into a wide open country, where you will die and your chariots will be destroyed. You're a disgrace to those you serve.
Isa22:19 The Lord is going to take away your job!
Isa22:20 He will give your official robes and your authority to his servant Eliakim son of Hilkiah. Eliakim will be like a father to the people of Jerusalem and to the royal family of Judah.
Isa22:21 ...
Isa22:22 The Lord will put him in charge of the key that belongs to King David's family. No one will be able to unlock what he locks, and no one will be able to lock what he unlocks.
Isa22:23 The Lord will make him as firm in his position as a tent peg hammered in the ground, and Eliakim will bring honor to his family.
Isa22:24 His children and relatives will be supported by him, like pans hanging from a peg on the wall.
Isa22:25 That peg is fastened firmly now, but someday it will be shaken loose and fall down. Then everything that was hanging on it will be destroyed. This is what the Lord All-Powerful has promised.
Isa23:1 This is a message from distant islands about the city of Tyre: Cry, you seagoing ships! Tyre and its houses lie in ruins.
Isa23:2 Mourn in silence, you shop owners of Sidon, you people on the coast. Your sailors crossed oceans, making your city rich.
Isa23:3 Your merchants sailed the seas, making you wealthy by trading with nation after nation. They brought back grain that grew along the Nile.
Isa23:4 Sidon, you are a mighty fortress built along the sea. But you will be disgraced like a married woman who never had children.
Isa23:5 When Egypt hears about Tyre, it will tremble.
Isa23:6 All of you along the coast had better cry and sail far across the ocean.
Isa23:7 Can this be the happy city that has stood for centuries? Its people have spread to distant lands;
Isa23:8 its merchants were kings honored all over the world. Who planned to destroy Tyre?
Isa23:9 The Lord All-Powerful planned it to bring shame and disgrace to those who are honored by everyone on earth.
Isa23:10 People of Tyre, your harbor is destroyed! You will have to become farmers just like the Egyptians.
Isa23:11 The Lord 's hand has reached across the sea, upsetting the nations. He has given a command to destroy fortresses in the land of Canaan.
Isa23:12 The Lord has said to the people of Sidon, "Your celebrating is over -  you are crushed. Even if you escape to Cyprus, you won't find peace."
Isa23:13 Look what the Assyrians have done to Babylonia! They have attacked, destroying every palace in the land. Now wild animals live among the ruins.
Isa23:14 Not a fortress will be left standing, so tell all the seagoing ships to mourn.
Isa23:15 The city of Tyre will be forgotten for seventy years, which is the lifetime of a king. Then Tyre will be like that evil woman in the song:
Isa23:16 You're gone and forgotten, you evil woman! So strut through the town, singing and playing your favorite tune to be remembered again.
Isa23:17 At the end of those seventy years, the Lord will let Tyre get back into business. The city will be like a woman who sells her body to everyone of every nation on earth,
Isa23:18 but none of what is earned will be kept in the city. That money will belong to the Lord , and it will be used to buy more than enough food and good clothes for those who worship the Lord .
Isa24:1 The Lord is going to twist the earth out of shape and turn it into a desert. Everyone will be scattered,
Isa24:2 including ordinary people and priests, slaves and slave owners, buyers and sellers, lenders and borrowers, the rich and the poor.
Isa24:3 The earth will be stripped bare and left that way. This is what the Lord has promised.
Isa24:4 The earth wilts away; its mighty leaders melt to nothing.
Isa24:5 The earth is polluted because its people disobeyed the laws of God, breaking their agreement that was to last forever.
Isa24:6 The earth is under a curse; its people are dying out because of their sins.
Isa24:7 Grapevines have dried up: wine is almost gone -  mournful sounds are heard instead of joyful shouts.
Isa24:8 No one plays tambourines or stringed instruments; all noisy celebrating has come to an end.
Isa24:9 They no longer sing as they drink their wine, and it tastes sour.
Isa24:10 Towns are crushed and in chaos; houses are locked tight.
Isa24:11 Happy times have disappeared from the earth, and people shout in the streets, "We're out of wine!"
Isa24:12 Cities are destroyed; their gates are torn down.
Isa24:13 Nations will be stripped bare, like olive trees or vineyards after the harvest season.
Isa24:14 People in the west shout; they joyfully praise the majesty of the Lord .
Isa24:15 And so, everyone in the east and those on the islands should praise the Lord , the God of Israel.
Isa24:16 From all over the world songs of praise are heard for the God of justice. But I feel awful, terribly miserable. Can anyone be trusted? So many are treacherous!
Isa24:17 Terror, traps, and pits are waiting for everyone.
Isa24:18 If you are terrified and run, you will fall into a pit; if you crawl out of the pit, you will get caught in a trap. The sky has split apart like a window thrown open. The foundations of the earth have been shaken;
Isa24:19 the earth is shattered, ripped to pieces.
Isa24:20 It staggers and shakes like a drunkard or a hut in a windstorm. It is burdened down with sin; the earth will fall, never again to get up.
Isa24:21 On that day the Lord will punish the powers in the heavens and the kings of the earth.
Isa24:22 He will put them in a pit and keep them prisoner. Then later on, he will punish them.
Isa24:23 The moon and sun will both be embarrassed and ashamed. The Lord All-Powerful will rule on Mount Zion in Jerusalem, where he will show its rulers his wonderful glory.
Isa25:1 You, Lord , are my God! I will praise you for doing the wonderful things you had planned and promised since ancient times.
Isa25:2 You have destroyed the fortress of our enemies, leaving their city in ruins. Nothing in that foreign city will ever be rebuilt.
Isa25:3 Now strong and cruel nations will fear and honor you.
Isa25:4 You have been a place of safety for the poor and needy in times of trouble. Brutal enemies pounded us like a heavy rain or the heat of the sun at noon, but you were our shelter.
Isa25:5 Those wild foreigners struck like scorching desert heat. But you were like a cloud, protecting us from the sun. You kept our enemies from singing songs of victory.
Isa25:6 On this mountain the Lord All-Powerful will prepare for all nations a feast of the finest foods. Choice wines and the best meats will be served.
Isa25:7 Here the Lord will strip away the burial clothes that cover the nations.
Isa25:8 The Lord All-Powerful will destroy the power of death and wipe away all tears. No longer will his people be insulted everywhere. The Lord has spoken!
Isa25:9 At that time, people will say, "The Lord has saved us! Let's celebrate. We waited and hoped -  now our God is here."
Isa25:10 The powerful arm of the Lord will protect this mountain. The Moabites will be put down and trampled on like straw in a pit of manure.
Isa25:11 They will struggle to get out, but God will humiliate them no matter how hard they try.
Isa25:12 The walls of their fortresses will be knocked down and scattered in the dirt.
Isa26:1 The time is coming when the people of Judah will sing this song: "Our city is protected. The Lord is our fortress, and he gives us victory.
Isa26:2 Open the city gates for a law-abiding nation that is faithful to God.
Isa26:3 The Lord gives perfect peace to those whose faith is firm.
Isa26:4 So always trust the Lord because he is forever our mighty rock.
Isa26:5 God has put down our enemies in their mountain city and rubbed it in the dirt.
Isa26:6 Now the poor and abused stomp all over that city."
Isa26:7 Our Lord , you always do right, and you make the path smooth for those who obey you.
Isa26:8 You are the one we trust to bring about justice; above all else we want your name to be honored.
Isa26:9 Throughout the night, my heart searches for you, because your decisions show everyone on this earth how to live right.
Isa26:10 Even when the wicked are treated with mercy in this land of justice, they do wrong and are blind to your glory, our Lord .
Isa26:11 Your hand is raised and ready to punish them, but they don't see it. Put them to shame! Show how much you care for us and throw them into the fire intended for your enemies.
Isa26:12 You will give us peace, Lord , because everything we have done was by your power.
Isa26:13 Others have ruled over us besides you, our Lord God, but we obey only you.
Isa26:14 Those enemies are now dead and can never live again. You have punished them -  they are destroyed, completely forgotten.
Isa26:15 Our nation has grown because of you, our Lord . We have more land than before, and you are honored.
Isa26:16 When you punished our people, they turned and prayed to you, our Lord .
Isa26:17 Because of what you did to us, we suffered like a woman about to give birth.
Isa26:18 But instead of having a child, our terrible pain produced only wind. We have won no victories, and we have no descendants to take over the earth.
Isa26:19 Your people will rise to life! Tell them to leave their graves and celebrate with shouts. You refresh the earth like morning dew; you give life to the dead.
Isa26:20 Go inside and lock the doors, my people. Hide there for a little while, until the Lord is no longer angry.
Isa26:21 The Lord will come out to punish everyone on earth for their sins. And when he does, those who did violent crimes will be known and punished.
Isa27:1 On that day, Leviathan, the sea monster, will squirm and try to escape, but the Lord will kill him with a cruel, sharp sword. The Lord said:
Isa27:2 At that time you must sing about a fruitful vineyard.
Isa27:3 I, the Lord , will protect it and always keep it watered. I will guard it day and night to keep it from harm.
Isa27:4 I am no longer angry. But if it produces thorns, I will go to war against it and burn it to the ground.
Isa27:5 Yet if the vineyard depends on me for protection, it will become my friend and be at peace with me.
Isa27:6 Someday Israel will take root like a vine. It will blossom and bear fruit that covers the earth.
Isa27:7 I, the Lord , didn't punish and kill the people of Israel as fiercely as I punished and killed their enemies.
Isa27:8 I carefully measured out Israel's punishment and sent the scorching heat to chase them far away.
Isa27:9 There's only one way that Israel's sin and guilt can be completely forgiven: They must crush the stones of every pagan altar and place of worship.
Isa27:10 Fortress cities are left like a desert where no one lives. Cattle walk through the ruins, stripping the trees bare.
Isa27:11 When broken branches fall to the ground, women pick them up to feed the fire. But these people are so stupid that the God who created them will show them no mercy.
Isa27:12 The time is coming when the Lord will shake the land between the Euphrates River and the border of Egypt, and one by one he will bring all of his people together.
Isa27:13 A loud trumpet will be heard. Then the people of Israel who were dragged away to Assyria and Egypt will return to worship the Lord on his holy mountain in Jerusalem.
Isa28:1 The city of Samaria above a fertile valley is in for trouble! Its leaders are drunkards, who stuff themselves with food and wine. But they will be like flowers that dry up and wilt.
Isa28:2 Only the Lord is strong and powerful! His mighty hand will strike them down with the force of a hailstorm or a mighty whirlwind or an overwhelming flood.
Isa28:3 Every drunkard in Ephraim takes pride in Samaria, but it will be crushed.
Isa28:4 Samaria above a fertile valley will quickly lose its glory. It will be gobbled down like the first ripe fig at harvest season.
Isa28:5 When this time comes, the Lord All-Powerful will be a glorious crown for his people who survive.
Isa28:6 He will see that justice rules and that his people are able to defend their cities.
Isa28:7 Priests and prophets stumble because they are drunk. Their minds are too confused to receive God's messages or give honest decisions.
Isa28:8 Their tables are covered, completely covered, with their stinking vomit.
Isa28:9 You drunken leaders are like babies! How can you possibly understand or teach the Lord 's message?
Isa28:10 You don't even listen -  all you hear is senseless sound after senseless sound.
Isa28:11 So, the Lord will speak to his people in strange sounds and foreign languages.
Isa28:12 He promised you perfect peace and rest, but you refused to listen.
Isa28:13 Now his message to you will be senseless sound after senseless sound. Then you will fall backwards, injured and trapped.
Isa28:14 You rulers of Jerusalem do nothing but sneer; now you must listen to what the Lord says.
Isa28:15 Do you think you have an agreement with death and the world of the dead? Why do you trust in your lies to keep you safe from danger and the mighty flood?
Isa28:16 And so the Lord says, "I'm laying a firm foundation for the city of Zion. It's a valuable cornerstone proven to be trustworthy; no one who trusts it will ever be disappointed.
Isa28:17 Justice and fairness will be the measuring lines that help me build." Hailstones and floods will destroy and wash away your shelter of lies.
Isa28:18 Your agreement with death and the world of the dead will be broken. Then angry, roaring waves will sweep over you.
Isa28:19 Morning, noon, and night an overwhelming flood will wash you away. The terrible things that happen will teach you this lesson:
Isa28:20 Your bed is too short, your blanket too skimpy.
Isa28:21 The Lord will fiercely attack as he did at Mount Perazim and in Gibeon Valley. But this time the Lord will do something surprising, not what you expect.
Isa28:22 So you had better stop sneering or you will be in worse shape than ever before. I heard the Lord All-Powerful threaten the whole country with destruction.
Isa28:23 Pay close attention to what I am saying.
Isa28:24 Farmers don't just plow and break up the ground.
Isa28:25 When a field is ready, they scatter the seeds of dill and cumin; they plant the seeds of wheat and barley in the proper places.
Isa28:26 They learn this from their God.
Isa28:27 After dill and cumin have been harvested, the stalks are pounded, not run over with a wagon.
Isa28:28 Wheat and barley are pounded, but not beaten to pulp; they are run over with a wagon, but not ground to dust.
Isa28:29 This wonderful knowledge comes from the Lord All-Powerful, who has such great wisdom.
Isa29:1 Jerusalem, city of David, the place of my altar, you are in for trouble! Celebrate your festivals year after year.
Isa29:2 I will still make you suffer, and your people will cry when I make an altar of you.
Isa29:3 I will surround you and prepare to attack from all sides.
Isa29:4 From deep in the earth, you will call out for help with only a faint whisper.
Isa29:5 Then your cruel enemies will suddenly be swept away like dust in a windstorm.
Isa29:6 I, the Lord All-Powerful, will come to your rescue with a thundering earthquake and a fiery whirlwind.
Isa29:7 Every brutal nation that attacks Jerusalem and makes it suffer will disappear like a dream when night is over.
Isa29:8 Those nations that attack Mount Zion will suffer from hunger and thirst. They will dream of food and drink but wake up weary and hungry and thirsty as ever.
Isa29:9 Be shocked and stunned, you prophets! Refuse to see. Get drunk and stagger, but not from wine.
Isa29:10 The Lord has made you drowsy; he put you into a deep sleep and covered your head.
Isa29:11 Now his message is like a sealed letter to you. Some of you say, "We can't read it, because it's sealed."
Isa29:12 Others say, "We can't read it, because we don't know how to read."
Isa29:13 The Lord has said: "These people praise me with their words, but they never really think about me. They worship me by repeating rules made up by humans.
Isa29:14 So once again I will do things that shock and amaze them, and I will destroy the wisdom of those who claim to know and understand."
Isa29:15 You are in for trouble, if you try to hide your plans from the Lord ! Or if you think what you do in the dark can't be seen.
Isa29:16 You have it all backwards. A clay dish doesn't say to the potter, "You didn't make me. You don't even know how."
Isa29:17 Soon the forest of Lebanon will become a field with crops, thick as a forest.
Isa29:18 The deaf will be able to hear whatever is read to them; the blind will be freed from a life of darkness.
Isa29:19 The poor and the needy will celebrate and shout because of the Lord , the holy God of Israel.
Isa29:20 All who are cruel and arrogant will be gone forever. Those who live by crime will disappear,
Isa29:21 together with everyone who tells lies in court and keeps innocent people from getting a fair trial.
Isa29:22 The Lord who rescued Abraham has this to say about Jacob's descendants: "They will no longer be ashamed and disgraced.
Isa29:23 When they see how great I have made their nation, they will praise and honor me, the holy God of Israel.
Isa29:24 Everyone who is confused will understand, and all who have complained will obey my teaching."
Isa30:1 This is the Lord 's message for his rebellious people: "You follow your own plans instead of mine; you make treaties without asking me, and you keep on sinning.
Isa30:2 You trust Egypt for protection. So you refuse my advice and send messengers to Egypt to beg their king for help.
Isa30:3 You will be disappointed, completely disgraced for trusting Egypt.
Isa30:4 The king's power reaches from the city of Zoan as far south as Hanes.
Isa30:5 But Egypt can't protect you, and to trust that nation is useless and foolish."
Isa30:6 This is a message about the animals of the Southern Desert: You people carry treasures on donkeys and camels. You travel to a feeble nation through a troublesome desert filled with lions and flying fiery dragons.
Isa30:7 Egypt can't help you! That's why I call that nation a helpless monster."
Isa30:8 The Lord told me to write down his message for his people, so that it would be there forever.
Isa30:9 They have turned against the Lord and can't be trusted. They have refused his teaching
Isa30:10 and have said to his messengers and prophets: Don't tell us what God has shown you and don't preach the truth. Just say what we want to hear, even if it's false.
Isa30:11 Stop telling us what God has said! We don't want to hear any more about the holy God of Israel.
Isa30:12 Now this is the answer of the holy God of Israel: "You rejected my message, and you trust in violence and lies.
Isa30:13 This sin is like a crack that makes a high wall quickly crumble
Isa30:14 and shatter like a crushed bowl. There's not a piece left big enough to carry hot coals or to dip out water."
Isa30:15 The holy Lord God of Israel had told all of you, "I will keep you safe if you turn back to me and calm down. I will make you strong if you quietly trust me." Then you stubbornly
Isa30:16 said, "No! We will safely escape on speedy horses." But those who chase you will be even faster.
Isa30:17 As few as five of them, or even one, will be enough to chase a thousand of you. Finally, all that will be left will be a few survivors as lonely as a flag pole on a barren hill.
Isa30:18 The Lord God is waiting to show how kind he is and to have pity on you. The Lord always does right; he blesses those who trust him.
Isa30:19 People of Jerusalem, you don't need to cry anymore. The Lord is kind, and as soon as he hears your cries for help, he will come.
Isa30:20 The Lord has given you trouble and sorrow as your food and drink. But now you will again see the Lord, your teacher, and he will guide you.
Isa30:21 Whether you turn to the right or to the left, you will hear a voice saying, "This is the road! Now follow it."
Isa30:22 Then you will treat your idols of silver and gold like garbage; you will throw them away like filthy rags.
Isa30:23 The Lord will send rain to water the seeds you have planted - your fields will produce more crops than you need, and your cattle will graze in open pastures.
Isa30:24 Even the oxen and donkeys that plow your fields will be fed the finest grain.
Isa30:25 On that day people will be slaughtered and towers destroyed, but streams of water will flow from high hills and towering mountains.
Isa30:26 Then the Lord will bandage his people's injuries and heal the wounds he has caused. The moon will shine as bright as the sun, and the sun will shine seven times brighter than usual. It will be like the light of seven days all at once.
Isa30:27 The Lord is coming from far away with his fiery anger and thick clouds of smoke. His angry words flame up like a destructive fire;
Isa30:28 he breathes out a flood that comes up to the neck. He sifts the nations and destroys them. Then he puts a bridle in every foreigner's mouth and leads them to doom.
Isa30:29 The Lord 's people will sing as they do when they celebrate a religious festival at night. The Lord is Israel's mighty rock, and his people will be as happy as they are when they follow the sound of flutes to the mountain where he is worshiped.
Isa30:30 The Lord will get furious. His fearsome voice will be heard, his arm will be seen ready to strike, and his anger will be like a destructive fire, followed by thunderstorms and hailstones.
Isa30:31 When the Assyrians hear the Lord 's voice and see him striking with his iron rod, they will be terrified.
Isa30:32 He will attack them in battle, and each time he strikes them, it will be to the music of tambourines and harps.
Isa30:33 Long ago the Lord got a place ready for burning the body of the dead king. The place for the fire is deep and wide, the wood is piled high, and the Lord will start the fire by breathing out flaming sulfur.
Isa31:1 You are in for trouble if you go to Egypt for help, or if you depend on an army of chariots or a powerful cavalry. Instead you should depend on and trust the holy Lord God of Israel.
Isa31:2 The Lord isn't stupid! He does what he promises, and he can bring doom. If you are cruel yourself, or help those who are evil, you will be destroyed.
Isa31:3 The Egyptians are mere humans. They aren't God. Their horses are made of flesh; they can't live forever. When the Lord shows his power, he will destroy the Egyptians and all who depend on them. Together they will fall.
Isa31:4 The Lord All-Powerful said to me, "I will roar and attack like a fearless lion not frightened by the shouts of shepherds trying to protect their sheep. That's how I will come down and fight on Mount Zion.
Isa31:5 I, the Lord All-Powerful, will protect Jerusalem like a mother bird circling over her nest."
Isa31:6 People of Israel, come back! You have completely turned from the Lord .
Isa31:7 The time is coming when you will throw away your idols of silver and gold, made by your sinful hands.
Isa31:8 The Assyrians will be killed, but not by the swords of humans. Their young men will try to escape, but they will be captured and forced into slavery.
Isa31:9 Their fortress will fall when terror strikes; their army officers will be frightened and run from the battle. This is what the Lord has said, the Lord whose fiery furnace is built on Mount Zion.
Isa32:1 A king and his leaders will rule with justice.
Isa32:2 They will be a place of safety from stormy winds, a stream in the desert, and a rock that gives shade from the heat of the sun.
Isa32:3 Then everyone who has eyes will open them and see, and those who have ears will pay attention.
Isa32:4 All who are impatient will take time to think; everyone who stutters will talk clearly.
Isa32:5 Fools will no longer be highly respected, and crooks won't be given positions of honor.
Isa32:6 Fools talk foolishness. They always make plans to do sinful things, to lie about the Lord , to let the hungry starve, and to keep water from those who are thirsty.
Isa32:7 Cruel people tell lies -  they do evil things, and make cruel plans to destroy the poor and needy, even when they beg for justice.
Isa32:8 But helpful people can always be trusted to make helpful plans.
Isa32:9 Listen to what I say, you women who are carefree and careless!
Isa32:10 You may not have worries now, but in about a year, the grape harvest will fail, and you will tremble.
Isa32:11 Shake and shudder, you women without a care! Strip off your clothes -  put on sackcloth.
Isa32:12 Slap your breasts in sorrow because of what happened to the fruitful fields and vineyards,
Isa32:13 and to the happy homes in Jerusalem. The land of my people is covered with thorns.
Isa32:14 The palace will be deserted, the crowded city empty. Fortresses and towers will forever become playgrounds for wild donkeys and pastures for sheep.
Isa32:15 When the Spirit is given to us from heaven, deserts will become orchards thick as fertile forests.
Isa32:16 Honesty and justice will prosper there,
Isa32:17 and justice will produce lasting peace and security.
Isa32:18 You, the Lord 's people, will live in peace, calm and secure,
Isa32:19 even if hailstones flatten forests and cities.
Isa32:20 You will have God's blessing, as you plant your crops beside streams, while your donkeys and cattle roam freely about.
Isa33:1 You defeated my people. Now you're in for trouble! You've never been destroyed, but you will be destroyed; you've never been betrayed, but you will be betrayed. When you have finished destroying and betraying, you will be destroyed and betrayed in return.
Isa33:2 Please, Lord , be kind to us! We depend on you. Make us strong each morning, and come to save us when we are in trouble.
Isa33:3 Nations scatter when you roar and show your greatness.
Isa33:4 We attack our enemies like swarms of locusts; we take everything that belongs to them.
Isa33:5 You, Lord , are above all others, and you live in the heavens. You have brought justice and fairness to Jerusalem;
Isa33:6 you are the foundation on which we stand today. You always save us and give true wisdom and knowledge. Nothing means more to us than obeying you.
Isa33:7 Listen! Our bravest soldiers are running through the streets, screaming for help. Our messengers hoped for peace, but came home crying.
Isa33:8 No one travels anymore; every road is empty. Treaties are broken, and no respect is shown to any who keep promises.
Isa33:9 Fields are dry and barren; Mount Lebanon wilts with shame. Sharon Valley is a desert; the forests of Bashan and Carmel have lost their leaves.
Isa33:10 But the Lord says, "Now I will do something and be greatly praised.
Isa33:11 Your deeds are straw that will be set on fire by your very own breath.
Isa33:12 You will be burned to ashes like thorns in a fire.
Isa33:13 Everyone, both far and near, come look at what I have done. See my mighty power!"
Isa33:14 Those terrible sinners on Mount Zion tremble as they ask in fear, "How can we possibly live where a raging fire never stops burning?"
Isa33:15 But there will be rewards for those who live right and tell the truth, for those who refuse to take money by force or accept bribes, for all who hate murder and violent crimes.
Isa33:16 They will live in a fortress high on a rocky cliff, where they will have food and plenty of water.
Isa33:17 With your own eyes you will see the glorious King; you will see his kingdom reaching far and wide.
Isa33:18 Then you will ask yourself, "Where are those officials who terrified us and forced us to pay such heavy taxes?"
Isa33:19 You will never again have to see the proud people who spoke a strange and foreign language you could not understand.
Isa33:20 Look to Mount Zion where we celebrate our religious festivals. You will see Jerusalem, secure as a tent with pegs that cannot be pulled up and fastened with ropes that can never be broken.
Isa33:21 Our wonderful Lord will be with us! There will be deep rivers and wide streams safe from enemy ships.
Isa33:22 The Lord is our judge and our ruler; the Lord is our king and will keep us safe.
Isa33:23 But your nation is a ship with its rigging loose, its mast shaky, and its sail not spread. Someday even you that are lame will take everything you want from your enemies.
Isa33:24 The Lord will forgive your sins, and none of you will say, "I feel sick."
Isa34:1 Everyone of every nation, the entire earth, and all of its creatures, come here and listen!
Isa34:2 The Lord is terribly angry with the nations; he has condemned them to be slaughtered.
Isa34:3 Their dead bodies will be left to rot and stink; their blood will flow down the mountains.
Isa34:4 Each star will disappear -  the sky will roll up like a scroll. Everything in the sky will dry up and wilt like leaves on a vine or fruit on a tree.
Isa34:5 After the sword of the Lord has done what it wants to the skies above, it will come down on Edom, the nation that the Lord has doomed for destruction.
Isa34:6 The sword of the Lord is covered with blood from lambs and goats, together with fat from kidneys of rams. This is because the Lord will slaughter many people and make a sacrifice of them in the city of Bozrah and everywhere else in Edom.
Isa34:7 Edom's leaders are wild oxen. They are powerful bulls, but they will die with the others. Their country will be soaked with their blood, and its soil made fertile with their fat.
Isa34:8 The Lord has chosen the year and the day, when he will take revenge and come to Zion's defense.
Isa34:9 Edom's streams will turn into tar and its soil into sulfur -  then the whole country will go up in flames.
Isa34:10 It will burn night and day and never stop smoking. Edom will be a desert, generation after generation; no one will ever travel through that land.
Isa34:11 Owls, hawks, and wild animals will make it their home. God will leave it in ruins, merely a pile of rocks.
Isa34:12 Edom will be called "Kingdom of Nothing." Its rulers will also be nothing.
Isa34:13 Its palaces and fortresses will be covered with thorns; only wolves and ostriches will make their home there.
Isa34:14 Wildcats and hyenas will hunt together, demons will scream to demons, and creatures of the night will live among the ruins.
Isa34:15 Owls will nest there to raise their young among its shadows, while families of buzzards circle around.
Isa34:16 In The Book of the Lord  you can search and find where it is written, "The Lord brought together all of his creatures by the power of his Spirit. Not one is missing."
Isa34:17 The Lord has decided where they each should live; they will be there forever, generation after generation.
Isa35:1 Thirsty deserts will be glad; barren lands will celebrate and blossom with flowers.
Isa35:2 Deserts will bloom everywhere and sing joyful songs. They will be as majestic as Mount Lebanon, as glorious as Mount Carmel or Sharon Valley. Everyone will see the wonderful splendor of the Lord our God.
Isa35:3 Here is a message for all who are weak, trembling, and worried:
Isa35:4 "Cheer up! Don't be afraid. Your God is coming to punish your enemies. God will take revenge on them and rescue you."
Isa35:5 The blind will see, and the ears of the deaf will be healed.
Isa35:6 Those who were lame will leap around like deer; tongues once silent will begin to shout. Water will rush through the desert.
Isa35:7 Scorching sand will turn into a lake, and thirsty ground will flow with fountains. Grass will grow in wetlands, where packs of wild dogs once made their home.
Isa35:8 A good road will be there, and it will be named "God's Sacred Highway." It will be for God's people; no one unfit to worship God will walk on that road. And no fools can travel on that highway.
Isa35:9 No lions or other wild animals will come near that road; only those the Lord has saved will travel there.
Isa35:10 The people the Lord has rescued will come back singing as they enter Zion. Happiness will be a crown they will always wear. They will celebrate and shout because all sorrows and worries will be gone far away.
Isa36:1 Hezekiah had been king of Judah for fourteen years when King Sennacherib of Assyria invaded the country and captured every walled city
Isa36:2 except Jerusalem. The Assyrian king ordered his army commander to leave the city of Lachish and to take a large army to Jerusalem. The commander went there and stood on the road near the cloth makers' shops along the canal from the upper pool.
Isa36:3 Three of the king's highest officials came out of Jerusalem to meet him. One of them was Hilkiah's son Eliakim, who was the prime minister. The other two were Shebna, assistant to the prime minister, and Joah son of Asaph, keeper of the government records.
Isa36:4 The Assyrian commander told them: I have a message for Hezekiah from the great king of Assyria. Ask Hezekiah why he feels so sure of himself.
Isa36:5 Does he think he can plan and win a war with nothing but words? Who is going to help him, now that he has turned against the king of Assyria?
Isa36:6 Is he depending on Egypt and its king? That's the same as leaning on a broken stick, and it will go right through his hand.
Isa36:7 Is Hezekiah now depending on the Lord , your God? Didn't Hezekiah tear down all except one of the Lord 's altars and places of worship? Didn't he tell the people of Jerusalem and Judah to worship at that one place?
Isa36:8 The king of Assyria wants to make a bet with you people! He will give you two thousand horses, if you have enough troops to ride them.
Isa36:9 How could you even defeat our lowest ranking officer, when you have to depend on Egypt for chariots and cavalry?
Isa36:10 Don't forget that it was the Lord who sent me here with orders to destroy your nation!
Isa36:11 Eliakim, Shebna, and Joah said, "Sir, we don't want the people listening from the city wall to understand what you are saying. So please speak to us in Aramaic instead of Hebrew."
Isa36:12 The Assyrian army commander answered, "My king sent me to speak to everyone, not just to you leaders. These people will soon have to eat their own body waste and drink their own urine! And so will the three of you!"
Isa36:13 Then, in a voice loud enough for everyone to hear, he shouted out in Hebrew: Listen to what the great king of Assyria says!
Isa36:14 Don't be fooled by Hezekiah. He can't save you.
Isa36:15 Don't trust him when he tells you that the Lord will protect you from the king of Assyria.
Isa36:16 Stop listening to Hezekiah. Pay attention to my king. Surrender to him. He will let you keep your own vineyards, fig trees, and cisterns
Isa36:17 for a while. Then he will come and take you away to a country just like yours, where you can plant vineyards and raise your own grain.
Isa36:18 Hezekiah claims the Lord will save you. But don't be fooled by him. Were any other gods able to defend their land against the king of Assyria?
Isa36:19 What happened to the gods of Hamath, Arpad, and Sepharvaim? Were the gods of Samaria able to protect their land against the Assyrian forces?
Isa36:20 None of these gods kept their people safe from the king of Assyria. Do you think the Lord , your God, can do any better?
Isa36:21 Eliakim, Shebna, and Joah had been warned by King Hezekiah not to answer the Assyrian commander. So they tore their clothes in sorrow and reported to Hezekiah everything the commander had said.
Isa36:22 ...
Isa37:1 As soon as Hezekiah heard the news, he tore off his clothes in sorrow and put on sackcloth. Then he went into the temple of the Lord .
Isa37:2 He told Prime Minister Eliakim, Assistant Prime Minister Shebna, and the senior priests to dress in sackcloth and tell me:
Isa37:3 Isaiah, these are difficult and disgraceful times. Our nation is like a woman too weak to give birth, when it's time for her baby to be born.
Isa37:4 Please pray for those of us who are left alive. The king of Assyria sent his army commander to insult the living God. Perhaps the Lord heard what he said and will do something, if you will pray.
Isa37:5 When these leaders came to me,
Isa37:6 I told them that the Lord had this message for Hezekiah: I am the Lord . Don't worry about the insulting things that have been said about me by these messengers from the king of Assyria.
Isa37:7 I will upset him with rumors about what's happening in his own country. He will go back, and there I will make him die a violent death.
Isa37:8 Meanwhile the commander of the Assyrian forces heard that his king had left the town of Lachish and was now attacking Libnah. So he went there.
Isa37:9 About this same time, the king of Assyria learned that King Tirhakah of Ethiopia was on his way to attack him. Then the king of Assyria sent some messengers with this note for Hezekiah:
Isa37:10 Don't trust your God or be fooled by his promise to defend Jerusalem against me.
Isa37:11 You have heard how we Assyrian kings have completely wiped out other nations. What makes you feel so safe?
Isa37:12 The Assyrian kings before me destroyed the towns of Gozan, Haran, Rezeph, and everyone from Eden who lived in Telassar. What good did their gods do them?
Isa37:13 The kings of Hamath, Arpad, Sepharvaim, Hena, and Ivvah have all disappeared.
Isa37:14 After Hezekiah had read the note from the king of Assyria, he took it to the temple and spread it out for the Lord to see.
Isa37:15 Then he prayed:
Isa37:16 Lord God All-Powerful of Israel, your throne is above the winged creatures. You created the heavens and the earth, and you alone rule the kingdoms of this world.
Isa37:17 Just look and see how Sennacherib has insulted you, the living God.
Isa37:18 It is true, our Lord , that Assyrian kings have turned nations into deserts.
Isa37:19 They destroyed the idols of wood and stone that the people of those nations had made and worshiped.
Isa37:20 But you are our Lord and our God! We ask you to keep us safe from the Assyrian king. Then everyone in every kingdom on earth will know that you are the only Lord .
Isa37:21 I went to Hezekiah and told him that the Lord God of Israel had said: Hezekiah, you prayed to me about King Sennacherib of Assyria. Now this is what I say to that king: The people of Jerusalem hate and make fun of you; they laugh behind your back.
Isa37:22 ...
Isa37:23 Sennacherib, you cursed, shouted, and sneered at me, the holy God of Israel.
Isa37:24 You let your officials insult me, the Lord. And here is what you have said about yourself, "I led my chariots to the highest heights of Lebanon's mountains. I went deep into its forest, cutting down the best cedar and cypress trees.
Isa37:25 I dried up every stream in the land of Egypt, and I drank water from wells I had dug."
Isa37:26 Sennacherib, now listen to me, the Lord . I planned all of this long ago. And you don't even know that I alone am the one who decided that you would do these things. I let you make ruins of fortified cities.
Isa37:27 Their people became weak, terribly confused. They were like wild flowers or like tender young grass growing on a flat roof or like a field of grain before it matures.
Isa37:28 I know all about you, even how fiercely angry you are with me.
Isa37:29 I have seen your pride and the tremendous hatred you have for me. Now I will put a hook in your nose, a bit in your mouth, then I will send you back to where you came from.
Isa37:30 Hezekiah, I will tell you what's going to happen. This year you will eat crops that grow on their own, and the next year you will eat whatever springs up where those crops grew. But the third year, you will plant grain and vineyards, and you will eat what you harvest.
Isa37:31 Those who survive in Judah will be like a vine that puts down deep roots and bears fruit.
Isa37:32 I, the Lord All-Powerful, will see to it that some who live in Jerusalem will survive.
Isa37:33 I promise that the king of Assyria won't get into Jerusalem, or shoot an arrow into the city, or even surround it and prepare to attack.
Isa37:34 As surely as I am the Lord , he will return by the way he came and will never enter Jerusalem.
Isa37:35 I will protect it for the sake of my own honor and because of the promise I made to my servant David.
Isa37:36 The Lord sent an angel to the camp of the Assyrians, and he killed one hundred eighty-five thousand of them all in one night. The next morning, the camp was full of dead bodies.
Isa37:37 After this, King Sennacherib went back to Assyria and lived in the city of Nineveh.
Isa37:38 One day he was worshiping in the temple of his god Nisroch, when his sons, Adrammelech and Sharezer, killed him with their swords. They escaped to the land of Ararat, and his son Esarhaddon became king.
Isa38:1 About this time, Hezekiah got sick and was almost dead. So I went in and told him, "The Lord says you won't ever get well. You are going to die, and so you had better start doing what needs to be done."
Isa38:2 Hezekiah turned toward the wall and prayed,
Isa38:3 "Don't forget that I have been faithful to you, Lord . I have obeyed you with all my heart, and I do whatever you say is right." After this, he cried hard.
Isa38:4 Then the Lord sent me
Isa38:5 with this message for Hezekiah: I am the Lord God, who was worshiped by your ancestor David. I heard you pray, and I saw you cry. I will let you live fifteen years more,
Isa38:6 while I protect you and your city from the king of Assyria.
Isa38:7 Now I will prove to you that I will keep my promise.
Isa38:8 Do you see the shadow made by the setting sun on the stairway built for King Ahaz? I will make the shadow go back ten steps. Then the shadow went back ten steps.
Isa38:9 This is what Hezekiah wrote after he got well:
Isa38:10 I thought I would die during my best years and stay as a prisoner forever in the world of the dead.
Isa38:11 I thought I would never again see you, my Lord , or any of the people who live on this earth.
Isa38:12 My life was taken from me like the tent that a shepherd pulls up and moves. You cut me off like thread from a weaver's loom; you make a wreck of me day and night.
Isa38:13 Until morning came, I thought you would crush my bones just like a hungry lion; both night and day you make a wreck of me.
Isa38:14 I cry like a swallow; I mourn like a dove. My eyes are red from looking to you, Lord . I am terribly abused. Please come and help me.
Isa38:15 There's nothing I can say in answer to you, since you are the one who has done this to me. My life has turned sour; I will limp until I die.
Isa38:16 Your words and your deeds bring life to everyone, including me. Please make me healthy and strong again.
Isa38:17 It was for my own good that I had such hard times. But your love protected me from doom in the deep pit, and you turned your eyes away from my sins.
Isa38:18 No one in the world of the dead can thank you or praise you; none of those in the deep pit can hope for you to show them how faithful you are.
Isa38:19 Only the living can thank you, as I am doing today. Each generation tells the next about your faithfulness.
Isa38:20 You, Lord , will save me, and every day that we live we will sing in your temple to the music of stringed instruments.
Isa38:21 I had told King Hezekiah's servants to put some mashed figs on the king's open sore, and he would get well.
Isa38:22 Then Hezekiah asked for proof that he would again worship in the Lord 's temple.
Isa39:1 Merodach Baladan, the son of Baladan, was now king of Babylonia. And when he learned that Hezekiah was well, he sent messengers with letters and a gift for him.
Isa39:2 Hezekiah welcomed the messengers and showed them all the silver, the gold, the spices, and the fine oils that were in his storehouse. He even showed them where he kept his weapons. Nothing in his palace or in his entire kingdom was kept hidden from them.
Isa39:3 I asked Hezekiah, "Where did these men come from? What did they want?" "They came all the way from Babylonia," Hezekiah answered.
Isa39:4 "What did you show them?" I asked. Hezekiah answered, "I showed them everything in my kingdom."
Isa39:5 Then I told Hezekiah: I have a message for you from the Lord All-Powerful.
Isa39:6 One day everything you and your ancestors have stored up will be taken to Babylonia. The Lord has promised that nothing will be left.
Isa39:7 Some of your own sons will be taken to Babylonia, where they will be disgraced and made to serve in the king's palace.
Isa39:8 Hezekiah thought, "At least our nation will be at peace for a while." So he told me, "The message you brought from the Lord is good."
Isa40:1 Our God has said: "Encourage my people! Give them comfort.
Isa40:2 Speak kindly to Jerusalem and announce: Your slavery is past; your punishment is over. I, the Lord , made you pay double for your sins."
Isa40:3 Someone is shouting: "Clear a path in the desert! Make a straight road for the Lord our God.
Isa40:4 Fill in the valleys; flatten every hill and mountain. Level the rough and rugged ground.
Isa40:5 Then the glory of the Lord will appear for all to see. The Lord has promised this!"
Isa40:6 Someone told me to shout, and I asked, "What should I shout?" We humans are merely grass, and we last no longer than wild flowers.
Isa40:7 At the Lord 's command, flowers and grass disappear, and so do we.
Isa40:8 Flowers and grass fade away, but what our God has said will never change.
Isa40:9 There is good news for the city of Zion. Shout it as loud as you can from the highest mountain. Don't be afraid to shout to the towns of Judah, "Your God is here!"
Isa40:10 Look! The powerful Lord God is coming to rule with his mighty arm. He brings with him what he has taken in war, and he rewards his people.
Isa40:11 The Lord cares for his nation, just as shepherds care for their flocks. He carries the lambs in his arms, while gently leading the mother sheep.
Isa40:12 Did any of you measure the ocean by yourself or stretch out the sky with your own hands? Did you put the soil of the earth in a bucket or weigh the hills and mountains on balance scales?
Isa40:13 Has anyone told the Lord  what he must do or given him advice?
Isa40:14 Did the Lord ask anyone to teach him wisdom and justice? Who gave him knowledge and understanding?
Isa40:15 To the Lord , all nations are merely a drop in a bucket or dust on balance scales; all of the islands are but a handful of sand.
Isa40:16 The cattle on Lebanon's mountains would not be enough to offer as a sacrifice to God, and the trees would not be enough for the fire.
Isa40:17 God thinks of the nations as far less than nothing.
Isa40:18 Who compares with God? Is anything like him?
Isa40:19 Is an idol at all like God? It is made of bronze with a thin layer of gold, and decorated with silver.
Isa40:20 Or special wood may be chosen because it doesn't rot -  then skilled hands take care to make an idol that won't fall on its face.
Isa40:21 Don't you know? Haven't you heard? Isn't it clear that God created the world?
Isa40:22 God is the one who rules the whole earth, and we that live here are merely insects. He spread out the heavens like a curtain or an open tent.
Isa40:23 God brings down rulers and turns them into nothing.
Isa40:24 They are like flowers freshly sprung up and starting to grow. But when God blows on them, they wilt and are carried off like straw in a storm.
Isa40:25 The holy God asks, "Who compares with me? Is anyone my equal?"
Isa40:26 Look at the evening sky! Who created the stars? Who gave them each a name? Who leads them like an army? The Lord is so powerful that none of the stars are ever missing.
Isa40:27 You people of Israel, say, "God pays no attention to us! He doesn't care if we are treated unjustly." But how can you say that?
Isa40:28 Don't you know? Haven't you heard? The Lord is the eternal God, Creator of the earth. He never gets weary or tired; his wisdom cannot be measured.
Isa40:29 The Lord gives strength to those who are weary.
Isa40:30 Even young people get tired, then stumble and fall.
Isa40:31 But those who trust the Lord will find new strength. They will be strong like eagles soaring upward on wings; they will walk and run without getting tired.
Isa41:1 Be silent and listen, every island in the sea. Have courage and come near, every one of you nations. Let's settle this matter!
Isa41:2 Who appointed this ruler from the east? Who puts nations and kings in his power? His sword and his arrows turn them to dust blown by the wind.
Isa41:3 He goes after them so quickly that his feet barely touch the ground -  he doesn't even get hurt.
Isa41:4 Who makes these things happen? Who controls human events? I do! I am the Lord . I was there at the beginning; I will be there at the end.
Isa41:5 Islands and foreign nations saw what I did and trembled as they came near.
Isa41:6 Worshipers of idols comfort each other, saying, "Don't worry!"
Isa41:7 Woodcarvers, goldsmiths, and other workers encourage one another and say, "We've done a great job!" Then they nail the idol down, so it won't fall over.
Isa41:8 Israel, you are my servant. I chose you, the family of my friend Abraham.
Isa41:9 From far across the earth I brought you here and said, "You are my chosen servant. I haven't forgotten you."
Isa41:10 Don't be afraid. I am with you. Don't tremble with fear. I am your God. I will make you strong, as I protect you with my arm and give you victories.
Isa41:11 Everyone who hates you will be terribly disgraced; those who attack will vanish into thin air.
Isa41:12 You will look around for those brutal enemies, but you won't find them because they will be gone.
Isa41:13 I am the Lord your God. I am holding your hand, so don't be afraid. I am here to help you.
Isa41:14 People of Israel, don't worry, though others may say, "Israel is only a worm!" I am the holy God of Israel, who saves and protects you.
Isa41:15 I will let you be like a log covered with sharp spikes. You will grind and crush every mountain and hill until they turn to dust.
Isa41:16 A strong wind will scatter them in all directions. Then you will celebrate and praise me, your Lord , the holy God of Israel.
Isa41:17 When the poor and needy are dying of thirst and cannot find water, I, the Lord God of Israel, will come to their rescue. I won't forget them.
Isa41:18 I will make rivers flow on mountain peaks. I will send streams to fill the valleys. Dry and barren land will flow with springs and become a lake.
Isa41:19 I will fill the desert with all kinds of trees -  cedars, acacias, and myrtles; olive and cypress trees; fir trees and pines.
Isa41:20 Everyone will see this and know that I, the holy Lord God of Israel, created it all.
Isa41:21 I am the Lord , the King of Israel! Come argue your case with me. Present your evidence.
Isa41:22 Come near me, you idols. Tell us about the past, and we will think about it. Tell us about the future, so we will know what is going to happen.
Isa41:23 Prove that you are gods by making your predictions come true. Do something good or evil, so we can be amazed and terrified.
Isa41:24 You idols are nothing, and you are powerless. To worship you would be disgusting.
Isa41:25 I, the Lord , appointed a ruler in the north; now he comes from the east to honor my name. He tramples kings like mud, as potters trample clay.
Isa41:26 Did any of you idols predict what would happen? Did any of you get it right? None of you told about this or even spoke a word.
Isa41:27 I was the first to tell the people of Jerusalem, "Look, it's happening!" I was the one who announced this good news to Zion.
Isa41:28 None of these idols are able to give advice or answer questions.
Isa41:29 They are nothing, and they can do nothing -  they are less than a passing breeze.
Isa42:1 Here is my servant! I have made him strong. He is my chosen one; I am pleased with him. I have given him my Spirit, and he will bring justice to the nations.
Isa42:2 He won't shout or yell or call out in the streets.
Isa42:3 He won't break off a bent reed or put out a dying flame, but he will make sure that justice is done.
Isa42:4 He won't quit or give up until he brings justice everywhere on earth, and people in foreign nations long for his teaching.
Isa42:5 I am the Lord God. I created the heavens like an open tent above. I made the earth and everything that grows on it. I am the source of life for all who live on this earth, so listen to what I say.
Isa42:6 I chose you to bring justice, and I am here at your side. I selected and sent you to bring light and my promise of hope to the nations.
Isa42:7 You will give sight to the blind; you will set prisoners free from dark dungeons.
Isa42:8 My name is the Lord ! I won't let idols or humans share my glory and praise.
Isa42:9 Everything has happened just as I said it would; now I will announce what will happen next.
Isa42:10 Tell the whole world to sing a new song to the Lord ! Tell those who sail the ocean and those who live far away to join in the praise.
Isa42:11 Tell the tribes of the desert and everyone in the mountains to celebrate and sing.
Isa42:12 Let them announce his praises everywhere.
Isa42:13 The Lord is marching out like an angry soldier, shouting with all his might while attacking his enemies.
Isa42:14 For a long time, I, the Lord , have held my temper; now I will scream and groan like a woman giving birth.
Isa42:15 I will destroy the mountains and what grows on them; I will dry up rivers and ponds.
Isa42:16 I will lead the blind on roads they have never known; I will guide them on paths they have never traveled. Their road is dark and rough, but I will give light to keep them from stumbling. This is my solemn promise.
Isa42:17 Everyone who worships idols as though they were gods will be terribly ashamed.
Isa42:18 You people are deaf and blind, but the Lord commands you to listen and to see.
Isa42:19 No one is as blind or deaf as his messenger, his chosen servant,
Isa42:20 who sees and hears so much, but pays no attention.
Isa42:21 The Lord always does right, and so he wanted his Law to be greatly praised.
Isa42:22 But his people were trapped and imprisoned in holes with no one to rescue them. All they owned had been taken, and no one was willing to give it back.
Isa42:23 Why won't his people ever learn to listen?
Isa42:24 Israel sinned and refused to obey the Lord or follow his instructions. So the Lord let them be robbed of everything they owned.
Isa42:25 He was furious with them and punished their nation with the fires of war. Still they paid no attention. They didn't even care when they were surrounded and scorched by flames.
Isa43:1 Descendants of Jacob, I, the Lord , created you and formed your nation. Israel, don't be afraid. I have rescued you. I have called you by name; now you belong to me.
Isa43:2 When you cross deep rivers, I will be with you, and you won't drown. When you walk through fire, you won't be burned or scorched by the flames.
Isa43:3 I am the Lord , your God, the Holy One of Israel, the God who saves you. I gave up Egypt, Ethiopia, and the region of Seba in exchange for you.
Isa43:4 To me, you are very dear, and I love you. That's why I gave up nations and people to rescue you.
Isa43:5 Don't be afraid! I am with you. From both east and west I will bring you together.
Isa43:6 I will say to the north and to the south, "Free my sons and daughters! Let them return from distant lands.
Isa43:7 They are my people -  I created each of them to bring honor to me." The Lord said:
Isa43:8 Bring my people together. They have eyes and ears, but they can't see or hear.
Isa43:9 Tell everyone of every nation to gather around. None of them can honestly say, "We told you so!" If someone heard them say this, then tell us about it now.
Isa43:10 My people, you are my witnesses and my chosen servant. I want you to know me, to trust me, and understand that I alone am God. I have always been God; there can be no others.
Isa43:11 I alone am the Lord ; only I can rescue you.
Isa43:12 I promised to save you, and I kept my promise. You are my witnesses that no other god did this. I, the Lord , have spoken.
Isa43:13 I am God now and forever. No one can snatch you from me or stand in my way.
Isa43:14 I, the Lord , will rescue you! I am Israel's holy God, and this is my promise: For your sake, I will send an army against Babylon to drag its people away, crying as they go.
Isa43:15 I am the Lord , your holy God, Israel's Creator and King.
Isa43:16 I am the one who cut a path through the mighty ocean.
Isa43:17 I sent an army to chase you with chariots and horses; now they lie dead, unable to move. They are like an oil lamp with the flame snuffed out. The Lord said:
Isa43:18 Forget what happened long ago! Don't think about the past.
Isa43:19 I am creating something new. There it is! Do you see it? I have put roads in deserts, streams in thirsty lands.
Isa43:20 Every wild animal honors me, even jackals and owls. I provide water in deserts -  streams in thirsty lands for my chosen people.
Isa43:21 I made them my own nation, so they would praise me.
Isa43:22 I, the Lord , said to Israel: You have become weary, but not from worshiping me.
Isa43:23 You have not honored me by sacrificing sheep or other animals. And I have not burdened you with demands for sacrifices or sweet-smelling incense.
Isa43:24 You have not brought delicious spices for me or given me the best part of your sacrificed animals. Instead, you burden me down with your terrible sins.
Isa43:25 But I wipe away your sins because of who I am. And so, I will forget the wrongs you have done.
Isa43:26 Meet me in court! State your case and prove that you are right.
Isa43:27 Your earliest ancestor and all of your leaders rebelled against me.
Isa43:28 That's why I don't allow your priests to serve me; I let Israel be destroyed and your people disgraced.
Isa44:1 People of Israel, I have chosen you as my servant.
Isa44:2 I am your Creator. You were in my care even before you were born. Israel, don't be terrified! You are my chosen servant, my very favorite.
Isa44:3 I will bless the thirsty land by sending streams of water; I will bless your descendants by giving them my Spirit.
Isa44:4 They will spring up like grass or like willow trees near flowing streams.
Isa44:5 They will worship me and become my people. They will write my name on the back of their hands.
Isa44:6 I am the Lord All-Powerful, the first and the last, the one and only God. Israel, I have rescued you! I am your King.
Isa44:7 Can anyone compare with me? If so, let them speak up and tell me now. Let them say what has happened since I made my nation long ago, and let them tell what is going to happen.
Isa44:8 Don't tremble with fear! Didn't I tell you long ago? Didn't you hear me? I alone am God -  no one else is a mighty rock. The Lord said:
Isa44:9 Those people who make idols are nothing themselves, and the idols they treasure are just as worthless. Worshipers of idols are blind, stupid, and foolish.
Isa44:10 Why make an idol or an image that can't do a thing?
Isa44:11 Everyone who makes idols and all who worship them are mere humans, who will end up sadly disappointed. Let them face me in court and be terrified.
Isa44:12 A metalworker shapes an idol by using a hammer and heat from the fire. In his powerful hand he holds a hammer, as he pounds the metal into the proper shape. But he gets hungry and thirsty and loses his strength.
Isa44:13 Some woodcarver measures a piece of wood, then draws an outline. The idol is carefully carved with each detail exact. At last it looks like a person and is placed in a temple.
Isa44:14 Either cedar, cypress, oak, or any tree from the forest may be chosen. Or even a pine tree planted by the woodcarver and watered by the rain.
Isa44:15 Some of the wood is used to make a fire for heating or for cooking. One piece is made into an idol, then the woodcarver bows down and worships it.
Isa44:16 He enjoys the warm fire and the meat that was roasted over the burning coals.
Isa44:17 Afterwards, he bows down to worship the wooden idol. "Protect me!" he says. "You are my god."
Isa44:18 Those who worship idols are stupid and blind!
Isa44:19 They don't have enough sense to say to themselves, "I made a fire with half of the wood and cooked my bread and meat on it. Then I made something worthless with the other half. Why worship a block of wood?"
Isa44:20 How can anyone be stupid enough to trust something that can be burned to ashes? No one can save themselves like that. Don't they realize that the idols they hold in their hands are not really gods?
Isa44:21 People of Israel, you are my servant, so remember all of this. Israel, I created you, and you are my servant. I won't forget you.
Isa44:22 Turn back to me! I have rescued you and swept away your sins as though they were clouds.
Isa44:23 Tell the heavens and the earth to start singing! Tell the mountains and every tree in the forest to join in the song! The Lord has rescued his people; now they will worship him.
Isa44:24 Israel, I am your Lord . I am your source of life, and I have rescued you. I created everything from the sky above to the earth below.
Isa44:25 I make liars of false prophets and fools of fortunetellers. I take human wisdom and turn it into nonsense.
Isa44:26 I will make the message of my prophets come true. They are saying, "Jerusalem will be filled with people, and the Lord will rebuild the towns of Judah."
Isa44:27 I am the one who commands the sea and its streams to run dry.
Isa44:28 I am also the one who says, "Cyrus will lead my people and obey my orders. Jerusalem and the temple will be rebuilt."
Isa45:1 The Lord said to Cyrus, his chosen one: I have taken hold of your right hand to help you capture nations and remove kings from power. City gates will open for you; not one will stay closed.
Isa45:2 As I lead you, I will level mountains and break the iron bars on bronze gates of cities.
Isa45:3 I will give you treasures hidden in dark and secret places. Then you will know that I, the Lord God of Israel, have called you by name.
Isa45:4 Cyrus, you don't even know me! But I have called you by name and highly honored you because of Israel, my chosen servant.
Isa45:5 Only I am the Lord ! There are no other gods. I have made you strong, though you don't know me.
Isa45:6 Now everyone from east to west will learn that I am the Lord . No other gods are real.
Isa45:7 I create light and darkness, happiness and sorrow. I, the Lord , do all of this.
Isa45:8 Tell the heavens to send down justice like showers of rain. Prepare the earth for my saving power to sprout and produce justice that I, the Lord , create. The Lord said:
Isa45:9 Israel, you have no right to argue with your Creator. You are merely a clay pot shaped by a potter. The clay doesn't ask, "Why did you make me this way? Where are the handles?"
Isa45:10 Children don't have the right to demand of their parents, "What have you done to make us what we are?"
Isa45:11 I am the Lord , the Creator, the holy God of Israel. Do you dare question me about my own nation or about what I have done?
Isa45:12 I created the world and covered it with people; I stretched out the sky and filled it with stars.
Isa45:13 I have done the right thing by placing Cyrus in power, and I will make the roads easy for him to follow. I am the Lord All-Powerful! Cyrus will rebuild my city and set my people free without being paid a thing. I, the Lord , have spoken.
Isa45:14 My people, I, the Lord , promise that the riches of Egypt and the treasures of Ethiopia will belong to you. You will force into slavery those tall people of Seba. They will bow down and say, "The only true God is with you; there are no other gods."
Isa45:15 People of Israel, your God is a mystery, though he alone can save.
Isa45:16 Anyone who makes idols will be confused and terribly disgraced.
Isa45:17 But Israel, I, the Lord , will always keep you safe and free from shame.
Isa45:18 The Lord alone is God! He created the heavens and made a world where people can live, instead of creating an empty desert. The Lord alone is God; there are no others.
Isa45:19 The Lord did not speak in a dark secret place or command Jacob's descendants to search for him in vain. The Lord speaks the truth, and this is what he says
Isa45:20 to every survivor from every nation: "Gather around me! Learn how senseless it is to worship wooden idols or pray to helpless gods.
Isa45:21 "Why don't you get together and meet me in court? Didn't I tell you long ago what would happen? I am the only God! There are no others. I bring about justice, and have the power to save.
Isa45:22 "I invite the whole world to turn to me and be saved. I alone am God! No others are real.
Isa45:23 I have made a solemn promise, one that won't be broken: Everyone will bow down and worship me.
Isa45:24 They will admit that I alone can bring about justice. Everyone who is angry with me will be terribly ashamed and will turn to me.
Isa45:25 I, the Lord , will give victory and great honor to the people of Israel."
Isa46:1 The gods Bel and Nebo are down on their knees, as wooden images of them are carried away on weary animals.
Isa46:2 They are down on their knees to rescue the heavy load, but the images are still taken to a foreign country.
Isa46:3 You survivors in Israel, listen to me, the Lord . Since the day you were born, I have carried you along.
Isa46:4 I will still be the same when you are old and gray, and I will take care of you. I created you. I will carry you and always keep you safe.
Isa46:5 Can anyone compare with me? Is anyone my equal?
Isa46:6 Some people hire a goldsmith and give silver and gold to be formed into an idol for them to worship.
Isa46:7 They carry the idol on their shoulders, then put it on a stand, but it cannot move. They call out to the idol when they are in trouble, but it doesn't answer, and it cannot help.
Isa46:8 Now keep this in mind, you sinful people. And don't ever forget it.
Isa46:9 I alone am God! There are no other gods; no one is like me. Think about what happened many years ago.
Isa46:10 From the very beginning, I told what would happen long before it took place. I kept my word
Isa46:11 and brought someone from a distant land to do what I wanted. He attacked from the east, like a hawk swooping down. Now I will keep my promise and do what I planned.
Isa46:12 You people are stubborn and far from being safe, so listen to me.
Isa46:13 I will soon come to save you. I am not far away and will waste no time; I take pride in Israel and will save Jerusalem.
Isa47:1 City of Babylon, You are delicate and untouched, but that will change. Surrender your royal power and sit in the dirt.
Isa47:2 Start grinding grain! Take off your veil. Strip off your fancy clothes and cross over rivers.
Isa47:3 You will suffer the shame of going naked, because I will take revenge, and no one can escape.
Isa47:4 I am the Lord All-Powerful, the holy God of Israel. I am their Savior.
Isa47:5 Babylon, be silent! Sit in the dark. No longer will nations accept you as their queen.
Isa47:6 I was angry with my people. So I let you take their land and bring disgrace on them. You showed them no mercy, but were especially cruel to those who were old.
Isa47:7 You thought that you would be queen forever. You didn't care what you did; it never entered your mind that you might get caught.
Isa47:8 You think that you alone are all-powerful, that you won't be a widow or lose your children. All you care about is pleasure, but listen to what I say.
Isa47:9 Your magic powers and charms will suddenly fail, then you will be a widow and lose your children.
Isa47:10 You hid behind evil like a shield and said, "No one can see me!" You were fooled by your wisdom and your knowledge; you felt sure that you alone were in full control.
Isa47:11 But without warning, disaster will strike -  and your magic charms won't help at all.
Isa47:12 Keep using your magic powers and your charms as you have always done. Maybe - just maybe -  you will frighten somebody!
Isa47:13 You have worn yourself out, asking for advice from those who study the stars and tell the future month after month. Go ask them how to be saved from what will happen.
Isa47:14 People who trust the stars are as helpless as straw in a flaming fire. No one can even keep warm, sitting by a fire that feeds only on straw.
Isa47:15 These are the fortunetellers you have done business with all of your life. But they don't know where they are going, and they can't save you.
Isa48:1 People of Israel, you come from Jacob's family and the tribe of Judah. You claim to worship me, the Lord God of Israel, but you are lying.
Isa48:2 You call Jerusalem your home and say you depend on me, the Lord All-Powerful, the God of Israel.
Isa48:3 Long ago I announced what was going to be, then without warning, I made it happen.
Isa48:4 I knew you were stubborn and hardheaded.
Isa48:5 And I told you these things, so that when they happened you would not say, "The idols we worship did this."
Isa48:6 You heard what I said, and you have seen it happen. Now admit that it's true! I will show you secrets you have never known.
Isa48:7 Today I am doing something new, something you cannot say you have heard before.
Isa48:8 You have never been willing to listen to what I say; from the moment of your birth, I knew you would rebel.
Isa48:9 I, the Lord , am true to myself; I will be praised for not punishing and destroying you.
Isa48:10 I tested you in hard times just as silver is refined in a heated furnace.
Isa48:11 I did this because of who I am. I refuse to be dishonored or share my praise with any other god.
Isa48:12 Israel, my chosen people, listen to me. I alone am the Lord , the first and the last.
Isa48:13 With my own hand I created the earth and stretched out the sky. They obey my every command.
Isa48:14 Gather around me, all of you! Listen to what I say. Did any of your idols predict this would happen? Did they say that my friend would do what I want done to Babylonia?
Isa48:15 I was the one who chose him. I have brought him this far, and he will be successful.
Isa48:16 Come closer and listen! I have never kept secret the things I have said, and I was here before time began. By the power of his Spirit the Lord God has sent me
Isa48:17 with this message: People of Israel, I am the holy Lord God, the one who rescues you. For your own good, I teach you, and I lead you along the right path.
Isa48:18 How I wish that you had obeyed my commands! Your success and good fortune would then have overflowed like a flooding river.
Isa48:19 Your nation would be blessed with more people than there are grains of sand along the seashore. And I would never have let your country be destroyed.
Isa48:20 Now leave Babylon! Celebrate as you go. Be happy and shout for everyone to hear, "The Lord has rescued his servant Israel!
Isa48:21 He led us through the desert and made water flow from a rock to satisfy our thirst.
Isa48:22 But the Lord has promised that none who are evil will live in peace."
Isa49:1 Everyone, listen, even you foreign nations across the sea. The Lord chose me and gave me a name before I was born.
Isa49:2 He made my words pierce like a sharp sword or a pointed arrow; he kept me safely hidden in the palm of his hand.
Isa49:3 The Lord said to me, "Israel, you are my servant; and because of you I will be highly honored."
Isa49:4 I said to myself, "I'm completely worn out; my time has been wasted. But I did it for the Lord God, and he will reward me."
Isa49:5 Even before I was born, the Lord God chose me to serve him and to lead back the people of Israel. So the Lord has honored me and made me strong.
Isa49:6 Now the Lord says to me, "It isn't enough for you to be merely my servant. You must do more than lead back survivors from the tribes of Israel. I have placed you here as a light for other nations; you must take my saving power to everyone on earth."
Isa49:7 Israel, I am the holy Lord God, the one who rescues you. You are slaves of rulers and of a nation who despises you. Now this is what I promise: Kings and rulers will honor you by kneeling at your feet. You can trust me! I am your Lord , the holy God of Israel, and you are my chosen ones.
Isa49:8 This is what the Lord says: I will answer your prayers because I have set a time when I will help by coming to save you. I have chosen you to take my promise of hope to other nations. You will rebuild the country from its ruins, then people will come and settle there.
Isa49:9 You will set prisoners free from dark dungeons to see the light of day. On their way home, they will find plenty to eat, even on barren hills.
Isa49:10 They won't go hungry or get thirsty; they won't be bothered by the scorching sun or hot desert winds. I will be merciful while leading them along to streams of water.
Isa49:11 I will level the mountains and make roads.
Isa49:12 Then my people will return from distant lands in the north and the west and from the city of Syene.
Isa49:13 Tell the heavens and the earth to celebrate and sing; command every mountain to join in the song. The Lord 's people have suffered, but he has shown mercy and given them comfort.
Isa49:14 The people of Zion said, "The Lord has turned away and forgotten us."
Isa49:15 The Lord answered, "Could a mother forget a child who nurses at her breast? Could she fail to love an infant who came from her own body? Even if a mother could forget, I will never forget you.
Isa49:16 A picture of your city is drawn on my hand. You are always in my thoughts!
Isa49:17 "Your city will be built faster than it was destroyed  -  those who attacked it will retreat and leave.
Isa49:18 Look around! You will see your people coming home. As surely as I live, I, the Lord , promise that your city with its people will be as lovely as a bride wearing her jewelry."
Isa49:19 Jerusalem is now in ruins! Nothing is left of the city. But it will be rebuilt and soon overcrowded; its cruel enemies will be gone far away.
Isa49:20 Jerusalem is a woman whose children were born while she was in deep sorrow over the loss of her husband. Now those children will come and seek room in the crowded city,
Isa49:21 and Jerusalem will ask, "Am I really their mother? How could I have given birth when I was still mourning in a foreign land? Who raised these children? Where have they come from?"
Isa49:22 The Lord God says: "I will soon give a signal for the nations to return your sons and your daughters to the arms of Jerusalem.
Isa49:23 The kings and queens of those nations where they were raised will come and bow down. They will take care of you just like a slave taking care of a child. Then you will know that I am the Lord . You won't be disappointed if you trust me."
Isa49:24 Is it possible to rescue victims from someone strong and cruel?
Isa49:25 But the Lord has promised to fight on our side and to rescue our children from those strong and violent enemies.
Isa49:26 He will make those cruel people dine on their own flesh and get drunk from drinking their own blood. Then everyone will know that the Lord is our Savior; the powerful God of Israel has rescued his people.
Isa50:1 The Lord says, "Children, I didn't divorce your mother or sell you to pay debts; I divorced her and sold you because of your sins.
Isa50:2 I came and called out, but you didn't answer. Have I lost my power to rescue and save? At my command oceans and rivers turn into deserts; fish rot and stink for lack of water.
Isa50:3 I make the sky turn dark like the sackcloth you wear at funerals."
Isa50:4 The Lord God gives me the right words to encourage the weary. Each morning he awakens me eager to learn his teaching;
Isa50:5 he made me willing to listen and not rebel or run away.
Isa50:6 I let them beat my back and pull out my beard. I didn't turn aside when they insulted me and spit in my face.
Isa50:7 But the Lord God keeps me from being disgraced. So I refuse to give up, because I know God will never let me down.
Isa50:8 My protector is nearby; no one can stand here to accuse me of wrong.
Isa50:9 The Lord God will help me and prove I am innocent. My accusers will wear out like moth-eaten clothes.
Isa50:10 None of you respect the Lord or obey his servant. You walk in the dark instead of the light; you don't trust the name of the Lord your God.
Isa50:11 Go ahead and walk in the light of the fires you have set. But with his own hand, the Lord will punish you and make you suffer.
Isa51:1 If you want to do right and obey the Lord , follow Abraham's example. He was the rock from which you were chipped.
Isa51:2 God chose Abraham and Sarah to be your ancestors. The Lord blessed Abraham, and from that one man came many descendants.
Isa51:3 Though Zion is in ruins, the Lord will bring comfort, and the city will be as lovely as the garden of Eden that he provided. Then Zion will celebrate; it will be thankful and sing joyful songs.
Isa51:4 The Lord says: You are my people and nation! So pay attention to me. My teaching will cause justice to shine like a light for every nation.
Isa51:5 Those who live across the sea are eagerly waiting for me to rescue them. I am strong and ready; soon I will come to save and to rule all nations.
Isa51:6 Look closely at the sky! Stare at the earth. The sky will vanish like smoke; the earth will wear out like clothes. Everyone on this earth will die like flies. But my victory will last; my saving power never ends.
Isa51:7 If you want to do right and to obey my teaching with all your heart, then pay close attention. Don't be discouraged when others insult you and say hurtful things.
Isa51:8 They will be eaten away like a moth-eaten coat. But my victory will last; my saving power will never end.
Isa51:9 Wake up! Do something, Lord . Be strong and ready. Wake up! Do what you did for our people long ago. Didn't you chop up Rahab the monster?
Isa51:10 Didn't you dry up the deep sea and make a road for your people to follow safely across?
Isa51:11 Now those you have rescued will return to Jerusalem, singing on their way. They will be crowned with great happiness, never again to be burdened with sadness and sorrow.
Isa51:12 I am the Lord , the one who encourages you. Why are you afraid of mere humans? They dry up and die like grass.
Isa51:13 I spread out the heavens and laid foundations for the earth. But you have forgotten me, your Lord and Creator. All day long you were afraid of those who were angry and hoped to abuse you. Where are they now?
Isa51:14 Everyone crying out in pain will be quickly set free; they will be rescued from the power of death and never go hungry.
Isa51:15 I will help them because I am your God, the Lord All-Powerful, who makes the ocean roar.
Isa51:16 I have told you what to say, and I will keep you safe in the palm of my hand. I spread out the heavens and laid foundations for the earth. Now I say, "Jerusalem, your people are mine."
Isa51:17 Jerusalem, wake up! Stand up! You've drunk too much from the cup filled with the Lord 's anger. You have swallowed every drop, and you can't walk straight.
Isa51:18 Not one of your many children is there to guide you or to offer a helping hand.
Isa51:19 You have been destroyed by war and by famine; I cannot comfort you.
Isa51:20 The Lord your God is angry, and on every street corner your children lie helpless, like deer trapped in nets.
Isa51:21 You are in trouble and drunk, but not from wine. So pay close attention
Isa51:22 to the Lord your God, who defends you and says, "I have taken from your hands the cup filled with my anger that made you drunk. You will never be forced to drink it again.
Isa51:23 Instead I will give it to your brutal enemies, who treated you like dirt and walked all over you."
Isa52:1 Jerusalem, wake up! Stand up and be strong. Holy city of Zion, dress in your best clothes. Those foreigners who ruined your sacred city won't bother you again.
Isa52:2 Zion, rise from the dirt! Free yourself from the rope around your neck.
Isa52:3 The Lord says: My people, you were sold, but not for money; now you will be set free, but not for a payment.
Isa52:4 Long ago you went to Egypt where you lived as foreigners. Then Assyria was cruel to you,
Isa52:5 and now another nation has taken you prisoner for no reason at all. Your leaders groan with pain, and day after day my own name is cursed.
Isa52:6 My people, you will learn who I am and who is speaking because I am here.
Isa52:7 What a beautiful sight! On the mountains a messenger announces to Jerusalem, "Good news! You're saved. There will be peace. Your God is now King."
Isa52:8 Everyone on guard duty, sing and celebrate! Look! You can see the Lord returning to Zion.
Isa52:9 Jerusalem, rise from the ruins! Join in the singing. The Lord has given comfort to his people; he comes to your rescue.
Isa52:10 The Lord has shown all nations his mighty strength; now everyone will see the saving power of our God.
Isa52:11 Leave the city of Babylon! Don't touch anything filthy. Wash yourselves. Be ready to carry back everything sacred that belongs to the Lord .
Isa52:12 You won't need to run. No one is chasing you. The Lord God of Israel will lead and protect you from enemy attacks.
Isa52:13 The Lord says: My servant will succeed! He will be given great praise and the highest honors.
Isa52:14 Many were horrified at what happened to him. But everyone who saw him was even more horrified because he suffered until he no longer looked human.
Isa52:15 My servant will make nations worthy to worship me; kings will be silent as they bow in wonder. They will see and think about things they have never seen or thought about before.
Isa53:1 Has anyone believed us or seen the mighty power of the Lord in action?
Isa53:2 Like a young plant or a root that sprouts in dry ground, the servant grew up obeying the Lord . He wasn't some handsome king. Nothing about the way he looked made him attractive to us.
Isa53:3 He was hated and rejected; his life was filled with sorrow and terrible suffering. No one wanted to look at him. We despised him and said, "He is a nobody!"
Isa53:4 He suffered and endured great pain for us, but we thought his suffering was punishment from God.
Isa53:5 He was wounded and crushed because of our sins; by taking our punishment, he made us completely well.
Isa53:6 All of us were like sheep that had wandered off. We had each gone our own way, but the Lord gave him the punishment we deserved.
Isa53:7 He was painfully abused, but he did not complain. He was silent like a lamb being led to the butcher, as quiet as a sheep having its wool cut off.
Isa53:8 He was condemned to death without a fair trial. Who could have imagined what would happen to him? His life was taken away because of the sinful things my people had done.
Isa53:9 He wasn't dishonest or violent, but he was buried in a tomb of cruel and rich people.
Isa53:10 The Lord decided his servant would suffer as a sacrifice to take away the sin and guilt of others. Now the servant will live to see his own descendants. He did everything the Lord had planned.
Isa53:11 By suffering, the servant will learn the true meaning of obeying the Lord . Although he is innocent, he will take the punishment for the sins of others, so that many of them will no longer be guilty.
Isa53:12 The Lord will reward him with honor and power for sacrificing his life. Others thought he was a sinner, but he suffered for our sins and asked God to forgive us.
Isa54:1 Sing and shout, even though you have never had children! The Lord has promised that you will have more children than someone married for a long time.
Isa54:2 Make your tents larger! Spread out the tent pegs; fasten them firmly.
Isa54:3 You and your descendants will take over the land of other nations. You will settle in towns that are now in ruins.
Isa54:4 Don't be afraid or ashamed and don't be discouraged. You won't be disappointed. Forget how sinful you were when you were young; stop feeling ashamed for being left a widow.
Isa54:5 The Lord All-Powerful, the Holy God of Israel, rules all the earth. He is your Creator and husband, and he will rescue you.
Isa54:6 You were like a young wife, brokenhearted and crying because her husband had divorced her. But the Lord your God says, "I am taking you back!
Isa54:7 I rejected you for a while, but with love and tenderness I will embrace you again.
Isa54:8 For a while, I turned away in furious anger. Now I will have mercy and love you forever! I, your protector and Lord , make this promise."
Isa54:9 I once promised Noah that I would never again destroy the earth by a flood. Now I have promised that I will never again get angry and punish you.
Isa54:10 Every mountain and hill may disappear. But I will always be kind and merciful to you; I won't break my agreement to give your nation peace.
Isa54:11 Jerusalem, you are sad and discouraged, tossed around in a storm. But I, the Lord , will rebuild your city with precious stones; for your foundation I will use blue sapphires.
Isa54:12 Your fortresses will be built of rubies, your gates of jewels, and your walls of gems.
Isa54:13 I will teach your children and make them successful.
Isa54:14 You will be built on fairness with no fears of injustice; every one of your worries will be taken far from you.
Isa54:15 I will never send anyone to attack your city, and you will make prisoners of those who do attack.
Isa54:16 Don't forget that I created metalworkers who make weapons over burning coals. I also created armies that can bring destruction.
Isa54:17 Weapons made to attack you won't be successful; words spoken against you won't hurt at all. My servants, Jerusalem is yours! I, the Lord , promise to bless you with victory.
Isa55:1 If you are thirsty, come and drink water! If you don't have any money, come, eat what you want! Drink wine and milk without paying a cent.
Isa55:2 Why waste your money on what really isn't food? Why work hard for something that doesn't satisfy? Listen carefully to me, and you will enjoy the very best foods.
Isa55:3 Pay close attention! Come to me and live. I will promise you the eternal love and loyalty that I promised David.
Isa55:4 I made him the leader and ruler of the nations; he was my witness to them.
Isa55:5 You will call out to nations you have never known. And they have never known you, but they will come running because I am the Lord , the holy God of Israel, and I have honored you.
Isa55:6 Turn to the Lord ! He can still be found. Call out to God! He is near.
Isa55:7 Give up your crooked ways and your evil thoughts. Return to the Lord our God. He will be merciful and forgive your sins.
Isa55:8 The Lord says: "My thoughts and my ways are not like yours.
Isa55:9 Just as the heavens are higher than the earth, my thoughts and my ways are higher than yours.
Isa55:10 "Rain and snow fall from the sky. But they don't return without watering the earth that produces seeds to plant and grain to eat.
Isa55:11 That's how it is with my words. They don't return to me without doing everything I send them to do."
Isa55:12 When you are set free, you will celebrate and travel home in peace. Mountains and hills will sing as you pass by, and trees will clap.
Isa55:13 Cypress and myrtle trees will grow in fields once covered by thorns. And then those trees will stand as a lasting witness to the glory of the Lord .
Isa56:1 The Lord said: Be honest and fair! Soon I will come to save you; my saving power will be seen everywhere on earth.
Isa56:2 I will bless everyone who respects the Sabbath and refuses to do wrong.
Isa56:3 Foreigners who worship me must not say, "The Lord won't let us be part of his people." Men who are unable to become fathers must no longer say, "We are dried-up trees."
Isa56:4 To them, I, the Lord , say: Respect the Sabbath, obey me completely, and keep our agreement.
Isa56:5 Then I will set up monuments in my temple with your names written on them. This will be much better than having children, because these monuments will stand there forever.
Isa56:6 Foreigners will follow me. They will love me and worship in my name; they will respect the Sabbath and keep our agreement.
Isa56:7 I will bring them to my holy mountain, where they will celebrate in my house of worship. Their sacrifices and offerings will always be welcome on my altar. Then my house will be known as a house of worship for all nations.
Isa56:8 I, the Lord , promise to bring together my people who were taken away, and let them join the others.
Isa56:9 Come from the forest, you wild animals! Attack and gobble down your victims.
Isa56:10 You leaders of Israel should be watchdogs, protecting my people. But you can't see a thing, and you never warn them. Dozing and daydreaming are all you ever do.
Isa56:11 You stupid leaders are a pack of hungry and greedy dogs that never get enough. You are shepherds who mistreat your own sheep for selfish gain.
Isa56:12 You say to each other, "Let's drink till we're drunk! Tomorrow we'll do it again. We'll really enjoy ourselves."
Isa57:1 God's faithful people are dragged off and killed, and no one even cares. Evil sweeps them away,
Isa57:2 but in death they find peace for obeying God.
Isa57:3 You people are unfaithful! You go to fortunetellers, and you worship idols. Now pay close attention!
Isa57:4 Who are you making fun of? Who are you sneering at? Look how your sins have made fools of you.
Isa57:5 All you think about is sex under those green trees where idols are worshiped. You sacrifice your children on altars built in valleys under rocky slopes.
Isa57:6 You have chosen to worship idols made of stone; you have given them offerings of wine and grain. Should I be pleased?
Isa57:7 You have spread out your beds on the tops of high mountains, where you sacrifice to idols.
Isa57:8 Even in your homes you have placed pagan symbols all around your huge beds. Yes, you have rejected me, sold yourselves to your lovers, and gone to bed with them.
Isa57:9 You smear on olive oil and all kinds of perfume to worship the god Molech. You even seek advice from spirits of the dead.
Isa57:10 Though you tired yourself out by running after idols, you refused to stop. Your desires were so strong that they kept you going.
Isa57:11 Did you forget about me and become unfaithful because you were more afraid of someone else? Have I been silent so long that you no longer fear me?
Isa57:12 You think you're so good, but I'll point out the truth.
Isa57:13 Ask your idols to save you when you are in trouble. Be careful though -  it takes only a faint breath to blow them over. But if you come to me for protection, this land and my holy mountain will always belong to you.
Isa57:14 The Lord says, "Clear the road! Get it ready for my people."
Isa57:15 Our holy God lives forever in the highest heavens, and this is what he says: Though I live high above in the holy place, I am here to help those who are humble and depend only on me.
Isa57:16 My people, I won't stay angry and keep on accusing you. After all, I am your Creator. I don't want you to give up in complete despair.
Isa57:17 Your greed made me furious. That's why I punished you and refused to be found, while you kept returning to your old sinful ways.
Isa57:18 I know what you are like! But I will heal you, lead you, and give you comfort, until those who are mourning
Isa57:19 start singing my praises. No matter where you are, I, the Lord , will heal you and give you peace.
Isa57:20 The wicked are a restless sea tossing up mud.
Isa57:21 But I, the Lord , have promised that none who are evil will live in peace.
Isa58:1 Shout the message! Don't hold back. Say to my people Israel: You've sinned! You've turned against the Lord .
Isa58:2 Day after day, you worship him and seem eager to learn his teachings. You act like a nation that wants to do right by obeying his laws. You ask him about justice, and say you enjoy worshiping the Lord .
Isa58:3 You wonder why the Lord pays no attention when you go without eating and act humble. But on those same days that you give up eating, you think only of yourselves and abuse your workers.
Isa58:4 You even get angry and ready to fight. No wonder God won't listen to your prayers!
Isa58:5 Do you think the Lord wants you to give up eating and to act as humble as a bent-over bush? Or to dress in sackcloth and sit in ashes? Is this really what he wants on a day of worship?
Isa58:6 I'll tell you what it really means to worship the Lord . Remove the chains of prisoners who are chained unjustly. Free those who are abused!
Isa58:7 Share your food with everyone who is hungry; share your home with the poor and homeless. Give clothes to those in need; don't turn away your relatives.
Isa58:8 Then your light will shine like the dawning sun, and you will quickly be healed. Your honesty will protect you as you advance, and the glory of the Lord will defend you from behind.
Isa58:9 When you beg the Lord for help, he will answer, "Here I am!" Don't mistreat others or falsely accuse them or say something cruel.
Isa58:10 Give your food to the hungry and care for the homeless. Then your light will shine in the dark; your darkest hour will be like the noonday sun.
Isa58:11 The Lord will always guide you and provide good things to eat when you are in the desert. He will make you healthy. You will be like a garden that has plenty of water or like a stream that never runs dry.
Isa58:12 You will rebuild those houses left in ruins for years; you will be known as a builder and repairer of city walls and streets.
Isa58:13 But first, you must start respecting the Sabbath as a joyful day of worship. You must stop doing and saying whatever you please on this special day.
Isa58:14 Then you will truly enjoy knowing the Lord . He will let you rule from the highest mountains and bless you with the land of your ancestor Jacob. The Lord has spoken!
Isa59:1 The Lord hasn't lost his powerful strength; he can still hear and answer prayers.
Isa59:2 Your sins are the roadblock between you and your God. That's why he doesn't answer your prayers or let you see his face.
Isa59:3 Your talk is filled with lies and plans for violence; every finger on your hands is covered with blood.
Isa59:4 You falsely accuse others and tell lies in court; sin and trouble are the names of your children.
Isa59:5 You eat the deadly eggs of poisonous snakes, and more snakes crawl out from the eggs left to hatch. You weave spider webs,
Isa59:6 but you can't make clothes with those webs or hide behind them. You're sinful and brutal.
Isa59:7 You hurry off to do wrong or murder innocent victims. All you think about is sin; you leave ruin and destruction wherever you go.
Isa59:8 You don't know how to live in peace or to be fair with others. The roads you make are crooked; your followers cannot find peace.
Isa59:9 No one has come to defend us or to bring about justice. We hoped for a day of sunshine, but all we found was a dark, gloomy night.
Isa59:10 We feel our way along, as if we were blind; we stumble at noon, as if it were night. We can see no better than someone dead.
Isa59:11 We growl like bears and mourn like doves. We hope for justice and victory, but they escape us.
Isa59:12 How often have we sinned and turned against you, the Lord God? Our sins condemn us! We have done wrong.
Isa59:13 We have rebelled and refused to follow you. Our hearts were deceitful, and so we lied; we planned to abuse others and turn our backs on you.
Isa59:14 Injustice is everywhere; justice seems far away. Truth is chased out of court; honesty is shoved aside.
Isa59:15 Everyone tells lies; those who turn from crime end up ruined. When the Lord noticed that justice had disappeared, he became very displeased.
Isa59:16 It disgusted him even more to learn that no one would do a thing about it. So with his own powerful arm, he won victories for truth.
Isa59:17 Justice was the Lord 's armor; saving power was his helmet; anger and revenge were his clothes.
Isa59:18 Now the Lord will get furious and do to his enemies, both near and far, what they did to his people.
Isa59:19 He will attack like a flood in a mighty windstorm. Nations in the west and the east will then honor and praise his wonderful name.
Isa59:20 The Lord has promised to rescue the city of Zion and Jacob's descendants who turn from sin.
Isa59:21 The Lord says: "My people, I promise to give you my Spirit and my message. These will be my gifts to you and your families forever. I, the Lord , have spoken."
Isa60:1 Jerusalem, stand up! Shine! Your new day is dawning. The glory of the Lord shines brightly on you.
Isa60:2 The earth and its people are covered with darkness, but the glory of the Lord is shining upon you.
Isa60:3 Nations and kings will come to the light of your dawning day. The Lord said:
Isa60:4 Open your eyes! Look around! Crowds are coming. Your sons are on their way from distant lands; your daughters are being carried like little children.
Isa60:5 When you see this, your faces will glow; your hearts will pound and swell with pride. Treasures from across the sea and the wealth of nations will be brought to you.
Isa60:6 Your country will be covered with caravans of young camels from Midian and Ephah. The people of Sheba will bring gold and spices in praise of me, the Lord .
Isa60:7 Every sheep of Kedar will come to you; rams from Nebaioth will be yours as well. I will accept them as offerings and bring honor to my temple.
Isa60:8 What is that sailing by like clouds or like doves flying home?
Isa60:9 On those distant islands your people are waiting for me, the Lord . Seagoing ships lead the way to bring them home with their silver and gold. I, the holy Lord God of Israel, do this to honor your people, so they will honor me. The Lord said:
Isa60:10 Jerusalem, your city walls will be rebuilt by foreigners; their rulers will become your slaves. I punished you in my anger; now I will be kind and treat you with mercy.
Isa60:11 Your gates will be open day and night to let the rulers of nations lead their people to you with all their treasures.
Isa60:12 Any nation or kingdom that refuses to serve you will be wiped out.
Isa60:13 Wood from Lebanon's best trees will be brought to you -  the pines, the firs, and the cypress trees. It will be used in my temple to make beautiful the place where I rest my feet.
Isa60:14 The descendants of enemies who hated and mistreated you will kneel at your feet. They will say, "You are Zion, the city of the Lord , the holy God of Israel."
Isa60:15 You were hated and deserted, rejected by everyone. But I will make you beautiful, a city to be proud of for all time to come.
Isa60:16 You will drain the wealth of kings and foreign nations. You will know that I, the mighty Lord God of Israel, have saved and rescued you.
Isa60:17 I will bring bronze and iron in place of wood and stone; in place of bronze and iron, I will bring gold and silver. I will appoint peace and justice as your rulers and leaders.
Isa60:18 Violence, destruction, and ruin will never again be heard of within your borders. "Victory" will be the name you give to your walls; "Praise" will be the name you give to your gates.
Isa60:19 You won't need the light of the sun or the moon. I, the Lord your God, will be your eternal light and bring you honor.
Isa60:20 Your sun will never set or your moon go down. I, the Lord , will be your everlasting light, and your days of sorrow will come to an end.
Isa60:21 Your people will live right and always own the land; they are the trees I planted to bring praise to me.
Isa60:22 Even the smallest family will be a powerful nation. I am the Lord , and when the time comes, I will quickly do all this.
Isa61:1 The Spirit of the Lord God has taken control of me! The Lord has chosen and sent me to tell the oppressed the good news, to heal the brokenhearted, and to announce freedom for prisoners and captives.
Isa61:2 This is the year when the Lord God will show kindness to us and punish our enemies. The Lord has sent me to comfort those who mourn,
Isa61:3 especially in Jerusalem. He sent me to give them flowers in place of their sorrow, olive oil in place of tears, and joyous praise in place of broken hearts. They will be called "Trees of Justice," planted by the Lord to honor his name.
Isa61:4 Then they will rebuild cities that have been in ruins for many generations.
Isa61:5 They will hire foreigners to take care of their sheep and their vineyards.
Isa61:6 But they themselves will be priests and servants of the Lord our God. The treasures of the nations will belong to them, and they will be famous.
Isa61:7 They were terribly insulted and horribly mistreated; now they will be greatly blessed and joyful forever.
Isa61:8 I, the Lord , love justice! But I hate robbery and injustice. My people, I solemnly promise to reward you with an eternal agreement.
Isa61:9 Your descendants will be known in every nation. All who see them will realize that they have been blessed, by me, the Lord .
Isa61:10 I celebrate and shout because of my Lord God. His saving power and justice are the very clothes I wear. They are more beautiful than the jewelry worn by a bride or a groom.
Isa61:11 The Lord will bring about justice and praise in every nation on earth, like flowers blooming in a garden.
Isa62:1 Jerusalem, I will speak up for your good. I will never be silent till you are safe and secure, sparkling like a flame.
Isa62:2 Your great victory will be seen by every nation and king; the Lord will even give you a new name.
Isa62:3 You will be a glorious crown, a royal headband, for the Lord your God.
Isa62:4 Your name will no longer be "Deserted and Childless," but "Happily Married." You will please the Lord ; your country will be his bride.
Isa62:5 Your people will take the land, just as a young man takes a bride. The Lord will be pleased because of you, just as a husband is pleased with his bride.
Isa62:6 Jerusalem, on your walls I have stationed guards, whose duty it is to speak out day and night, without resting. They must remind the Lord
Isa62:7 and not let him rest till he makes Jerusalem strong and famous everywhere.
Isa62:8 The Lord has given his word and made this promise: "Never again will I give to your enemies the grain and grapes for which you struggled.
Isa62:9 As surely as you harvest your grain and grapes, you will eat your bread with thankful hearts, and you will drink your wine in my temple."
Isa62:10 People of Jerusalem, open your gates! Repair the road to the city and clear it of stones; raise a banner to help the nations find their way.
Isa62:11 Here is what the Lord has said for all the earth to hear: "Soon I will come to save the city of Zion, and to reward you.
Isa62:12 Then you will be called, The Lord 's Own People, The Ones He Rescued!' Your city will be known as a good place to live and a city full of people."
Isa63:1 Who is this coming from Bozrah in Edom with clothes stained red? Who is this hero marching in his glorious uniform? "It's me, the Lord ! I have won the battle, and I can save you!"
Isa63:2 What are those red spots? Your clothes look stained from stomping on grapes.
Isa63:3 "I alone stomped the grapes! None of the nations helped. I stomped nations in my anger and stained my clothes with their blood.
Isa63:4 I did this because I wanted to take revenge -  the time had come to rescue my people.
Isa63:5 No one was there to help me or to give support; my mighty arm won the battle, strengthened by my anger.
Isa63:6 In my fury I stomped on nations and made them drunk; their blood poured out everywhere on earth."
Isa63:7 I will tell about the kind deeds the Lord has done. They deserve praise! The Lord has shown mercy to the people of Israel; he has been kind and good.
Isa63:8 The Lord rescued his people, and said, "They are mine. They won't betray me."
Isa63:9 It troubled the Lord to see them in trouble, and his angel saved them. The Lord was truly merciful, so he rescued his people. He took them in his arms and carried them all those years.
Isa63:10 Then the Lord 's people turned against him and made his Holy Spirit sad. So he became their enemy and attacked them.
Isa63:11 But his people remembered what had happened during the time of Moses. Didn't the Lord  bring them and their leaders safely through the sea? Didn't he give them his Holy Spirit?
Isa63:12 The glorious power of the Lord marched beside Moses. The Lord will be praised forever for dividing the sea.
Isa63:13 He led his people across like horses running wild without stumbling.
Isa63:14 His Spirit gave them rest, just as cattle find rest when led into a valley. The name of the Lord was praised for doing these things.
Isa63:15 Please, Lord , look down from your holy and glorious home in the heavens and see what's going on. Have you lost interest? Where is your power? Show that you care about us and have mercy!
Isa63:16 Our ancestors Abraham and Jacob have both rejected us. But you are still our Father; you have been our protector since ancient times.
Isa63:17 Why did you make us turn away from you, our Lord ? Why did you make us want to disobey you? Please change your mind! We are your servants, your very own people.
Isa63:18 For a little while, your temple belonged to us; and now our enemies have torn it down.
Isa63:19 We act as though you had never ruled us or called us your people.
Isa64:1 Rip the heavens apart! Come down, Lord ; make the mountains tremble.
Isa64:2 Be a spark that starts a fire causing water to boil. Then your enemies will know who you are; all nations will tremble because you are nearby.
Isa64:3 Your fearsome deeds have completely amazed us; even the mountains shake when you come down.
Isa64:4 You are the only God ever seen or heard of who works miracles for his followers.
Isa64:5 You help all who gladly obey and do what you want, but sin makes you angry. Only by your help can we ever be saved.
Isa64:6 We are unfit to worship you; each of our good deeds is merely a filthy rag. We dry up like leaves; our sins are storm winds sweeping us away.
Isa64:7 No one worships in your name or remains faithful. You have turned your back on us and let our sins melt us away.
Isa64:8 You, Lord , are our Father. We are nothing but clay, but you are the potter who molded us.
Isa64:9 Don't be so furious or keep our sins in your thoughts forever! Remember that all of us are your people.
Isa64:10 Every one of your towns has turned into a desert, especially Jerusalem.
Isa64:11 Zion's glorious and holy temple where our ancestors praised you has been destroyed by fire. Our beautiful buildings are now a pile of ruins.
Isa64:12 When you see these things, how can you just sit there and make us suffer more?
Isa65:1 I, the Lord , was ready answer even those who were not asking and to be found by those who were not searching. To a nation that refused to worship me, I said, "Here I am!"
Isa65:2 All day long I have reached out to stubborn and sinful people going their own way.
Isa65:3 They keep making me angry by sneering at me, while offering sacrifices to idols in gardens and burning incense to them on bricks.
Isa65:4 They spend their nights hiding in burial caves; they eat the meat of pigs, cooked in sauces made of stuff unfit to eat.
Isa65:5 And then they say to others, "Don't come near us! We're dedicated to God." Such people are like smoke, irritating my nose all day.
Isa65:6 I have written this down; I won't keep silent. I'll pay them back just as their sins deserve.
Isa65:7 I, the Lord , will make them pay for their sins and for those of their ancestors -  they have disgraced me by burning incense on mountains.
Isa65:8 Here is what the Lord says: A cluster of grapes that produces wine is worth keeping! So, because of my servants, I won't destroy everyone.
Isa65:9 I have chosen the people of Israel and Judah, and I will bless them with many descendants. They will settle here in this land of mountains, and it will be theirs.
Isa65:10 My people will worship me. Then the coastlands of Sharon and the land as far as Achor Valley will turn into pastureland where cattle and sheep will feed and rest.
Isa65:11 What will I, the Lord , do if any of you reject me and my holy mountain? What will happen to you for offering food and wine to the gods you call "Good Luck" and "Fate"?
Isa65:12 Your luck will end! I will see to it that you are slaughtered with swords. You refused to answer when I called out; you paid no attention to my instructions. Instead, you did what I hated, knowing it was wrong.
Isa65:13 I, the Lord God, will give food and drink to my servants, and they will celebrate. But all of you sinners will go hungry and thirsty, overcome with disgrace.
Isa65:14 My servants will laugh and sing, but you will be sad and cry out in pain.
Isa65:15 I, the Lord God, promise to see that you are killed and that my chosen servants use your names as curse words. But I will give new names to my servants.
Isa65:16 I am God! I can be trusted. Your past troubles are gone; I no longer think of them. When you pray for someone to receive a blessing, or when you make a promise, you must do it in my name. I alone am the God who can be trusted.
Isa65:17 I am creating new heavens and a new earth; everything of the past will be forgotten.
Isa65:18 Celebrate and be glad forever! I am creating a Jerusalem, full of happy people.
Isa65:19 I will celebrate with Jerusalem and all of its people; there will be no more crying or sorrow in that city.
Isa65:20 No child will die in infancy; everyone will live to a ripe old age. Anyone a hundred years old will be considered young, and to die younger than that will be considered a curse.
Isa65:21 My people will live in the houses they build; they will enjoy grapes from their own vineyards.
Isa65:22 No one will take away their homes or vineyards. My chosen people will live to be as old as trees, and they will enjoy what they have earned.
Isa65:23 Their work won't be wasted, and their children won't die of dreadful diseases. I will bless their children and their grandchildren.
Isa65:24 I will answer their prayers before they finish praying.
Isa65:25 Wolves and lambs will graze together; lions and oxen will feed on straw. Snakes will eat only dirt! They won't bite or harm anyone on my holy mountain. I, the Lord , have spoken!
Isa66:1 The Lord said: Heaven is my throne; the earth is my footstool. What kind of house could you build for me? In what place will I rest?
Isa66:2 I have made everything; that's how it all came to be. I, the Lord , have spoken. The people I treasure most are the humble -  they depend only on me and tremble when I speak.
Isa66:3 You sacrifice oxen to me, and you commit murder; you sacrifice lambs to me and dogs to other gods; you offer grain to me and pigs' blood to idols; you burn incense to me and praise your idols. You have made your own choice to do these disgusting things that you enjoy so much.
Isa66:4 You refused to answer when I called out; you paid no attention to my instructions. Instead, you did what I hated, knowing it was wrong. Now I will punish you in a way you dread the most.
Isa66:5 If you tremble when the Lord speaks, listen to what he says: "Some of your own people hate and reject you because of me. They make fun and say, Let the Lord show his power! Let us see him make you truly happy.' But those who say these things will be terribly ashamed."
Isa66:6 Do you hear that noise in the city and those shouts coming from the temple? It is the Lord shouting as he punishes his enemies.
Isa66:7 Have you ever heard of a woman who gave birth to a child before having labor pains?
Isa66:8 Who ever heard of such a thing or imagined it could happen? Can a nation be born in a day or come to life in a second? Jerusalem is like a mother who gave birth to her children as soon as she was in labor.
Isa66:9 The Lord is the one who makes birth possible. And he will see that Zion has many more children. The Lord has spoken.
Isa66:10 If you love Jerusalem, celebrate and shout! If you were in sorrow because of the city, you can now be glad.
Isa66:11 She will nurse and comfort you, just like your own mother, until you are satisfied. You will fully enjoy her wonderful glory.
Isa66:12 The Lord has promised: "I will flood Jerusalem with the wealth of nations and make the city prosper. Zion will nurse you at her breast, carry you in her arms, and hold you in her lap.
Isa66:13 I will comfort you there like a mother comforting her child."
Isa66:14 When you see this happen, you will celebrate; your strength will return faster than grass can sprout. Then everyone will know that the Lord is present with his servants, but he is angry with his enemies.
Isa66:15 The Lord will come down like a whirlwind with his flaming chariots. He will be terribly furious and punish his enemies with fire.
Isa66:16 The Lord 's fiery sword will bring justice everywhere on this earth and execute many people.
Isa66:17 Some of you get yourselves ready and go to a garden to worship a foreign goddess. You eat the meat of pigs, lizards, and mice. But I, the Lord , will destroy you for this.
Isa66:18 I know everything you do and think! The time has now come to bring together the people of every language and nation and to show them my glory
Isa66:19 by proving what I can do. I will send the survivors to Tarshish, Pul, Lud, Meshech, Tubal, Javan, and to the distant islands. I will send them to announce my wonderful glory to nations that have never heard about me.
Isa66:20 They will bring your relatives from the nations as an offering to me, the Lord . They will come on horses, chariots, wagons, mules, and camels to Jerusalem, my holy mountain. It will be like the people of Israel bringing the right offering to my temple.
Isa66:21 I promise that some of them will be priests and others will be helpers in my temple. I, the Lord , have spoken.
Isa66:22 I also promise that you will always have descendants and will never be forgotten, just as the new heavens and the new earth that I create will last forever.
Isa66:23 On the first day of each month and on each Sabbath, everyone will worship me. I, the Lord , have spoken.
Isa66:24 My people will go out and look at the dead bodies of those who turned against me. The worms there never die, the fire never stops burning, and the sight of those bodies will be disgusting to everyone.
Jer1:1 My name is Jeremiah. I am a priest, and my father Hilkiah and everyone else in my family are from Anathoth in the territory of the Benjamin tribe. This book contains the things that the Lord told me to say.
Jer1:2 The Lord first spoke to me in the thirteenth year that Josiah was king of Judah,
Jer1:3 and he continued to speak to me during the rule of Josiah's son Jehoiakim. The last time the Lord spoke to me was in the fifth month of the eleventh year that Josiah's son Zedekiah was king. That was also when the people of Jerusalem were taken away as prisoners.
Jer1:4 The Lord said:
Jer1:5 "Jeremiah, I am your Creator, and before you were born, I chose you to speak for me to the nations."
Jer1:6 I replied, "I'm not a good speaker, Lord , and I'm too young."
Jer1:7 "Don't say you're too young," the Lord answered. "If I tell you to go and speak to someone, then go! And when I tell you what to say, don't leave out a word!
Jer1:8 I promise to be with you and keep you safe, so don't be afraid."
Jer1:9 The Lord reached out his hand, then he touched my mouth and said, "I am giving you the words to say,
Jer1:10 and I am sending you with authority to speak to the nations for me. You will tell them of doom and destruction, and of rising and rebuilding again."
